WEBVTT

1
00:01:38.666 --> 00:01:41.134
<i>Since Vadim Baranov</i>
<i>stepped down as advisor</i>

2
00:01:41.168 --> 00:01:44.404
<i>to Vladimir</i>
<i>Vladimirovich Putin. the Tzar.</i>

3
00:01:44.438 --> 00:01:47.675
<i>the legends about him haven't</i>
<i>waned. they've multiplied.</i>

4
00:01:48.710 --> 00:01:52.412
<i>Most men of power get their</i>
<i>aura from the position they</i>
<i>hold.</i>

5
00:01:52.446 --> 00:01:55.248
<i>When they lose it. it's like a</i>
<i>plug has been pulled.</i>

6
00:01:56.684 --> 00:01:58.553
<i>Baranov was a different breed.</i>

7
00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:03.423
<i>Some say he retreated</i>
<i>to a monastery in Mount Athos.</i>

8
00:02:04.291 --> 00:02:08.630
<i>Others swore they saw him in</i>
<i>Ibiza. surrounded by coked-up</i>
<i>models.</i>

9
00:02:09.864 --> 00:02:13.568
<i>Still others insist they</i>
<i>spotted him on the</i>
<i>front line in Donbas.</i>

10
00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:20.708
<i>Vadim Baranov went through life</i>
<i>in a swirl of enigmas.</i>

11
00:02:20.742 --> 00:02:24.112
<i>The sole certainty</i>
<i>was his influence on the Tzar.</i>

12
00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:27.447
<i>In his fifteen years of</i>
<i>service.</i>

13
00:02:27.481 --> 00:02:31.218
<i>he contributed decisively to</i>
<i>the growth of the Tzar's power.</i>

14
00:02:32.120 --> 00:02:35.089
<i>He was known</i>
<i>as the Wizard of the Kremlin.</i>

15
00:02:35.123 --> 00:02:36.724
<i>the New Rasputin.</i>

16
00:02:39.961 --> 00:02:42.563
<i>He would show up</i>
<i>unannounced at the President's</i>
<i>office</i>

17
00:02:42.597 --> 00:02:45.667
<i>in the middle of the night</i>
<i>to handle urgent matters.</i>

18
00:02:46.968 --> 00:02:48.736
<i>Perhaps the Tzar himself</i>
<i>would call him in</i>

19
00:02:48.836 --> 00:02:50.237
<i>on his personal line.</i>

20
00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:54.441
<i>Occasionally the two of them</i>
<i>were joined by</i>

21
00:02:54.474 --> 00:02:56.443
<i>a prominent minister or the CEO</i>

22
00:02:56.476 --> 00:02:58.412
<i>of some state-owned</i>
<i>conglomerate.</i>

23
00:02:59.914 --> 00:03:02.449
<i>but these witnesses never</i>
<i>shed any light on the Tzar</i>

24
00:03:02.482 --> 00:03:04.852
<i>and his advisors' nightly</i>
<i>activities.</i>

25
00:03:09.123 --> 00:03:12.827
<i>When I returned to</i>
<i>Moscow a few years after his</i>
<i>disappearance</i>

26
00:03:12.994 --> 00:03:15.495
<i>Baranov's memory still loomed</i>
<i>large.</i>

27
00:03:16.164 --> 00:03:18.398
<i>The press persisted in</i>
<i>attributing to him</i>

28
00:03:18.432 --> 00:03:20.768
<i>the most baffling measures</i>
<i>taken by the Kremlin.</i>

29
00:03:21.936 --> 00:03:25.506
<i>As for me. I had just published</i>
<i>an essay in</i> Foreign Affairs

30
00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:27.307
<i>that created something of a</i>
<i>stir.</i>

31
00:03:28.643 --> 00:03:32.279
<i>It was called: "Vadim Baranov</i>
<i>and the Invention of Fake</i>
<i>Democracy".</i>

32
00:03:32.379 --> 00:03:34.682
Laurance Rowland.

33
00:03:38.318 --> 00:03:40.555
If you need anything. just dial
9.

34
00:03:40.655 --> 00:03:41.589
Thank you.

35
00:03:41.789 --> 00:03:44.058
-Have a good day. Mr. Rowland.
-You too.

36
00:03:48.295 --> 00:03:50.297
<i>I took a year's</i>
<i>sabbatical from Yale</i>

37
00:03:50.330 --> 00:03:53.300
<i>to write the first biography</i>
<i>of Yevgeny Zamyatin.</i>

38
00:03:53.333 --> 00:03:55.136
<i>one of Russia's great writers</i>

39
00:03:55.169 --> 00:03:58.840
<i>and an early antagonist</i>
<i>of Stalin's communist regime.</i>

40
00:04:01.408 --> 00:04:03.310
<i>I walked in the pale winter</i>
<i>light.</i>

41
00:04:03.978 --> 00:04:05.680
<i>leafed through old books.</i>

42
00:04:07.181 --> 00:04:09.584
<i>Zamyatin became my obsession.</i>

43
00:04:09.684 --> 00:04:13.221
<i>He was a visionary. and not</i>
<i>just when it came to Stalin.</i>

44
00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:15.223
<i>All subsequent dictators as</i>
<i>well.</i>

45
00:04:16.224 --> 00:04:19.961
<i>From Silicon Valley oligarchs</i>
<i>to China's one-party state.</i>

46
00:04:20.061 --> 00:04:22.362
<i>from Mark Zuckerberg to Xi</i>
<i>Jinping.</i>

47
00:04:24.732 --> 00:04:26.968
<i>His dystopian novel</i>
We

48
00:04:27.068 --> 00:04:30.104
<i>inspired George Orwell's</i> 1984 <i>.</i>

49
00:05:18.886 --> 00:05:21.454
<i>Just outside the city</i>
<i>gloomy.</i>

50
00:05:21.488 --> 00:05:24.926
<i>never-ending woods stretched</i>
<i>all the way to Siberia.</i>

51
00:05:27.161 --> 00:05:29.931
<i>I felt a mix of curiosity</i>
<i>and apprehension.</i>

52
00:05:31.265 --> 00:05:34.735
<i>In Russia. things generally go</i>
<i>pretty well.</i>

53
00:05:34.769 --> 00:05:37.872
<i>But when they go bad.</i>
<i>they go really bad.</i>

54
00:05:53.287 --> 00:05:55.923
[door opens. creaks

55
00:05:56.924 --> 00:05:58.159
Good morning.

56
00:05:58.793 --> 00:05:59.961
Good morning.

57
00:06:01.829 --> 00:06:03.531
Please follow me. Mr. Rowland.

58
00:06:05.666 --> 00:06:06.934
May I take your coat?

59
00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:12.472
I will bring you some tea. Thank
you.

60
00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:14.575
Thank you.

61
00:06:44.372 --> 00:06:46.707
I didn't know you collected old
books.

62
00:06:46.741 --> 00:06:48.843
I don't collect them. I read
them.

63
00:06:48.876 --> 00:06:50.344
There's a major difference.

64
00:06:52.079 --> 00:06:53.748
So you're a reader of Zamyatin.

65
00:06:55.349 --> 00:06:58.485
I have something to show you
that you will truly appreciate.

66
00:07:08.495 --> 00:07:09.730
Do you know what this is?

67
00:07:11.232 --> 00:07:13.701
A letter Zamyatin wrote to
Stalin.

68
00:07:13.734 --> 00:07:16.270
Asking permission
to leave the USSR.

69
00:07:17.238 --> 00:07:19.507
"Dear Iosif Vissarionovich.

70
00:07:19.607 --> 00:07:21.509
"just as the Christians created
the Devil

71
00:07:21.542 --> 00:07:24.645
"as a convenient personification
of all evil.

72
00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:26.747
"so the critics
have transformed me

73
00:07:26.781 --> 00:07:28.783
into the Devil of Soviet
literature."

74
00:07:30.251 --> 00:07:33.387
Zamyatin understood too much.
too quickly.

75
00:07:33.421 --> 00:07:35.556
and made the rash decision
to write about it.

76
00:07:39.694 --> 00:07:40.695
Please.

77
00:07:41.395 --> 00:07:42.530
have a seat.

78
00:07:45.633 --> 00:07:47.635
- You read it?
- Of course.

79
00:07:50.137 --> 00:07:52.540
You even took the
time to make notes.

80
00:07:52.573 --> 00:07:53.674
I'm honored.

81
00:07:53.774 --> 00:07:55.409
Let's not get carried away.

82
00:07:56.944 --> 00:08:00.047
However. compared to the others.
you did understand something.

83
00:08:00.147 --> 00:08:02.283
Not much. but something.

84
00:08:04.418 --> 00:08:06.420
Thank you.

85
00:08:07.455 --> 00:08:09.290
You said
you consider yourself an artist.

86
00:08:10.458 --> 00:08:12.293
Let's just say I played
a supporting role.

87
00:08:12.326 --> 00:08:13.461
I'm retired now.

88
00:08:14.228 --> 00:08:15.529
You don't miss the adrenaline?

89
00:08:15.563 --> 00:08:17.298
Trust me. there is no greater
joy

90
00:08:17.331 --> 00:08:19.033
than waking up every morning.

91
00:08:19.066 --> 00:08:21.669
having coffee and taking
your daughter to school.

92
00:08:22.970 --> 00:08:24.472
How did the others take it?

93
00:08:24.572 --> 00:08:25.439
My leaving?

94
00:08:25.473 --> 00:08:27.208
Badly. of course.

95
00:08:27.975 --> 00:08:31.712
Courtiers forgive everyone:
thieves. murderers. traitors.

96
00:08:31.746 --> 00:08:32.980
But not deserters.

97
00:08:33.681 --> 00:08:36.717
"What? You don't want
what we're willing to kill for?"

98
00:08:36.817 --> 00:08:37.818
And the Tzar?

99
00:08:38.853 --> 00:08:40.454
The Tzar is a different story.

100
00:08:43.691 --> 00:08:46.594
My father feared this library.

101
00:08:47.962 --> 00:08:49.730
It belonged to my grandfather.

102
00:08:49.764 --> 00:08:51.732
Custine. Gracián.

103
00:08:51.766 --> 00:08:52.967
Machiavelli...

104
00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.369
The skeptics. the disillusioned.

105
00:08:55.469 --> 00:08:57.471
Hardly the Soviet doxa.

106
00:08:57.506 --> 00:09:00.374
But to his credit. he never
tried to deny me any of them.

107
00:09:00.474 --> 00:09:01.675
Your father?

108
00:09:01.709 --> 00:09:03.878
He ended up director of the
Academy of Social Sciences

109
00:09:03.978 --> 00:09:05.346
for the Communist Party.

110
00:09:05.379 --> 00:09:07.314
His one goal in life was to
avoid

111
00:09:07.348 --> 00:09:11.185
being awakened at dawn by the
KGB banging on his front door.

112
00:09:11.218 --> 00:09:13.888
In his position. he shouldn't
have had to worry about that.

113
00:09:13.988 --> 00:09:16.357
No one was safe in the Soviet
Union.

114
00:09:17.358 --> 00:09:20.027
No one is safe in Russia.
period.

115
00:09:20.127 --> 00:09:21.530
Not me.

116
00:09:21.629 --> 00:09:22.730
Not even you.

117
00:09:26.067 --> 00:09:29.203
<i>When I was growing up.</i>
<i>the most sought after privilege</i>
<i>in Moscow</i>

118
00:09:29.236 --> 00:09:30.671
<i>was the Kremlyovka.</i>

119
00:09:30.704 --> 00:09:33.908
<i>a food basket reserved for the</i>
<i>Communist Party's senior</i>
<i>officials.</i>

120
00:09:34.008 --> 00:09:35.643
What are we eating today?

121
00:09:35.743 --> 00:09:37.244
Salmon piroshki.

122
00:09:38.479 --> 00:09:39.980
lamb cutlets...

123
00:09:40.347 --> 00:09:43.717
<i>Ultimately. my problem</i>
<i>is that I had a happy</i>
<i>childhood.</i>

124
00:09:43.751 --> 00:09:46.287
<i>And in Russia. that's not</i>
<i>normal.</i>

125
00:09:46.387 --> 00:09:48.889
All the Russian elite
experienced Soviet poverty

126
00:09:48.923 --> 00:09:52.426
before they gained access
to villas on the Côte d'Azur.

127
00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:54.261
They still haven't gotten over
it.

128
00:09:55.062 --> 00:09:56.163
<i>Even the Tzar:</i>

129
00:09:56.697 --> 00:09:59.400
<i>"Me. the kid who grew up</i>
<i>in a shoddy kommunalka</i>

130
00:09:59.433 --> 00:10:01.669
<i>"in a gloomy courtyard</i>
<i>in Saint Petersburg.</i>

131
00:10:01.702 --> 00:10:04.539
<i>"Now I'm invited to Buckingham</i>
<i>Palace!"</i>

132
00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:08.676
-Things have changed.
-Not that much.

133
00:10:08.709 --> 00:10:11.178
For you Westerners. money is
essential.

134
00:10:11.212 --> 00:10:13.881
What matters in Russia
is your proximity to power.

135
00:10:13.914 --> 00:10:17.051
The Soviet system was based
on privilege. not cash.

136
00:10:17.785 --> 00:10:21.322
Yesterday there wasn't any.
Tomorrow. who knows. so...

137
00:10:21.355 --> 00:10:23.057
you might as well just blow it
all.

138
00:10:24.859 --> 00:10:26.694
Do you know what a <i>vertushka</i> is?

139
00:10:26.794 --> 00:10:28.929
It was a telephone without a
dial

140
00:10:28.963 --> 00:10:32.433
<i>that allowed Party leaders to</i>
<i>communicate directly with you.</i>

141
00:10:32.466 --> 00:10:34.335
Having one meant you'd made it.

142
00:10:34.435 --> 00:10:36.837
Look. This is a vertushka.

143
00:10:36.937 --> 00:10:39.106
Gray. like everything Soviet.

144
00:10:39.206 --> 00:10:41.543
You think Moscow's gray.
try Washington.

145
00:10:41.576 --> 00:10:44.579
God. they're not gray
there. they're dead.

146
00:10:44.613 --> 00:10:48.082
Anyway. I'm banned from entering
the USA and Europe.

147
00:10:49.817 --> 00:10:51.452
-Is your father still alive?
-No.

148
00:10:51.485 --> 00:10:54.288
He might have subsisted
in this world for a long time.

149
00:10:54.321 --> 00:10:57.858
But then along came Gorbachev
and his glass of milk.

150
00:10:57.892 --> 00:10:59.093
Glass of milk?

151
00:10:59.628 --> 00:11:01.695
You don't have to listen
Gorbachev to know that

152
00:11:01.729 --> 00:11:03.430
he was about to destroy
the Soviet Union.

153
00:11:03.464 --> 00:11:05.466
It was enough to look at him.

154
00:11:05.499 --> 00:11:08.736
<i>He took to the rostrum.</i>
<i>they handed him a glass of</i>
<i>milk.</i>

155
00:11:08.836 --> 00:11:11.739
<i>And he proceeded</i>
<i>to double the price of vodka.</i>

156
00:11:11.839 --> 00:11:14.509
<i>And try to get everyone on</i>
<i>milk.</i>

157
00:11:14.609 --> 00:11:15.610
<i>In Russia!</i>

158
00:11:15.644 --> 00:11:16.877
<i>Can you imagine?</i>

159
00:11:18.846 --> 00:11:21.115
No wonder everything
spun out of control.

160
00:11:23.117 --> 00:11:26.153
That was it for communism
and for my father.

161
00:11:26.253 --> 00:11:28.088
He lost everything.

162
00:11:28.122 --> 00:11:31.158
His job. privileges. reputation.

163
00:11:31.258 --> 00:11:33.260
What about you?
What did you do in those times?

164
00:11:34.128 --> 00:11:36.830
<i>My father</i>
<i>wanted me to be a diplomat.</i>

165
00:11:36.864 --> 00:11:39.033
<i>But I was never keen on</i>
<i>studying.</i>

166
00:11:39.133 --> 00:11:40.234
<i>I did odd jobs.</i>

167
00:11:40.267 --> 00:11:43.837
<i>Found television sets. cassette</i>
<i>decks. and resold them.</i>

168
00:11:43.871 --> 00:11:45.139
<i>Business was good.</i>

169
00:11:46.774 --> 00:11:48.776
<i>I started to make more</i>
<i>money than my father.</i>

170
00:11:48.876 --> 00:11:50.311
<i>A lot more than my father.</i>

171
00:11:51.312 --> 00:11:53.113
<i>I was just a know-nothing kid.</i>

172
00:11:53.147 --> 00:11:55.916
<i>That's why I was better suited</i>
<i>to the new world.</i>

173
00:11:59.453 --> 00:12:01.155
<i>In the early '90s.</i>

174
00:12:01.188 --> 00:12:02.990
<i>Moscow was a dynamic city.</i>

175
00:12:03.023 --> 00:12:06.927
<i>The place was filled with hope</i>
<i>for a few years. Just a few.</i>

176
00:12:06.961 --> 00:12:09.296
<i>Banned books</i>
<i>were coming out every week.</i>

177
00:12:09.396 --> 00:12:12.266
<i>Solzhenitsyn. Pasternak.</i>
<i>Bulgakov...</i>

178
00:12:12.299 --> 00:12:15.869
<i>Art magazines and literary</i>
<i>revues were selling in the</i>
<i>millions.</i>

179
00:12:15.903 --> 00:12:18.839
<i>The Russian appetite for</i>
<i>freedom was insatiable.</i>

180
00:12:21.408 --> 00:12:23.444
<i>So I enrolled in</i>
<i>the Russian Institute</i>

181
00:12:23.477 --> 00:12:25.379
<i>of Theater Arts in Moscow</i>

182
00:12:25.412 --> 00:12:28.683
<i>and began living the messy life</i>
<i>of a thespian.</i>

183
00:12:37.324 --> 00:12:39.793
<i>We were barely 20</i>
<i>and a whole new world</i>

184
00:12:39.827 --> 00:12:41.095
<i>had opened up to us</i>

185
00:12:41.128 --> 00:12:43.964
<i>just as we were finally strong</i>
<i>enough to conquer it.</i>

186
00:13:02.717 --> 00:13:03.718
Hey!

187
00:13:05.019 --> 00:13:06.287
Open the door!

188
00:13:06.387 --> 00:13:09.256
Open this fucking door or I'll
bust you up!

189
00:13:18.966 --> 00:13:21.969
♪ Hush... Comrade ♪

190
00:13:22.303 --> 00:13:25.339
♪ Chaos. Despair. Dread. ♪

191
00:13:25.707 --> 00:13:28.710
♪ That's you in my head. ♪

192
00:13:29.109 --> 00:13:32.079
♪ Chaos. Despair. Dread. ♪

193
00:13:32.112 --> 00:13:35.849
♪ That's you in my head. ♪

194
00:13:35.883 --> 00:13:38.886
♪ Unshook unfelt in the snow. ♪

195
00:13:38.919 --> 00:13:42.323
♪ No they will never know. ♪

196
00:13:42.724 --> 00:13:45.694
♪ Hush little Comrade
You're a train wreck. ♪

197
00:13:45.727 --> 00:13:49.229
♪ Seriously shut it tie your
tongue around your neck. ♪

198
00:13:51.131 --> 00:13:54.569
♪ Unshook unfelt in the snow. ♪

199
00:13:54.602 --> 00:13:57.806
♪ No they will never know. ♪

200
00:13:58.072 --> 00:14:01.075
♪ You can't know what I mean ♪

201
00:14:01.475 --> 00:14:07.716
♪ when I say
Odin Odin Odin. ♪

202
00:14:07.749 --> 00:14:11.251
♪ Little Comrade. ♪

203
00:14:11.285 --> 00:14:14.656
♪ Little Comrade. ♪

204
00:14:15.657 --> 00:14:17.257
You! Fuck off!

205
00:14:20.294 --> 00:14:21.663
Bitch! Fuck you!

206
00:14:23.464 --> 00:14:26.033
Oh. Come here.

207
00:14:30.471 --> 00:14:31.539
Perfect.

208
00:14:34.542 --> 00:14:35.710
You really impressed me.

209
00:14:37.679 --> 00:14:38.713
Yeah?

210
00:14:38.813 --> 00:14:41.448
I had to tell you
because it doesn't happen often.

211
00:14:41.549 --> 00:14:42.950
Okay. well...

212
00:14:44.451 --> 00:14:46.788
That's interesting. um...

213
00:14:46.821 --> 00:14:48.690
Guess you must be pretty
important.

214
00:14:48.723 --> 00:14:50.625
-What exactly impressed you?
-You.

215
00:14:51.559 --> 00:14:52.861
Your performance.

216
00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:54.094
What performance?

217
00:14:54.128 --> 00:14:56.096
Well. wasn't that you singing?

218
00:14:56.130 --> 00:14:57.965
You call that singing?

219
00:14:58.065 --> 00:14:59.601
Oh. what do you call it?

220
00:14:59.634 --> 00:15:01.168
Trendy... bullshit?

221
00:15:02.169 --> 00:15:05.005
-I did that as a favor.
-For who?

222
00:15:05.973 --> 00:15:08.108
The KGB agents watching us.

223
00:15:08.208 --> 00:15:09.376
Ah.

224
00:15:09.476 --> 00:15:10.978
And I'm happy to give them
something

225
00:15:11.078 --> 00:15:12.747
to spice up their reports.

226
00:15:14.481 --> 00:15:16.116
That's a shame. you have talent.

227
00:15:16.216 --> 00:15:19.219
Because I do what New Yorkers
did 15 years ago?

228
00:15:20.254 --> 00:15:22.122
You're a real Soviet.

229
00:15:22.222 --> 00:15:25.693
You think the world's
just waiting for you.

230
00:15:25.727 --> 00:15:27.461
And you're not a real Soviet?

231
00:15:27.494 --> 00:15:31.633
Well. my parents were poor and
crazy.

232
00:15:31.733 --> 00:15:33.967
They were hippies.

233
00:15:34.001 --> 00:15:36.738
They carted me around
from commune to commune.

234
00:15:36.771 --> 00:15:38.840
Now they're old and sick

235
00:15:38.873 --> 00:15:41.208
and they don't believe
in their old values any longer.

236
00:15:41.241 --> 00:15:44.579
And I tell you one thing.
I'm not gonna end up like them.

237
00:15:44.612 --> 00:15:46.146
I'd like to talk to you about a
role.

238
00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:48.783
Would you deign to take me
seriously for a second?

239
00:15:48.883 --> 00:15:49.884
A role.

240
00:15:51.418 --> 00:15:54.087
What.

241
00:15:54.121 --> 00:15:55.989
you mean like the kind
offered to actresses?

242
00:15:56.023 --> 00:15:57.991
Yes. like the kind
offered to actresses.

243
00:15:58.025 --> 00:16:02.162
Well. unfortunately.
I'm not an actress.

244
00:16:02.262 --> 00:16:03.598
And I have no desire to be one.

245
00:16:03.631 --> 00:16:07.167
I might even say
I've done everything in my power

246
00:16:07.201 --> 00:16:09.036
not to be one.

247
00:16:09.136 --> 00:16:10.538
Do you know Yevgeny Zamyatin?

248
00:16:10.638 --> 00:16:11.573
Yeah.

249
00:16:11.840 --> 00:16:16.243
An icon of the most conventional
avant-gardists.

250
00:16:16.945 --> 00:16:18.178
I'm not into that stuff.

251
00:16:18.278 --> 00:16:20.180
With all due respect.
you're missing out.

252
00:16:20.214 --> 00:16:21.749
I'm putting on a
version of his novel

253
00:16:21.783 --> 00:16:24.552
We at the
Institute of Theater Arts.

254
00:16:24.652 --> 00:16:27.789
You take risks.
I might be warming to you a bit.

255
00:16:29.289 --> 00:16:30.658
- Do you have a car?
- Yes.

256
00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:34.294
Take me home.

257
00:16:34.328 --> 00:16:35.563
I'm done with this party.

258
00:16:37.565 --> 00:16:38.600
In a hurry?

259
00:16:39.801 --> 00:16:41.335
What? Too fast for you?

260
00:16:45.072 --> 00:16:48.442
<i>I don't know how I</i>
<i>managed to make contact with</i>
<i>Planet Ksenia.</i>

261
00:16:48.475 --> 00:16:52.145
<i>but I knew immediately that</i>
<i>even if I lived a thousand</i>
<i>years.</i>

262
00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:54.448
<i>I'd never meet anyone else like</i>
<i>her.</i>

263
00:16:54.481 --> 00:16:56.416
Alright. everyone. We're going
to take it again from the top.

264
00:16:56.450 --> 00:16:57.585
Places. please.

265
00:16:57.619 --> 00:17:00.487
Scissors. D-503. places. Let's
go!

266
00:17:00.588 --> 00:17:01.956
Which scene should
we start with?

267
00:17:02.122 --> 00:17:04.659
The scene we've been doing all
night. Yuri. the mirror scene.

268
00:17:04.692 --> 00:17:06.728
And should I sit down or lie
down?

269
00:17:06.761 --> 00:17:08.095
You should be lying and then

270
00:17:08.128 --> 00:17:10.598
when you feel the lights from
the Integral. you may sit up.

271
00:17:10.698 --> 00:17:13.935
Alright. it's all in the
repetition.

272
00:17:13.968 --> 00:17:15.737
This was excellent. thank you
ladies.

273
00:17:15.837 --> 00:17:17.672
The dinner scene was far too
casual.

274
00:17:17.705 --> 00:17:19.306
I need something more
mechanical.

275
00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:21.809
- Is the Integral ready?
- Ready!

276
00:17:21.843 --> 00:17:24.244
Alright. keep your actions going

277
00:17:24.278 --> 00:17:26.380
until you feel the lights
from the Integral.

278
00:17:26.480 --> 00:17:30.083
at which point you all stand up
and walk towards the windows.

279
00:17:30.117 --> 00:17:32.520
Milana. ready?

280
00:17:32.620 --> 00:17:33.521
Yes!

281
00:17:39.861 --> 00:17:41.495
My brothers.

282
00:17:41.529 --> 00:17:44.699
as you all know.
down below in the city

283
00:17:44.732 --> 00:17:46.500
they're building
the Integral Spaceship.

284
00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:55.510
Down with the
Integral! Down with it!

285
00:17:56.678 --> 00:17:57.679
My brothers.

286
00:17:58.746 --> 00:18:02.149
the Integral must be ours.

287
00:18:03.518 --> 00:18:05.553
And she will be ours.

288
00:18:07.021 --> 00:18:10.390
When she rises skywards
for the first time.

289
00:18:10.424 --> 00:18:13.393
we will be the ones aboard.

290
00:18:15.395 --> 00:18:19.433
For we have with us
the builder of the Integral.

291
00:18:20.668 --> 00:18:23.403
He left the city
and came here with me.

292
00:18:24.906 --> 00:18:26.306
To be with you.

293
00:18:26.340 --> 00:18:28.275
Long live the
Builder!

294
00:18:47.562 --> 00:18:49.697
Her ambitions may have been
vague. but...

295
00:18:50.430 --> 00:18:53.067
In any case Muscovite
avant-garde theater had little
chance

296
00:18:53.101 --> 00:18:54.401
of satisfying them.

297
00:18:54.434 --> 00:18:57.038
I know. I lived in Moscow
during those years.

298
00:18:57.071 --> 00:18:58.606
There were no limits.

299
00:18:58.706 --> 00:19:01.843
Everything was collapsing
and being rebuilt at once.

300
00:19:01.943 --> 00:19:06.114
It was a fascinating and
terrifying time.

301
00:19:06.213 --> 00:19:08.281
Ksenia and I lived in our
artistic bubble

302
00:19:08.315 --> 00:19:11.418
while life outside
was rife with possibilities.

303
00:19:11.451 --> 00:19:12.553
Nearly every day.

304
00:19:12.587 --> 00:19:14.856
some former classmate
would come to me with an idea.

305
00:19:14.889 --> 00:19:16.490
a business proposition.

306
00:19:16.591 --> 00:19:18.860
First on his grandfather's
bicycle.

307
00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:22.229
then in an armored Bentley.
surrounded by bodyguards.

308
00:19:23.731 --> 00:19:26.100
That's pretty much
how it happened for Dmitry.

309
00:19:26.134 --> 00:19:27.969
-Sidorov?
-Sidorov. yes.

310
00:19:28.002 --> 00:19:29.336
Dmitry Sidorov.

311
00:19:30.605 --> 00:19:32.106
<i>I'd known him in high school.</i>

312
00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:35.109
<i>Now he was head of the Young</i>
<i>Communist League at the</i>
<i>university.</i>

313
00:19:35.143 --> 00:19:37.244
<i>Don't think he was a Party</i>
<i>apparatchik.</i>

314
00:19:37.344 --> 00:19:39.647
<i>In the late '80s</i>
<i>the student cooperative</i>

315
00:19:39.747 --> 00:19:41.849
<i>was the incubator for Russian</i>
<i>capitalism.</i>

316
00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:45.318
<i>I liked hearing about his</i>
<i>adventures.</i>

317
00:19:45.352 --> 00:19:48.656
<i>I wanted to write a play</i>
<i>about entrepreneurs like him.</i>

318
00:19:48.756 --> 00:19:50.124
You seen Dmitry?

319
00:19:50.158 --> 00:19:52.760
Saw him 5 minutes ago.
Check the bar.

320
00:19:52.794 --> 00:19:56.764
<i>They were a new social</i>
<i>class. emerging out of nowhere</i>
<i>in a matter of months.</i>

321
00:19:56.864 --> 00:19:57.932
<i>It was pretty remarkable.</i>

322
00:19:59.266 --> 00:20:00.267
Vadya!

323
00:20:02.036 --> 00:20:03.403
Good to see you.

324
00:20:03.437 --> 00:20:05.173
Listen.
this café was my first business

325
00:20:05.205 --> 00:20:07.975
but obviously I used it as a
launching pad for more lucrative
endeavors.

326
00:20:08.009 --> 00:20:09.777
Not all of which were legal.

327
00:20:09.811 --> 00:20:12.146
Vadya! There is no more
legality. that's over forget it.

328
00:20:12.180 --> 00:20:13.246
Let me tell you a story.

329
00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:15.750
No writing. close your eyes.
Pretend I'm your Mama.

330
00:20:15.783 --> 00:20:18.786
Once upon a time. I come across
a supply of cognac.

331
00:20:18.886 --> 00:20:19.887
You mean fake cognac.

332
00:20:19.921 --> 00:20:21.622
Fake. real who cares?
It's not the point.

333
00:20:21.656 --> 00:20:23.524
I put it on the market for $50 a
bottle.

334
00:20:24.525 --> 00:20:25.526
You hear that?

335
00:20:27.795 --> 00:20:29.697
Nothing.
No one wants it.

336
00:20:29.797 --> 00:20:32.667
I mark it up to $500.
they're fucking fighting for it!

337
00:20:33.201 --> 00:20:35.169
I'm sure you didn't stop at
cognac.

338
00:20:35.203 --> 00:20:37.772
Computers. acid-wash jeans.
tourist trinkets. software

339
00:20:37.805 --> 00:20:39.272
all of it thanks to the Student
Cooperative.

340
00:20:39.306 --> 00:20:43.077
A few minor cons.
I struggle to believe you.

341
00:20:43.177 --> 00:20:44.779
Can't fool you!

342
00:20:44.812 --> 00:20:47.447
These are some stories to make
you laugh. To make your audience
laugh. It's a play!

343
00:20:47.481 --> 00:20:49.316
It's a play!

344
00:20:49.416 --> 00:20:50.785
An actual fact that
I came up with a scheme

345
00:20:50.818 --> 00:20:53.554
to facilitate the flow of
payments between state-run
businesses.

346
00:20:53.588 --> 00:20:55.890
In a nutshell. I borrow money
and lend it to others for a fee.

347
00:20:55.923 --> 00:20:58.059
Basically what is known as a
bank. but...

348
00:20:59.827 --> 00:21:01.829
no one in this country knows
what a bank is.

349
00:21:05.365 --> 00:21:07.802
Tough questions!

350
00:21:12.372 --> 00:21:13.406
Yes. you could say that

351
00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:15.710
and since I created Russia's
first commercial bank.

352
00:21:15.743 --> 00:21:17.578
I'll tell you how I did it.
I found a book:

353
00:21:17.612 --> 00:21:21.414
<i>Commercial Banks of Capitalist</i>
<i>Countries.</i>

354
00:21:21.448 --> 00:21:22.850
Remarkable work!

355
00:21:22.884 --> 00:21:24.986
It explains simply and in great
detail

356
00:21:25.086 --> 00:21:26.521
how the banking system works.

357
00:21:26.621 --> 00:21:28.589
And I said. hey. I like this.

358
00:21:30.758 --> 00:21:33.493
Would you describe yourself as
greedy?

359
00:21:33.528 --> 00:21:35.495
Absolutely. Yes. absolutely.

360
00:21:35.530 --> 00:21:37.765
I didn't use to be. but I grow
greedier. now. by the day.

361
00:21:37.865 --> 00:21:39.366
It's an asset in my line of
work.

362
00:21:39.466 --> 00:21:40.868
I have a banker's personality.

363
00:21:40.968 --> 00:21:42.570
I love money.

364
00:21:44.772 --> 00:21:46.373
-Nice suit.
-Nice shirt.

365
00:21:49.376 --> 00:21:50.645
Good read.

366
00:21:50.745 --> 00:21:53.514
A bit behind the times.
you still had your moustache.

367
00:21:53.548 --> 00:21:55.783
Journalists are always behind
the times. I don't need to tell
you. Vadya.

368
00:21:57.251 --> 00:21:58.385
Bloody hick mustache.

369
00:21:58.418 --> 00:22:00.087
You did well to shave it off.

370
00:22:00.121 --> 00:22:01.956
How's the play coming along?

371
00:22:01.989 --> 00:22:04.525
-Um. my play about you?
-Yes.

372
00:22:04.559 --> 00:22:06.459
-I won't write it.
-Why?

373
00:22:06.493 --> 00:22:07.795
Because it's over now.

374
00:22:07.895 --> 00:22:09.396
You can't tell me the truth
anymore.

375
00:22:11.299 --> 00:22:12.266
You're right.

376
00:22:13.901 --> 00:22:15.536
But you know I never could tell
you the whole truth.

377
00:22:15.636 --> 00:22:18.639
No. but you used to tell me a
bit more.

378
00:22:25.580 --> 00:22:26.581
Thank you.

379
00:22:34.021 --> 00:22:36.924
So. this is the famous Dmitry?

380
00:22:37.024 --> 00:22:37.925
I see no other.

381
00:22:39.026 --> 00:22:41.762
Vadim says you're worth
80 million rubles a year.

382
00:22:41.796 --> 00:22:43.931
-Is that true?
-Could be. I don't know.

383
00:22:44.031 --> 00:22:45.266
He also says you're a thug.

384
00:22:46.934 --> 00:22:47.802
Is that so?

385
00:22:47.835 --> 00:22:49.436
There's nothing wrong with that.

386
00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:54.175
Uh...

387
00:22:54.208 --> 00:22:55.442
Ulysse Nardin.

388
00:22:56.811 --> 00:22:58.846
A bit too flashy to be elegant.

389
00:22:58.946 --> 00:23:00.815
- Don't you think?
- Flashy?

390
00:23:00.848 --> 00:23:03.184
Says the girl
with a fucking bear on her head!

391
00:23:03.217 --> 00:23:05.853
In the world I move in. it's
better to be flashy than
elegant.

392
00:23:05.953 --> 00:23:06.988
You get more respect.

393
00:23:08.689 --> 00:23:10.591
That explains your dreadful tie.

394
00:23:10.625 --> 00:23:13.460
Eugenio Marinelli from Naples.
va bene!

395
00:23:13.493 --> 00:23:15.462
Bellissima cravata.

396
00:23:15.495 --> 00:23:16.797
Never heard of it.

397
00:23:16.831 --> 00:23:18.966
Of course you haven't. one tiny
boutique.

398
00:23:19.066 --> 00:23:21.302
He travels the world
to make ties to measure.

399
00:23:21.335 --> 00:23:23.037
They make ties to measure?

400
00:23:23.070 --> 00:23:24.572
In the world I move in. they
can.

401
00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:27.742
You like champagne?
Too flashy for you?

402
00:23:29.877 --> 00:23:32.113
<i>I should have known</i>
<i>from that very first encounter</i>

403
00:23:32.146 --> 00:23:33.714
<i>that my fate was sealed.</i>

404
00:23:33.748 --> 00:23:35.883
<i>Ksenia would choose Dmitry.</i>

405
00:23:35.983 --> 00:23:38.686
<i>his vulgarity. his energy.</i>

406
00:23:38.719 --> 00:23:40.655
<i>He felt it immediately.</i>

407
00:23:40.755 --> 00:23:42.356
<i>And so did I.</i>

408
00:23:42.390 --> 00:23:44.759
<i>But for a long time</i>
<i>I refused to believe it.</i>

409
00:23:49.730 --> 00:23:50.865
Yes?

410
00:23:50.898 --> 00:23:52.499
Coming. coming. coming.

411
00:23:54.402 --> 00:23:55.736
-Bad time?
-Dmitry?

412
00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:56.737
I wanted to surprise you.

413
00:23:56.771 --> 00:23:57.571
Come. come. come. come. come.

414
00:23:57.605 --> 00:23:58.438
come. come. come. come. come..

415
00:23:58.471 --> 00:24:00.341
Let's go. let's go!
Are you hungry?

416
00:24:00.374 --> 00:24:02.510
- I have some flashy things!
- Yes!

417
00:24:02.610 --> 00:24:03.844
Caviar!

418
00:24:03.878 --> 00:24:07.348
Vadya! Maybe you put
me in a play I show you. okay?

419
00:24:07.381 --> 00:24:08.749
<i>From that moment on.</i>

420
00:24:08.783 --> 00:24:12.019
<i>Dmitry became a frequent</i>
<i>visitor to our house.</i>

421
00:24:12.119 --> 00:24:15.022
<i>There I was. thinking he came</i>
<i>out of some deep-rooted respect</i>

422
00:24:15.056 --> 00:24:18.259
<i>for the art Ksenia and I had</i>
<i>chosen to dedicate our lives</i>
<i>to.</i>

423
00:24:18.793 --> 00:24:20.761
<i>As if culture still</i>
<i>had the power to exert</i>

424
00:24:20.795 --> 00:24:22.596
<i>any influence over the real</i>
<i>world.</i>

425
00:24:22.630 --> 00:24:24.365
Oh. man. I love that sound!

426
00:24:29.036 --> 00:24:30.671
<i>The sleek.</i>
<i>shiny world of money</i>

427
00:24:30.705 --> 00:24:32.907
<i>was Dmitry's natural habitat.</i>

428
00:24:32.940 --> 00:24:34.775
<i>Nothing could</i>
<i>turn him away from it.</i>

429
00:24:36.911 --> 00:24:38.179
<i>But he wanted Ksenia.</i>

430
00:24:38.212 --> 00:24:40.247
<i>so he was willing</i>
<i>to spend a little time with us</i>

431
00:24:40.281 --> 00:24:42.216
<i>in the ruins of the city of the</i>
<i>dead.</i>

432
00:24:43.050 --> 00:24:44.952
Ksenia. go. go. go.

433
00:24:45.052 --> 00:24:46.721
<i>As the months passed.</i>

434
00:24:46.754 --> 00:24:51.425
<i>Ksenia became increasingly</i>
<i>receptive to his largess.</i>

435
00:24:51.459 --> 00:24:54.195
<i>Everything that initially</i>
<i>defined our friendship.</i>

436
00:24:54.228 --> 00:24:57.565
<i>books we shared. concerts.</i>
<i>the all-night discussions.</i>

437
00:24:57.598 --> 00:24:58.899
<i>had fallen by the wayside</i>

438
00:24:58.933 --> 00:25:01.802
<i>in favor of more</i>
<i>money-centric activities.</i>

439
00:25:01.836 --> 00:25:04.271
<i>Gallery and discotheque</i>
<i>openings.</i>

440
00:25:04.305 --> 00:25:06.974
<i>dinners at White Sun or</i>
<i>Ermitazh.</i>

441
00:25:07.074 --> 00:25:10.578
<i>Ksenia was getting higher</i>
<i>by the minute</i>
<i>on Dmitry's lifestyle.</i>

442
00:25:10.611 --> 00:25:12.646
Vadya's dancing!

443
00:25:28.329 --> 00:25:30.231
Vadya! Smile!

444
00:25:30.264 --> 00:25:31.565
I'm smiling!

445
00:25:31.599 --> 00:25:32.833
Communism is dead.

446
00:25:32.867 --> 00:25:34.668
There's a whole new world to
invent.

447
00:25:34.702 --> 00:25:36.470
You're gonna be a part of it.

448
00:25:45.646 --> 00:25:48.983
You know Vadya.
he doesn't like to go out.

449
00:25:49.016 --> 00:25:51.520
What he likes is going home.

450
00:25:57.858 --> 00:25:58.893
Yes!

451
00:26:12.039 --> 00:26:15.409
<i>I remember waking up one</i>
<i>night and gazing at her for a</i>
<i>long time.</i>

452
00:26:16.310 --> 00:26:17.278
<i>I felt so tired.</i>

453
00:26:17.378 --> 00:26:19.880
<i>even though I hadn't</i>
<i>accomplished anything yet.</i>

454
00:26:19.914 --> 00:26:21.649
<i>I nurtured the illusion that</i>

455
00:26:21.749 --> 00:26:24.285
<i>Ksenia would perceive my</i>
<i>greatness.</i>

456
00:26:24.318 --> 00:26:26.120
<i>But as the days passed.</i>

457
00:26:26.153 --> 00:26:29.223
<i>I noticed that the way she saw</i>
<i>me was changing.</i>

458
00:26:29.256 --> 00:26:32.827
<i>What began as a vague look of</i>
<i>irony was morphing into</i>
<i>contempt.</i>

459
00:26:33.394 --> 00:26:36.497
<i>"You're stronger than I am</i>
<i>because you don't love me."</i>

460
00:26:36.531 --> 00:26:37.832
<i>I wanted to tell her.</i>

461
00:26:39.433 --> 00:26:41.669
<i>My pain only augmented her</i>
<i>boredom.</i>

462
00:26:48.175 --> 00:26:49.677
Stop the car.

463
00:26:49.777 --> 00:26:51.045
Stop the car!

464
00:26:52.446 --> 00:26:54.181
Stop the fucking car!

465
00:27:04.859 --> 00:27:06.660
Yeah. you want some water?

466
00:27:12.199 --> 00:27:13.300
There you go.

467
00:27:23.444 --> 00:27:26.413
Dmitry. I've told you 10
times you drive too rough!

468
00:27:26.447 --> 00:27:27.715
I know no other way.

469
00:27:27.815 --> 00:27:29.717
Let Vadim take the wheel
or I hitchhike home.

470
00:27:31.586 --> 00:27:34.088
Do you wanna. like.
go in the back. or...

471
00:27:34.121 --> 00:27:35.489
That's sweet of you. honey.

472
00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:37.491
but I get even sicker in the
back.

473
00:28:24.639 --> 00:28:26.907
There's something I forgot to
tell you.

474
00:28:27.007 --> 00:28:28.008
I'm listening.

475
00:28:29.644 --> 00:28:30.645
I'm leaving.

476
00:28:35.783 --> 00:28:37.686
Is that all you can muster?

477
00:28:37.785 --> 00:28:39.486
You saw me in the car with
Dmitry.

478
00:28:39.521 --> 00:28:40.788
Do you think I missed that?

479
00:28:44.058 --> 00:28:45.627
It's been over between us for a
long time.

480
00:28:57.905 --> 00:28:59.306
Come in.

481
00:28:59.340 --> 00:29:01.041
You're not disturbing me.

482
00:29:01.075 --> 00:29:02.810
I was afraid to wake you.

483
00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:03.978
Have a seat.

484
00:29:07.047 --> 00:29:10.818
Finally I have an excuse
to stay in bed all day.

485
00:29:10.918 --> 00:29:13.220
Rereading the classics and
dozing.

486
00:29:13.320 --> 00:29:14.321
That suits me.

487
00:29:14.355 --> 00:29:16.056
There's the illness.

488
00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:17.324
This may surprise you.

489
00:29:17.424 --> 00:29:20.060
but illness is not necessarily
a serious thing.

490
00:29:21.061 --> 00:29:22.796
Serious things.

491
00:29:22.830 --> 00:29:24.599
like effort and work.

492
00:29:24.699 --> 00:29:27.234
are the burden of people in good
health.

493
00:29:27.334 --> 00:29:29.571
Those who are dying
have nothing more to do.

494
00:29:29.604 --> 00:29:31.740
They can just enjoy their days.

495
00:29:46.453 --> 00:29:48.355
I left Ksenia.

496
00:29:49.957 --> 00:29:50.958
I know.

497
00:29:52.393 --> 00:29:54.962
You'll have a dozen
opportunities to start over.

498
00:29:56.363 --> 00:29:59.099
I expected to suffer terribly.
but...

499
00:30:00.134 --> 00:30:03.003
I feel lighter. and strong.

500
00:30:03.103 --> 00:30:03.904
You see.

501
00:30:04.138 --> 00:30:06.807
But theater is no longer enough
for me.

502
00:30:08.042 --> 00:30:10.878
Losing Ksenia has made me
ambitious.

503
00:30:10.911 --> 00:30:12.046
Ambitious now?

504
00:30:13.615 --> 00:30:15.182
That's unexpected.

505
00:30:15.883 --> 00:30:18.252
But all the better.
I'll take it as good news.

506
00:30:18.285 --> 00:30:21.589
I cannot bear the writer's
failure to affect reality.

507
00:30:21.623 --> 00:30:24.358
I want to be part of my times.

508
00:30:24.391 --> 00:30:26.393
not just a witness.

509
00:30:26.427 --> 00:30:27.428
You know what?

510
00:30:29.263 --> 00:30:30.565
I'll leave your times to you.

511
00:30:31.633 --> 00:30:32.767
With no regrets.

512
00:30:37.404 --> 00:30:38.773
This is Sputnik.

513
00:30:38.807 --> 00:30:41.041
The only one allowed inside.

514
00:30:41.141 --> 00:30:43.310
Come here. Sputy. say hi.

515
00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:44.646
My daughter loves him.

516
00:30:46.146 --> 00:30:49.149
In the end. my father had an
attack and died very suddenly.

517
00:30:50.585 --> 00:30:53.921
The ceremony wasn't exactly
headline news.

518
00:30:55.322 --> 00:30:58.125
Four poor souls followed the
hearse in a beat-up car

519
00:30:58.158 --> 00:31:01.696
while the shiny SUVs of the
nouveaux riches sped past them.

520
00:31:01.796 --> 00:31:03.263
He died too late.

521
00:31:03.297 --> 00:31:05.933
He probably would have wanted
a nicer funeral.

522
00:31:06.835 --> 00:31:08.703
But in the end
he didn't give a damn.

523
00:31:08.803 --> 00:31:11.105
At least. I hope he didn't.

524
00:31:18.946 --> 00:31:20.948
<i>I needed to get my mind</i>
<i>off things.</i>

525
00:31:21.048 --> 00:31:24.218
<i>and Moscow in the mid-'90s was</i>
<i>the perfect place to do that.</i>

526
00:31:25.219 --> 00:31:28.188
<i>Imagine all those young men</i>
<i>and women suddenly seeing</i>

527
00:31:28.222 --> 00:31:31.358
<i>a new world of possibility</i>
<i>opening up before them.</i>

528
00:31:31.458 --> 00:31:33.293
<i>They could become</i>
<i>whatever they wanted.</i>

529
00:31:33.327 --> 00:31:35.929
<i>amass fortunes.</i>
<i>travel the world.</i>

530
00:31:35.963 --> 00:31:37.732
<i>It was enough to make your head</i>
<i>spin.</i>

531
00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:40.934
<i>It was a time of incredible</i>
<i>violence.</i>

532
00:31:40.968 --> 00:31:44.371
<i>There was gunfire everywhere.</i>
<i>for the most frivolous reasons.</i>

533
00:31:44.471 --> 00:31:47.542
<i>Men of no importance were</i>
<i>escorted by private militia</i>

534
00:31:47.575 --> 00:31:50.043
<i>until the day they were blown</i>
<i>sky-high.</i>

535
00:31:54.348 --> 00:31:55.983
<i>Turning my theater</i>
<i>experience</i>

536
00:31:56.083 --> 00:31:57.719
<i>into a career as a TV producer</i>

537
00:31:57.752 --> 00:32:00.454
<i>was like going from a horse and</i>
<i>cart to a Lamborghini.</i>

538
00:32:01.556 --> 00:32:03.123
<i>One day I was in a</i>
<i>kitchen</i>

539
00:32:03.223 --> 00:32:06.628
<i>rhapsodizing about Mayakovsky</i>
<i>and drinking hot tea.</i>

540
00:32:06.661 --> 00:32:08.128
<i>The next. I was nursing a latte</i>

541
00:32:08.228 --> 00:32:11.365
<i>in an open space</i>
<i>designed by Dutch architects.</i>

542
00:32:12.232 --> 00:32:14.836
Forget Channel One. forget state
TV.

543
00:32:14.869 --> 00:32:17.337
We're a private company.
Times have changed.

544
00:32:17.371 --> 00:32:19.741
We're going to do game shows
and politics.

545
00:32:19.774 --> 00:32:20.909
But different.

546
00:32:21.008 --> 00:32:23.410
The Soviets tried to
smother this country

547
00:32:23.511 --> 00:32:25.078
under a lid of boredom.

548
00:32:25.112 --> 00:32:28.015
The first rule. don't be boring.

549
00:32:29.416 --> 00:32:32.419
There's one project that stands
out from the others. This one.

550
00:32:33.420 --> 00:32:34.421
Do you know why?

551
00:32:34.522 --> 00:32:35.422
No.

552
00:32:36.524 --> 00:32:39.727
Because it has
all the Russian stereotypes.

553
00:32:39.761 --> 00:32:41.930
not a single one left out.

554
00:32:42.029 --> 00:32:43.531
The provincial Babushka.

555
00:32:43.631 --> 00:32:45.165
the nihilistic student.

556
00:32:45.199 --> 00:32:46.433
the ambitious slut.

557
00:32:46.534 --> 00:32:48.770
I read it. It stinks.

558
00:32:50.404 --> 00:32:51.940
I read them all. and they all
stink!

559
00:32:52.039 --> 00:32:53.240
Especially that one.

560
00:32:53.273 --> 00:32:56.009
Except that it'll work.

561
00:32:56.043 --> 00:32:58.178
Remember we're not just
producing shows.

562
00:32:58.212 --> 00:33:01.181
all the other institutions have
collapsed.

563
00:33:01.215 --> 00:33:03.050
It's now up to TV to show the
way.

564
00:33:03.150 --> 00:33:06.053
Maybe a reality show
about finishing schools that

565
00:33:06.153 --> 00:33:08.923
teach young girls to attract
freshly minted millionaires?

566
00:33:08.957 --> 00:33:11.693
Well that's not bad.
Does that genuinely exist?

567
00:33:11.726 --> 00:33:12.894
It totally exists.

568
00:33:12.927 --> 00:33:15.362
It's big and it's getting
bigger.

569
00:33:18.332 --> 00:33:20.935
My dream is to be
an international superstar.

570
00:33:23.938 --> 00:33:25.439
My dream is to buy my mom

571
00:33:25.472 --> 00:33:27.709
the most beautiful
house in Krasnoyarsk.

572
00:33:31.813 --> 00:33:34.214
My dream is to be the trophy
wife

573
00:33:34.314 --> 00:33:37.284
of the richest oligarch in
Russia

574
00:33:37.317 --> 00:33:40.287
- and live my life in Monte
Carlo. -

575
00:33:40.320 --> 00:33:42.089
She's the one.

576
00:33:42.189 --> 00:33:44.659
No. seriously. she's the one.

577
00:33:44.692 --> 00:33:46.594
Oh. it's an excellent project

578
00:33:46.694 --> 00:33:49.263
and this girl rightfully belongs
in it.

579
00:33:52.834 --> 00:33:54.936
<i>At that time. the owner</i>
<i>of RTP</i>

580
00:33:54.969 --> 00:33:59.007
<i>was a mathematician who'd</i>
<i>become a billionaire. Boris</i>
<i>Berezovsky.</i>

581
00:33:59.106 --> 00:34:03.110
<i>He bought an old palace</i>
<i>on Novokuznetskaya Street.</i>

582
00:34:03.210 --> 00:34:05.445
<i>It was meant to be the</i>
<i>headquarters of his business</i>

583
00:34:05.479 --> 00:34:07.749
<i>but Berezovsky did something</i>
<i>else with it entirely.</i>

584
00:34:07.849 --> 00:34:09.684
<i>something far more special.</i>

585
00:34:09.717 --> 00:34:12.820
<i>Made it a club of sorts.</i>
<i>the LogoVaz Club.</i>

586
00:34:16.724 --> 00:34:18.258
<i>It was very exclusive.</i>

587
00:34:18.358 --> 00:34:20.093
<i>The crème de la crème of</i>
<i>politics.</i>

588
00:34:20.127 --> 00:34:22.864
<i>big business. show biz and</i>
<i>crime.</i>

589
00:34:22.897 --> 00:34:26.266
So picture the scene: when the
Caucasus. we're in Chechnya.

590
00:34:27.001 --> 00:34:28.770
And I'm standing in front of a
warlord

591
00:34:28.803 --> 00:34:31.606
who has taken Russian officers
hostage.

592
00:34:31.639 --> 00:34:32.507
And it's no joke.

593
00:34:33.808 --> 00:34:35.643
He's already beheaded one of
them.

594
00:34:36.678 --> 00:34:39.881
But it wasn't politics. it was
business. He wanted money. only
cash.

595
00:34:39.914 --> 00:34:44.151
Right now. I don't have cash on
me. I don't walk around with
wads of cash.

596
00:34:44.184 --> 00:34:45.987
But I notice him eyeing my
watch.

597
00:34:46.020 --> 00:34:49.057
A Patek Philippe Nautilus like
the one I'm wearing tonight.

598
00:34:49.891 --> 00:34:51.224
So I say to him.

599
00:34:51.258 --> 00:34:52.259
"You like my watch?

600
00:34:53.260 --> 00:34:56.296
"Do you know how much it's
worth? It's worth more than your
hostages."

601
00:34:56.396 --> 00:34:58.298
And he says. "I know exactly
what it's worth:

602
00:34:58.398 --> 00:35:00.668
it's worth $800.000. used."

603
00:35:00.768 --> 00:35:03.370
That floored me.
He knew the exact price.

604
00:35:03.403 --> 00:35:04.438
Rustam was no fool.

605
00:35:04.539 --> 00:35:06.674
He said.

606
00:35:06.774 --> 00:35:09.043
"If you take the hostages home.

607
00:35:09.077 --> 00:35:12.145
"the publicity you'll get on TV
is worth more than $800.000."

608
00:35:12.179 --> 00:35:15.917
And he gave me this vacuous
soldier's stare. Zero bullshit.

609
00:35:17.284 --> 00:35:19.419
"So you come out ahead. Is it a
deal?"

610
00:35:21.623 --> 00:35:23.524
So I gave him my watch.
took the hostages home.

611
00:35:23.558 --> 00:35:25.593
It was the opening story
on the evening news.

612
00:35:27.929 --> 00:35:31.198
<i>In those days my modest</i>
<i>achievements as a TV producer</i>

613
00:35:31.231 --> 00:35:34.569
<i>got me the occasional</i>
<i>invitation to LogoVaz club.</i>

614
00:35:35.069 --> 00:35:38.438
<i>Usually. Berezovsky would</i>
<i>summon me for an</i>
<i>update on some project</i>

615
00:35:38.472 --> 00:35:41.709
<i>or to suggest</i>
<i>I hire some random relative</i>

616
00:35:41.743 --> 00:35:43.745
<i>or equally random mistress.</i>

617
00:35:45.580 --> 00:35:46.480
Come in.

618
00:35:48.883 --> 00:35:50.585
-Vadya!
-Boris.

619
00:35:52.887 --> 00:35:55.590
Our friend Vadya is a wizard.

620
00:35:56.456 --> 00:35:57.324
With his help.

621
00:35:58.458 --> 00:36:00.094
we pulverize our opponents.

622
00:36:01.963 --> 00:36:03.097
You happy where you are?

623
00:36:04.398 --> 00:36:05.933
I'm not sure I understand.

624
00:36:05.967 --> 00:36:08.870
In this country you run the same
risk.

625
00:36:08.903 --> 00:36:10.872
whether you have a dog in the
fight or no.

626
00:36:10.972 --> 00:36:12.239
I'll tell you my story.

627
00:36:12.272 --> 00:36:13.273
you'll see what I mean.

628
00:36:14.474 --> 00:36:17.244
So I was perfectly content
doing my own thing.

629
00:36:17.277 --> 00:36:20.615
I'd built a smart. modern. clean
business.

630
00:36:20.648 --> 00:36:23.651
From what I hear your business
was more of a scam.

631
00:36:23.751 --> 00:36:26.120
You resold stolen cars
right off the assembly line.

632
00:36:29.857 --> 00:36:31.391
I was only doing what everyone
was doing that time.

633
00:36:31.425 --> 00:36:32.527
Only worse.

634
00:36:32.627 --> 00:36:35.096
You weren't choosy about your
partners and their methods.

635
00:36:35.129 --> 00:36:36.864
-No offense.
-Anyway.

636
00:36:38.132 --> 00:36:39.466
One day this bastard shows up

637
00:36:39.499 --> 00:36:42.670
tries to steal my business
out from underneath me.

638
00:36:42.770 --> 00:36:43.971
What do you think he does?

639
00:36:44.005 --> 00:36:45.773
Does he open a competing
dealership?

640
00:36:45.873 --> 00:36:48.341
Try to beat me fair and square.
like in the US or Europe?

641
00:36:48.375 --> 00:36:50.178
No Boris. that's not what he
did.

642
00:36:50.277 --> 00:36:54.782
That son of a bitch
filled an old Opel with TNT.

643
00:36:54.882 --> 00:36:56.483
parked it on my route home.

644
00:36:56.517 --> 00:36:58.820
and as I passed.
he pushed a remote and boom...

645
00:37:00.555 --> 00:37:02.156
no more Berezovsky.

646
00:37:03.390 --> 00:37:04.992
At least that was the plan.

647
00:37:05.026 --> 00:37:07.294
But unfortunately.
it didn't work out for him.

648
00:37:08.663 --> 00:37:12.033
And I ended up with my
chauffeur's head in my arms.

649
00:37:13.167 --> 00:37:14.035
I survived.

650
00:37:15.536 --> 00:37:18.773
But that day I realized
that if you don't grab power.

651
00:37:18.806 --> 00:37:20.541
power grabs you.

652
00:37:20.575 --> 00:37:23.177
So I went to Switzerland
for two weeks to recover

653
00:37:23.211 --> 00:37:25.980
and do you know what I did
when I got back to Moscow?

654
00:37:26.814 --> 00:37:28.182
You learned to play tennis.

655
00:37:28.216 --> 00:37:30.818
And it wasn't easy.
I hate the sport.

656
00:37:31.719 --> 00:37:32.820
You hate all sports!

657
00:37:35.890 --> 00:37:38.593
<i>The old President.</i>
<i>Boris Yeltsin. was in decline.</i>

658
00:37:39.827 --> 00:37:42.462
<i>He overdid it on the vodka.</i>
<i>they say.</i>

659
00:37:42.563 --> 00:37:44.799
<i>He had a sports club</i>
<i>built on Sparrow Hills</i>

660
00:37:44.832 --> 00:37:46.200
<i>that looked out over Moscow.</i>

661
00:37:47.201 --> 00:37:50.605
<i>He spent all his spare time</i>
<i>playing tennis there.</i>

662
00:37:50.705 --> 00:37:52.472
<i>It was the only way to get near</i>
<i>him.</i>

663
00:37:55.342 --> 00:37:57.245
Let's face it. Boris was
finished.

664
00:37:57.344 --> 00:37:59.814
The elections were coming.
his numbers were in the dumps.

665
00:37:59.847 --> 00:38:03.350
His whole retinue of petty
schemers were at rock bottom.

666
00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:05.887
And they quickly understood
that I was their only hope.

667
00:38:06.453 --> 00:38:07.555
We hadn't lost yet.

668
00:38:17.865 --> 00:38:19.267
Listen to me.

669
00:38:19.366 --> 00:38:20.601
Boris Nikolayevich.

670
00:38:21.368 --> 00:38:22.770
Russia still needs you.

671
00:38:22.870 --> 00:38:26.240
Your courage and your integrity.

672
00:38:27.108 --> 00:38:29.442
No one loves me anymore.

673
00:38:29.476 --> 00:38:31.112
I saved democracy.

674
00:38:31.145 --> 00:38:33.114
but democracy here means

675
00:38:33.147 --> 00:38:36.017
that everyone has become poor.

676
00:38:36.117 --> 00:38:39.020
Except for a few smart devils
like you.

677
00:38:39.053 --> 00:38:40.755
who've gotten filthy rich!

678
00:38:43.257 --> 00:38:44.625
Well. if you give me

679
00:38:45.492 --> 00:38:47.161
control of state TV.

680
00:38:48.629 --> 00:38:52.033
Then I will give you an election
campaign like you've never seen.

681
00:38:52.133 --> 00:38:55.002
You're in dire straits now. but
in 2 months you'll be on top.

682
00:38:58.272 --> 00:39:00.473
This is how I took control of
Channel 1.

683
00:39:00.508 --> 00:39:02.276
RTP. as it's now called.

684
00:39:02.310 --> 00:39:03.277
And for the record.

685
00:39:04.411 --> 00:39:06.881
I kept my word.
I revived him in the polls.

686
00:39:06.914 --> 00:39:08.616
What you did was sink his
rivals.

687
00:39:08.649 --> 00:39:11.252
A bunch of Communist nostalgics.
taking them out was a cinch.

688
00:39:11.285 --> 00:39:14.454
You were defending your
interests. and those of the
other oligarchs.

689
00:39:15.189 --> 00:39:17.892
Yup. it's true.

690
00:39:17.925 --> 00:39:18.926
So what?

691
00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:21.696
-It's all part of the democratic
process. -Right!

692
00:39:21.796 --> 00:39:24.565
When you have a very loose
notion of democracy.

693
00:39:32.439 --> 00:39:34.208
So over the course of
the rallies

694
00:39:34.308 --> 00:39:35.810
the old man began to enjoy
himself.

695
00:39:36.409 --> 00:39:37.678
Problem was.

696
00:39:38.079 --> 00:39:40.648
that two weeks before the
election he had a heart attack
on us.

697
00:39:40.681 --> 00:39:42.783
-That was a close call.
-Hm.

698
00:39:42.817 --> 00:39:45.319
The-- the very day that
he was supposed to record

699
00:39:45.353 --> 00:39:46.587
his final speech to the nation.

700
00:39:46.621 --> 00:39:48.556
Obviously we canceled
everything.

701
00:39:48.589 --> 00:39:51.826
But a few days later.
the rumors began to spread.

702
00:39:51.859 --> 00:39:52.760
he had to show up.

703
00:39:52.994 --> 00:39:55.428
Except his doctor wouldn't
let him leave his residence.

704
00:39:55.462 --> 00:39:56.664
Oh. it was too risky.

705
00:39:56.697 --> 00:39:59.367
So we figured. to keep up
appearances.

706
00:39:59.967 --> 00:40:02.336
we'd bring the Kremlin furniture
to him.

707
00:40:04.872 --> 00:40:06.974
OK. flags.
Put the flags in the stands.

708
00:40:11.379 --> 00:40:13.114
Federation flag on the left.

709
00:40:13.147 --> 00:40:14.348
Check the distance.

710
00:40:15.082 --> 00:40:17.818
-The President is on his way
down. -Yeah. good.

711
00:40:24.225 --> 00:40:26.127
No. no. no.

712
00:40:31.899 --> 00:40:34.368
Good morning.
Boris Nikolayevich!

713
00:40:34.402 --> 00:40:36.203
Come over. see what we've done.

714
00:40:36.237 --> 00:40:38.706
A perfect copy of your Kremlin
office.

715
00:40:38.739 --> 00:40:40.741
No one's gonna notice the
difference.

716
00:40:41.742 --> 00:40:43.044
Help him with the chair.

717
00:41:17.645 --> 00:41:19.447
Russian citizens. um...

718
00:41:20.815 --> 00:41:21.949
it's why. um...

719
00:41:24.318 --> 00:41:26.153
the motherland. uh...

720
00:41:27.722 --> 00:41:29.924
- Let's try again.
- ...will take place.

721
00:41:29.957 --> 00:41:32.526
Misha. can you slow down the
prompter?

722
00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:33.928
...for the future.

723
00:41:35.463 --> 00:41:37.898
Russian citizens. um...

724
00:41:37.932 --> 00:41:38.966
Once again. please.

725
00:41:39.934 --> 00:41:41.802
Russian citizens...

726
00:41:43.170 --> 00:41:44.839
the 3rd of July

727
00:41:46.307 --> 00:41:48.075
elections day...

728
00:41:49.443 --> 00:41:50.778
you'll not...

729
00:41:50.811 --> 00:41:52.413
only vote for Yeltsin...

730
00:41:52.446 --> 00:41:54.348
This is not going to work.

731
00:41:54.949 --> 00:41:57.351
For-- for not-- for
the future.

732
00:41:58.319 --> 00:42:00.087
Just make him move his lips

733
00:42:00.187 --> 00:42:03.591
and we'll dub in bits
from his old speeches.

734
00:42:04.458 --> 00:42:06.794
<i>Yeltsin was reelected</i>
<i>by a landslide.</i>

735
00:42:06.827 --> 00:42:08.996
<i>And then he fell back into</i>
<i>lethargy.</i>

736
00:42:09.096 --> 00:42:10.765
<i>He had two more heart attacks.</i>

737
00:42:11.332 --> 00:42:13.234
<i>For four years of his 2nd term.</i>

738
00:42:13.334 --> 00:42:15.936
<i>Berezovsky was the real leader</i>
<i>of Russia.</i>

739
00:42:15.970 --> 00:42:18.973
<i>The oligarchs raked in</i>
<i>everything they could.</i>

740
00:42:19.006 --> 00:42:21.876
<i>That's how my old pal. Dmitry</i>
<i>Sidorov.</i>

741
00:42:21.976 --> 00:42:26.480
<i>bought himself a fossil fuel</i>
<i>giant for a mere 168 million.</i>

742
00:42:26.515 --> 00:42:29.316
<i>It would go on to make him</i>
<i>3 billion a year.</i>

743
00:42:30.151 --> 00:42:31.152
Olya!

744
00:42:32.720 --> 00:42:34.989
<i>Berezovsky sensed</i>
<i>the winds were turning.</i>

745
00:42:35.756 --> 00:42:38.759
<i>Russians were tired</i>
<i>and needed order.</i>

746
00:42:38.859 --> 00:42:40.261
<i>They'd grown up in a</i>
<i>motherland.</i>

747
00:42:40.294 --> 00:42:42.963
<i>now all they had was a</i>
<i>supermarket.</i>

748
00:42:42.997 --> 00:42:44.899
<i>A challenge was to come up with</i>
<i>a solution</i>

749
00:42:44.999 --> 00:42:46.367
<i>before someone else did.</i>

750
00:42:46.400 --> 00:42:47.234
So yes.

751
00:42:49.236 --> 00:42:51.138
I have friends in the Kremlin.

752
00:42:51.238 --> 00:42:53.040
And I lend a hand from time to
time.

753
00:42:54.141 --> 00:42:56.777
But the scenario has completely
changed.

754
00:42:56.811 --> 00:42:59.847
It's no longer a matter of
supporting the current regime.

755
00:42:59.880 --> 00:43:02.049
We need to invent something new.

756
00:43:02.149 --> 00:43:03.884
Something and someone.

757
00:43:03.918 --> 00:43:06.220
The President won't make it
to the end of his term.

758
00:43:06.253 --> 00:43:09.023
Someone to embody it. of course.
That's the easy part.

759
00:43:10.257 --> 00:43:11.425
But what we need.

760
00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:14.529
first. is a party
for everyone to rally around.

761
00:43:15.329 --> 00:43:16.397
The Unity Party.

762
00:43:20.167 --> 00:43:21.268
What do you think. Vadya?

763
00:43:22.571 --> 00:43:23.938
I already have an emblem.

764
00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:27.041
The bear.

765
00:43:27.074 --> 00:43:28.676
Symbol of the Russian soul.

766
00:43:32.179 --> 00:43:34.048
So. will you join us?

767
00:43:34.081 --> 00:43:36.317
I don't know. Boris.
I like my job.

768
00:43:36.417 --> 00:43:37.418
It's the same job.

769
00:43:40.054 --> 00:43:44.058
I'm merely suggesting that you
graduate to the next level.

770
00:43:44.091 --> 00:43:45.893
Stop making up stories.

771
00:43:45.926 --> 00:43:48.329
start inventing reality.

772
00:43:48.362 --> 00:43:49.163
With me.

773
00:44:00.708 --> 00:44:02.710
The head of the FSB
would make a good candidate.

774
00:44:04.945 --> 00:44:06.480
The old geezer trusts him.

775
00:44:06.581 --> 00:44:09.116
he's shown his mettle
at decisive moments

776
00:44:09.216 --> 00:44:11.085
and he's a modest guy.

777
00:44:11.118 --> 00:44:12.253
You'll like him.

778
00:44:21.395 --> 00:44:23.330
Director Putin will see you now.

779
00:44:33.974 --> 00:44:35.376
Come. sit.

780
00:44:37.845 --> 00:44:38.746
Sit.

781
00:44:40.615 --> 00:44:41.749
I know why you're here.

782
00:44:41.849 --> 00:44:43.684
Of course you do. You're the
best-informed man in Russia.

783
00:44:44.919 --> 00:44:47.221
I've been thinking it over.
Boris Abramovich.

784
00:44:47.254 --> 00:44:48.122
Uh.

785
00:44:49.658 --> 00:44:50.925
You see.

786
00:44:51.025 --> 00:44:55.029
the Secret Service has all the
advantages of politics

787
00:44:56.263 --> 00:44:57.765
without any of the drawbacks.

788
00:45:00.301 --> 00:45:02.269
I'm at the center of the system
here.

789
00:45:02.369 --> 00:45:04.438
I'm well positioned.
I hear. I see everything.

790
00:45:05.439 --> 00:45:07.908
I can effectively intervene
to protect the President.

791
00:45:07.942 --> 00:45:09.043
the President's family.

792
00:45:09.143 --> 00:45:10.778
I've done it before. I'll do it
again.

793
00:45:13.648 --> 00:45:16.016
You take me out of here.
put me in government.

794
00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:19.420
they chew me up. spit me out
like every other Prime Minister

795
00:45:19.521 --> 00:45:22.122
these past years.
these past months. right?

796
00:45:22.156 --> 00:45:25.125
And you lose the most loyal
guardian of the State.

797
00:45:25.159 --> 00:45:28.128
If we don't act quickly. within
a year there'll be no more

798
00:45:28.162 --> 00:45:30.164
President. no more family to
protect.

799
00:45:30.197 --> 00:45:34.435
And the first thing that the new
head of the Kremlin will do

800
00:45:34.468 --> 00:45:35.903
is replace you.

801
00:45:37.539 --> 00:45:38.472
Why me?

802
00:45:40.174 --> 00:45:41.308
I'm a civil servant.

803
00:45:42.677 --> 00:45:45.580
I-- Sure. I-- I've given. hm...

804
00:45:46.681 --> 00:45:47.948
a couple of speeches in public.

805
00:45:47.982 --> 00:45:51.085
but that they-- they were never
earth-shattering.

806
00:45:51.185 --> 00:45:54.321
The President steps into a room
and sniffs the air.

807
00:45:54.421 --> 00:45:58.058
everyone is on his side in two
minutes. laughing. and they're
crying.

808
00:45:58.092 --> 00:45:59.594
like they're having a chat in
his kitchen.

809
00:45:59.694 --> 00:46:02.162
I'm not-- I'm not that man.
I'm not cut from that cloth.

810
00:46:02.196 --> 00:46:04.431
If I may. Vladimir
Vladimirovich.

811
00:46:05.600 --> 00:46:08.035
that's exactly what this is
about.

812
00:46:08.068 --> 00:46:11.171
The President
has a one-of-a-kind personality.

813
00:46:11.205 --> 00:46:13.974
His human qualities were
essential for moving our country

814
00:46:14.008 --> 00:46:17.211
from the old Soviet Union
to today's Russia.

815
00:46:18.078 --> 00:46:19.514
But he's all used up.

816
00:46:20.447 --> 00:46:22.249
We need someone different.

817
00:46:22.349 --> 00:46:23.317
A clean break.

818
00:46:23.350 --> 00:46:25.352
If the President names
you Prime Minister of

819
00:46:25.386 --> 00:46:27.054
Vladimir Vladimirovich.

820
00:46:27.087 --> 00:46:29.223
you will represent legitimate
authority.

821
00:46:30.257 --> 00:46:33.427
Russians need stability and
security.

822
00:46:33.460 --> 00:46:36.631
You're young. athletic.
energetic.

823
00:46:36.731 --> 00:46:37.798
Something about you says.

824
00:46:38.065 --> 00:46:41.335
"I can handle the full
responsibility of command."

825
00:46:41.902 --> 00:46:43.505
Your career in
the secret services

826
00:46:43.538 --> 00:46:45.139
guarantees you're trustworthy.

827
00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:49.476
And being a man of few words
will work in your favor.

828
00:46:49.511 --> 00:46:50.344
Not against you.

829
00:46:50.578 --> 00:46:53.447
Russians are tired of carnival
barkers.

830
00:46:53.480 --> 00:46:55.617
And the campaign we have in mind

831
00:46:57.117 --> 00:47:01.088
won't be the usual rallies
and empty promises.

832
00:47:01.121 --> 00:47:04.024
We want to take the risk
of portraying you

833
00:47:04.058 --> 00:47:06.628
as a different brand of
politician.

834
00:47:06.661 --> 00:47:09.963
Vladimir Vladimirovich.
I don't know much about politics

835
00:47:09.997 --> 00:47:13.167
but I do know a few things
about communication.

836
00:47:13.267 --> 00:47:16.403
There are two dimensions in a
society.

837
00:47:16.437 --> 00:47:18.872
The horizontal axis
that is daily life

838
00:47:18.906 --> 00:47:21.275
and the vertical axis.
which is authority.

839
00:47:22.309 --> 00:47:24.311
The Soviet system was vertical

840
00:47:24.411 --> 00:47:26.681
then all of a sudden since
the end of the Soviet period

841
00:47:26.781 --> 00:47:28.916
it has become horizontal.

842
00:47:29.016 --> 00:47:32.986
Too much horizontality
is synonymous with chaos.

843
00:47:33.020 --> 00:47:35.757
Russians dream of verticality.

844
00:47:35.790 --> 00:47:38.058
Public opinion coalesces fast.

845
00:47:38.092 --> 00:47:42.764
But we only have a few months
to convince the Russian people

846
00:47:42.797 --> 00:47:45.432
that you are the man of the
hour.

847
00:47:48.837 --> 00:47:51.740
And remember.
you won't be on your own.

848
00:47:52.306 --> 00:47:56.176
I'll be there by your side
to help you and to advise you

849
00:47:56.210 --> 00:47:57.311
whenever you need me.

850
00:48:02.349 --> 00:48:03.450
It's in the bag.

851
00:48:05.185 --> 00:48:07.856
He's no rocket scientist.
but for now he'll do just fine.

852
00:48:10.958 --> 00:48:13.460
<i>I nodded along and</i>
<i>laughed with him.</i>

853
00:48:13.494 --> 00:48:15.229
<i>But things were a bit more</i>
<i>complicated</i>

854
00:48:15.329 --> 00:48:17.164
<i>than what Berezovsky seemed to</i>
<i>grasp.</i>

855
00:48:17.197 --> 00:48:18.800
How are you?

856
00:48:21.502 --> 00:48:22.604
<i>When he addressed</i>
<i>him with his own</i>

857
00:48:22.637 --> 00:48:24.806
<i>brand of chummy joviality.</i>

858
00:48:24.839 --> 00:48:27.575
<i>I sensed a hint of annoyance</i>
<i>in Putin's gaze.</i>

859
00:48:28.743 --> 00:48:30.444
<i>And then there was</i>
<i>that flash of irony</i>

860
00:48:30.477 --> 00:48:33.247
<i>when Boris promised to guide</i>
<i>him every step of the way.</i>

861
00:48:35.082 --> 00:48:37.685
<i>It seemed the very idea</i>
<i>of being guided by this man</i>

862
00:48:37.719 --> 00:48:40.755
<i>was wildly funny to the FSB</i>
<i>chief.</i>

863
00:48:45.025 --> 00:48:47.261
Hurry up. Vadim
Alexeyevich.

864
00:48:47.361 --> 00:48:48.863
Vladimir Vladimirovich is
waiting.

865
00:49:02.109 --> 00:49:03.545
Good afternoon. sir.

866
00:49:04.378 --> 00:49:05.647
Recommendations?

867
00:49:05.680 --> 00:49:08.148
Today we have excellent sea
scallops

868
00:49:08.248 --> 00:49:09.717
with cauliflower mousseline...

869
00:49:09.751 --> 00:49:10.652
A bowl of kasha.

870
00:49:10.752 --> 00:49:12.520
- Two.
- Certainly. sir.

871
00:49:15.890 --> 00:49:18.125
I have a lot of
respect for Berezovsky.

872
00:49:19.026 --> 00:49:20.795
I'm grateful

873
00:49:20.895 --> 00:49:22.764
for his offer. but if...

874
00:49:24.131 --> 00:49:25.265
I embark

875
00:49:26.266 --> 00:49:27.201
on this...

876
00:49:29.403 --> 00:49:30.270
journey.

877
00:49:31.138 --> 00:49:33.040
I'll be relying on my own
strengths.

878
00:49:33.775 --> 00:49:35.042
Not someone else's.

879
00:49:36.143 --> 00:49:39.914
The Russian president cannot and
must not

880
00:49:40.715 --> 00:49:42.817
be subservient to anyone.

881
00:49:44.719 --> 00:49:46.153
It's unthinkable to me.

882
00:49:48.088 --> 00:49:50.725
Your analysis the other day
was very interesting.

883
00:49:50.825 --> 00:49:54.228
But first we should clarify
something.

884
00:49:55.663 --> 00:49:57.431
If you accept my offer.

885
00:49:57.464 --> 00:49:59.767
you'll be working exclusively
for me.

886
00:50:01.435 --> 00:50:02.737
Vadim Alexeyevich.

887
00:50:11.813 --> 00:50:14.314
I've been thinking about your
concept of verticality.

888
00:50:14.983 --> 00:50:15.850
It's potent.

889
00:50:17.317 --> 00:50:18.753
But it cannot remain abstract.

890
00:50:21.188 --> 00:50:23.390
We need a well-defined arena
where we can

891
00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:25.425
restore the verticality of
power.

892
00:50:25.459 --> 00:50:28.930
Otherwise we'll appear helpless.
like all the other politicians
in this country.

893
00:50:28.963 --> 00:50:30.497
Indeed. Vladimir Vladimirovich.

894
00:50:30.598 --> 00:50:32.600
but we can't just snap our
fingers.

895
00:50:33.835 --> 00:50:35.737
There is always the unexpected.

896
00:50:35.770 --> 00:50:38.105
The unexpected is always a
result of incompetence.

897
00:50:38.205 --> 00:50:40.107
We're at the mercy of
circumstance.

898
00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:41.108
Circumstance?

899
00:50:41.208 --> 00:50:43.011
It's staring us in the face.

900
00:50:44.612 --> 00:50:45.513
Don't you see it?

901
00:50:48.516 --> 00:50:50.652
The Islamic fundamentalists

902
00:50:51.719 --> 00:50:54.388
are no longer content with just
Chechnya.

903
00:50:56.223 --> 00:50:57.491
They want Dagestan.

904
00:50:57.525 --> 00:51:00.227
Ingushetia. Bashkortostan.

905
00:51:02.362 --> 00:51:04.131
We let them have them.

906
00:51:05.399 --> 00:51:08.536
in a few years there'll be
nothing left of the Russian
Federation.

907
00:51:08.636 --> 00:51:10.004
I'm sorry but I would think
twice

908
00:51:10.038 --> 00:51:11.639
before getting involved in that
mess.

909
00:51:12.507 --> 00:51:14.141
These past few years

910
00:51:14.241 --> 00:51:16.711
Chechnya has killed more
political careers here in Moscow

911
00:51:16.744 --> 00:51:18.646
than enemies on the battlefield.

912
00:51:18.746 --> 00:51:22.149
None of them have put enough
energy into the issue.

913
00:51:22.249 --> 00:51:25.553
Those politicians want a war

914
00:51:25.653 --> 00:51:27.555
that dare not speak its name.

915
00:51:28.523 --> 00:51:30.558
A humane war.

916
00:51:30.592 --> 00:51:31.893
like the Americans do.

917
00:51:33.327 --> 00:51:34.829
I'm talking about something
else.

918
00:51:36.064 --> 00:51:38.733
I'm not interested in
winning the Nobel Peace Prize.

919
00:51:38.766 --> 00:51:39.934
What interests me

920
00:51:41.201 --> 00:51:44.806
is restoring integrity
to the Russian Federation.

921
00:51:44.906 --> 00:51:46.908
I won't comment on geopolitics.

922
00:51:46.941 --> 00:51:48.408
That's not my field of
expertise.

923
00:51:49.443 --> 00:51:51.178
What I will say. however.

924
00:51:52.279 --> 00:51:53.948
is that it's political suicide.

925
00:51:55.182 --> 00:51:56.216
I think you're mistaken.

926
00:51:58.185 --> 00:51:59.887
I think. you've let Westerners
persuade you

927
00:51:59.921 --> 00:52:03.423
that an electoral campaign has
to be two teams of economists

928
00:52:03.457 --> 00:52:05.593
discussing PowerPoint
presentations.

929
00:52:09.196 --> 00:52:10.464
In Russia.

930
00:52:11.365 --> 00:52:12.366
power

931
00:52:13.701 --> 00:52:15.235
is something else entirely.

932
00:52:18.973 --> 00:52:20.108
<i>That day.</i>

933
00:52:20.374 --> 00:52:23.276
<i>I didn't understand</i>
<i>precisely what Putin meant.</i>

934
00:52:23.310 --> 00:52:25.847
<i>But I left the lunch with one</i>
<i>certainty:</i>

935
00:52:25.947 --> 00:52:29.316
<i>Berezovsky had just made the</i>
<i>biggest mistake of his life.</i>

936
00:52:31.218 --> 00:52:32.954
<i>In the early days of August.</i>

937
00:52:32.987 --> 00:52:35.355
<i>Boris Yeltsin chose a new Prime</i>
<i>Minister.</i>

938
00:52:35.389 --> 00:52:37.091
<i>unknown to most.</i>

939
00:52:37.125 --> 00:52:38.860
<i>The choice of Vladimir Putin</i>

940
00:52:38.893 --> 00:52:41.361
<i>was greeted with general</i>
<i>skepticism.</i>

941
00:52:41.395 --> 00:52:43.131
<i>He was the fifth head</i>
<i>of government Yeltsin</i>

942
00:52:43.230 --> 00:52:45.332
<i>and enthroned in less than a</i>
<i>year.</i>

943
00:52:47.835 --> 00:52:50.138
<i>Our offices were located</i>
<i>in the former House of Soviets.</i>

944
00:52:50.237 --> 00:52:52.239
<i>dubbed the Russian White House.</i>

945
00:52:52.339 --> 00:52:55.977
<i>A giant block of naphthalene on</i>
<i>the banks of the Moskva River.</i>

946
00:52:56.644 --> 00:52:59.580
<i>A whole floor had been freed up</i>
<i>for new hires.</i>

947
00:52:59.614 --> 00:53:01.314
<i>Putin knew there were</i>
<i>only a few weeks left</i>

948
00:53:01.348 --> 00:53:03.216
<i>to harness public opinion.</i>

949
00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:04.752
<i>He had no time to lose.</i>

950
00:53:07.287 --> 00:53:09.957
Tell that son of a bitch
the Prime Minister wants results

951
00:53:09.991 --> 00:53:11.092
on the grounds.

952
00:53:11.125 --> 00:53:12.026
Doesn't matter how.

953
00:53:12.927 --> 00:53:16.130
Sorry. but the media doesn't
set our agenda. politics does.

954
00:53:16.164 --> 00:53:19.100
We're here to produce results.

955
00:53:19.133 --> 00:53:20.768
not limp excuses.

956
00:53:21.501 --> 00:53:24.404
I have the polls you requested.
I need you to crunch the
numbers.

957
00:53:24.438 --> 00:53:26.774
I'll meet you in your office.
I have to see Gusinsky first.

958
00:53:26.808 --> 00:53:27.875
We're on the right track.

959
00:53:27.909 --> 00:53:30.111
Dmitry Anatolyevich. we
shouldn't be on the right track.

960
00:53:30.144 --> 00:53:32.046
we should already be there.

961
00:53:38.152 --> 00:53:39.286
Where's Gusinsky?

962
00:53:39.386 --> 00:53:41.288
Unfortunately he couldn't make
it.

963
00:53:42.790 --> 00:53:45.660
-Are we not important enough for
him? -He's abroad.

964
00:53:45.693 --> 00:53:48.029
So who are you. his messengers?

965
00:53:48.062 --> 00:53:49.496
We run the NTV network.

966
00:53:49.530 --> 00:53:51.298
Uh.

967
00:53:51.398 --> 00:53:54.869
Please give Mr. Gusinsky
the following message:

968
00:53:54.902 --> 00:53:57.805
The policies of the Russian
Federation

969
00:53:57.905 --> 00:54:01.308
are not to be decided
in the offices of NTV.

970
00:54:01.408 --> 00:54:03.711
That never crossed Mr.
Gusinsky's mind.

971
00:54:03.811 --> 00:54:06.313
I watch Kukly.
your political puppet show.

972
00:54:06.413 --> 00:54:09.517
Sometimes I find it funny.
I laugh. I do!

973
00:54:10.685 --> 00:54:12.452
Unfortunately the Prime Minister

974
00:54:12.486 --> 00:54:15.056
doesn't share your sense of
humor.

975
00:54:15.089 --> 00:54:17.959
He suspects Mr. Gusinsky may
have a bone to pick with him.

976
00:54:18.059 --> 00:54:20.094
No way. never in a million
years.

977
00:54:20.194 --> 00:54:23.064
That's a shame he's not here
to explain that himself.

978
00:54:23.097 --> 00:54:24.331
You represent Prime Minister

979
00:54:24.431 --> 00:54:27.334
-Vladimir Vladimirovich Putin as
a midget. -That's not correct...

980
00:54:27.434 --> 00:54:30.171
A deformed dwarf
manipulated by oligarchs.

981
00:54:30.204 --> 00:54:33.674
I thinks in the minds of the
gagmen. he's more of a child.

982
00:54:33.708 --> 00:54:34.976
Yes.
exactly.

983
00:54:35.009 --> 00:54:38.345
And you see that as grounds for
laughter. an infantile gnome?

984
00:54:38.445 --> 00:54:39.479
It's a satirical show.

985
00:54:39.514 --> 00:54:41.983
It's up to the Prime Minister
to determine a line

986
00:54:42.016 --> 00:54:43.483
between satire and insult.

987
00:54:43.518 --> 00:54:45.352
especially during election
season.

988
00:54:45.452 --> 00:54:48.488
The Prime Minister has
determined a line that must not
be crossed.

989
00:54:48.523 --> 00:54:51.192
I believe Mr. Gusinsky
can guess where that line is.

990
00:54:51.225 --> 00:54:53.360
If not. he'll find out at his
own expense.

991
00:54:53.393 --> 00:54:54.394
Good day!

992
00:54:56.864 --> 00:54:58.866
<i>Of course I was working</i>
<i>18-hour days.</i>

993
00:54:58.966 --> 00:55:00.935
<i>Back-to-back meetings</i>
<i>with the Prime Minister.</i>

994
00:55:00.968 --> 00:55:02.870
<i>every single one of them</i>
<i>involving decisions</i>

995
00:55:02.970 --> 00:55:05.206
<i>of major historical importance.</i>

996
00:55:05.239 --> 00:55:08.242
<i>The deeper I sank into the</i>
<i>routine of governing men.</i>

997
00:55:08.276 --> 00:55:11.012
<i>the more the world seemed rife</i>
<i>with misunderstanding</i>

998
00:55:11.112 --> 00:55:12.513
<i>and missed opportunities.</i>

999
00:55:13.247 --> 00:55:15.783
<i>And that's</i>
<i>when the unexpected happened.</i>

1000
00:55:17.785 --> 00:55:20.221
<i>One autumn night.</i>
<i>just after midnight.</i>

1001
00:55:20.254 --> 00:55:23.558
<i>a terrific rumbling tore</i>
<i>through the darkness of the</i>
<i>capital.</i>

1002
00:55:23.658 --> 00:55:26.260
<i>On Guryanova Street</i>
<i>on the outskirts of Moscow.</i>

1003
00:55:26.294 --> 00:55:28.095
<i>hundreds of kilos of explosives</i>

1004
00:55:28.129 --> 00:55:31.132
<i>literally cut a 9-story</i>
<i>apartment complex in two.</i>

1005
00:55:32.767 --> 00:55:34.902
<i>Dozens of sleeping families</i>
<i>were swallowed up</i>

1006
00:55:34.936 --> 00:55:36.771
<i>alive by the explosion.</i>

1007
00:55:36.804 --> 00:55:37.905
<i>Four days later.</i>

1008
00:55:39.841 --> 00:55:42.610
<i>A second explosion</i>
<i>rocked the city at 5</i>
<i>o'clock the morning.</i>

1009
00:55:42.643 --> 00:55:44.912
<i>destroying another building</i>
<i>in the suburbs.</i>

1010
00:55:45.012 --> 00:55:47.148
<i>Over a hundred victims.</i>

1011
00:55:47.181 --> 00:55:49.183
<i>It was our September 11th.</i>

1012
00:55:49.283 --> 00:55:51.652
<i>Before that. the</i>
<i>Chechen War had felt remote.</i>

1013
00:55:51.686 --> 00:55:54.755
<i>But when buildings started</i>
<i>blowing up in the Moscow</i>
<i>suburbs.</i>

1014
00:55:54.789 --> 00:55:57.325
<i>Russians found themselves</i>
<i>with a war at their front door.</i>

1015
00:55:59.426 --> 00:56:00.795
Of course.

1016
00:56:00.828 --> 00:56:01.662
you know what...

1017
00:56:02.597 --> 00:56:03.698
people say?

1018
00:56:06.167 --> 00:56:08.035
They say we were behind it.

1019
00:56:09.036 --> 00:56:10.938
By "we" I mean the FSB.

1020
00:56:11.038 --> 00:56:12.607
It isn't just a rumor.

1021
00:56:13.841 --> 00:56:16.077
There's serious evidence to back
it up.

1022
00:56:16.177 --> 00:56:17.345
Frankly. I don't know.

1023
00:56:18.813 --> 00:56:20.581
If this is a bona fide secret.

1024
00:56:20.615 --> 00:56:22.415
thank God nobody shared it with
me

1025
00:56:22.449 --> 00:56:24.652
but why would we have done that?

1026
00:56:24.685 --> 00:56:26.587
We were certain to win.

1027
00:56:26.621 --> 00:56:27.889
To instill fear.

1028
00:56:28.623 --> 00:56:31.626
<i>So the Russian people would</i>
<i>feel threatened by the</i>
<i>Chechens.</i>

1029
00:56:32.994 --> 00:56:36.097
And to justify the second
Chechen War.

1030
00:56:36.130 --> 00:56:39.100
Perfectly timed to warm public
opinion

1031
00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:43.204
to a coming authoritarian
regime.

1032
00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:48.042
You know I don't like public
speaking.

1033
00:56:48.075 --> 00:56:50.745
Right now the people
need to hear your voice.

1034
00:56:50.845 --> 00:56:53.581
Here. on a state visit.
not from the Kremlin Palace.

1035
00:56:54.649 --> 00:56:56.317
You have to give them a sense of
urgency.

1036
00:56:56.350 --> 00:56:57.585
I'm not an actor.

1037
00:56:59.353 --> 00:57:01.022
I'll give them a simple
statement.

1038
00:57:07.261 --> 00:57:09.864
Word has it you've ordered
the bombing of Grozny Airport

1039
00:57:09.897 --> 00:57:11.732
in retaliation for the attacks.

1040
00:57:11.766 --> 00:57:14.602
Don't you think such actions
could aggravate the situation?

1041
00:57:15.603 --> 00:57:17.505
I'm tired of answering this kind
of question.

1042
00:57:17.605 --> 00:57:20.574
We'll get the terrorists
wherever they're hiding.

1043
00:57:20.608 --> 00:57:22.710
If they're in an airport.
we'll strike the airport.

1044
00:57:22.743 --> 00:57:24.712
if they're in the shitter.
excuse my language.

1045
00:57:24.745 --> 00:57:26.380
but we'll get them in the
shitter.

1046
00:57:27.915 --> 00:57:30.651
You have no idea
the impact that one sentence

1047
00:57:30.685 --> 00:57:32.219
had on the Russian people.

1048
00:57:32.253 --> 00:57:35.156
Finally. we were hearing
a voice of command and control.

1049
00:57:35.256 --> 00:57:37.792
Russians hadn't heard that
in the longest time.

1050
00:57:37.892 --> 00:57:39.026
Stalin's voice?

1051
00:57:39.126 --> 00:57:41.028
Not Yeltsin's in any case.

1052
00:57:41.062 --> 00:57:42.396
Or Gorbachev's.

1053
00:57:43.531 --> 00:57:46.200
That day. Putin became the Tzar.

1054
00:57:59.547 --> 00:58:00.480
Mr. Prime Minister...

1055
00:58:00.815 --> 00:58:02.883
...we can't land at Gudermes.

1056
00:58:02.917 --> 00:58:04.885
visibility is too poor.

1057
00:58:04.919 --> 00:58:08.055
I planned to spend New Year's
Eve with our troops. Understand?

1058
00:58:08.089 --> 00:58:09.323
We must land!

1059
00:58:09.423 --> 00:58:11.192
- We need--
- No. no. no. we must land!

1060
00:58:11.292 --> 00:58:14.528
We need 150 meters of
visibility.

1061
00:58:14.562 --> 00:58:17.698
We've got scarcely 100.
It's too dangerous.

1062
00:58:24.972 --> 00:58:27.742
We have troops stationed in
Dagestan.

1063
00:58:29.110 --> 00:58:31.946
They're ready for inspection.
Could serve as an alternative.

1064
00:58:38.819 --> 00:58:40.654
<i>If the Tzar wanted to</i>
<i>ring in the New Year</i>

1065
00:58:40.688 --> 00:58:43.491
<i>in Chechnya. well then.</i>
<i>that's where we'd go.</i>

1066
00:58:43.591 --> 00:58:45.960
<i>At 1 a.m. we got into some</i>
<i>jeeps</i>

1067
00:58:45.993 --> 00:58:48.596
<i>and headed for the mountain</i>
<i>passes.</i>

1068
00:59:18.159 --> 00:59:20.895
33rd division. Lieutenant
Colonel Fedorov.

1069
00:59:20.995 --> 00:59:22.663
Welcome on the base. Mr. Putin.

1070
00:59:23.998 --> 00:59:26.167
Men. what you're doing is so
important.

1071
00:59:27.501 --> 00:59:30.271
People believe in you.
I'm here to tell you that.

1072
00:59:30.304 --> 00:59:32.373
We're proud of you.
You're working hard.

1073
00:59:34.008 --> 00:59:37.546
I know what you and your men
have done. Very courageous.

1074
00:59:37.645 --> 00:59:41.649
I want you to know the Russian
people think of you

1075
00:59:42.383 --> 00:59:43.417
and are proud of you.

1076
00:59:44.318 --> 00:59:45.486
Happy New Year.

1077
01:01:01.462 --> 01:01:02.463
Wait. wait.

1078
01:01:04.965 --> 01:01:07.801
I would love to drink a toast
to the health of the wounded

1079
01:01:07.835 --> 01:01:08.969
and to wish

1080
01:01:10.004 --> 01:01:12.473
everyone present here
a happy new year.

1081
01:01:13.340 --> 01:01:16.110
but we have serious tasks ahead.

1082
01:01:17.612 --> 01:01:18.979
As you all know.

1083
01:01:20.114 --> 01:01:21.815
we're not only fighting

1084
01:01:21.849 --> 01:01:23.751
for the honor
and dignity of our country.

1085
01:01:23.784 --> 01:01:27.755
we're fighting to prevent
Russia from disintegrating.

1086
01:01:30.491 --> 01:01:33.761
We can't afford one second of
weakness. not one second.

1087
01:01:35.262 --> 01:01:37.131
If we let our guard down.

1088
01:01:37.765 --> 01:01:39.366
all those who died.

1089
01:01:40.034 --> 01:01:41.168
died in vain.

1090
01:01:42.803 --> 01:01:45.607
So I suggest we put our glasses
down.

1091
01:01:48.776 --> 01:01:51.445
We will toast. but uh later.

1092
01:01:59.286 --> 01:02:00.888
I am leaving...

1093
01:02:03.390 --> 01:02:06.026
Leaving before the end of my
term.

1094
01:02:07.027 --> 01:02:10.197
I understand that it is
necessary.

1095
01:02:11.465 --> 01:02:13.767
Russia must enter

1096
01:02:13.801 --> 01:02:16.804
a new millennium
with new political leaders.

1097
01:02:17.805 --> 01:02:20.808
and I leave you all
in the trusted hands

1098
01:02:20.908 --> 01:02:24.679
of Vladimir Vladimirovich Putin.

1099
01:02:30.050 --> 01:02:31.819
The Yeltsin era is over.

1100
01:02:31.852 --> 01:02:34.288
Your friend Berezovsky has to
know

1101
01:02:34.321 --> 01:02:38.058
I'm fed up with his bullshit
memos.

1102
01:02:38.092 --> 01:02:39.827
I thought he was <i>our</i> friend.

1103
01:02:39.927 --> 01:02:41.829
Boris is a very smart man.

1104
01:02:41.929 --> 01:02:45.065
But his intelligence is no
safeguard for his stupidity.

1105
01:02:47.602 --> 01:02:48.737
Better bring him in.

1106
01:02:55.075 --> 01:02:56.210
Boris Abramovich.

1107
01:02:57.111 --> 01:02:58.078
Come.

1108
01:02:59.380 --> 01:03:00.314
Sit.

1109
01:03:03.851 --> 01:03:05.986
I've read your messages.

1110
01:03:06.020 --> 01:03:07.254
some of your memos.

1111
01:03:08.355 --> 01:03:09.857
You've always offered good
advice.

1112
01:03:09.890 --> 01:03:11.058
I'm all ears.

1113
01:03:11.091 --> 01:03:13.360
Volodya. you made me wait an
hour...

1114
01:03:13.394 --> 01:03:14.729
You asked for this meeting.

1115
01:03:15.896 --> 01:03:16.964
Here we are.

1116
01:03:19.466 --> 01:03:20.535
Go ahead.

1117
01:03:23.103 --> 01:03:24.238
Well. I'll be brief.

1118
01:03:26.240 --> 01:03:28.208
We're becoming too negative.
Volodya.

1119
01:03:28.242 --> 01:03:30.844
It's too dark.
We're at war. fine. we get it.

1120
01:03:30.878 --> 01:03:33.648
You're a great general. you're
gonna lead us all to victory.

1121
01:03:33.748 --> 01:03:36.618
but let's make an effort. hm.

1122
01:03:36.651 --> 01:03:40.020
Give these poor Russians
a little bit of hope. too.

1123
01:03:40.054 --> 01:03:42.524
Otherwise rather than voting for
you. they're gonna jump out the
window.

1124
01:03:44.391 --> 01:03:48.596
Rallies and concerts.
and TV commercials. posters!

1125
01:03:48.630 --> 01:03:50.864
-We need to make a splash.
-And who will pay for that?

1126
01:03:50.898 --> 01:03:52.767
I will. of course!

1127
01:03:52.801 --> 01:03:56.036
I heard you passed up free
public TV airtime?

1128
01:03:56.070 --> 01:03:57.037
That's correct.

1129
01:03:57.137 --> 01:03:59.373
It's our choice. Our strategy.

1130
01:03:59.406 --> 01:04:01.475
We'll see if the facts prove us
right.

1131
01:04:01.509 --> 01:04:03.143
If you keep this up.

1132
01:04:03.177 --> 01:04:04.912
people will forget you're a
candidate.

1133
01:04:05.012 --> 01:04:06.447
Don't be ridiculous. Boris.

1134
01:04:07.281 --> 01:04:10.017
I've been interim President for
3 months. We're the government.

1135
01:04:12.086 --> 01:04:14.656
Our campaign is the news.
what we're doing.

1136
01:04:16.023 --> 01:04:17.424
the history we're making.

1137
01:04:19.527 --> 01:04:21.328
Nobody believes advertising
anymore.

1138
01:04:21.929 --> 01:04:25.032
Facts are the only advertising
we're interested in.

1139
01:04:28.969 --> 01:04:31.506
<i>The Tzar had reinstated</i>
<i>the Power Vertical</i>

1140
01:04:31.539 --> 01:04:34.074
<i>- and voters were grateful</i>
<i>to him for it.</i> -

1141
01:04:34.174 --> 01:04:37.444
<i>He was elected President</i>
<i>of the Russian Federation with</i>
<i>no runoff.</i>

1142
01:04:39.446 --> 01:04:41.281
<i>Berezovsky stopped bombarding</i>
<i>the Kremlin</i>

1143
01:04:41.315 --> 01:04:43.150
<i>with unanswered phone calls.</i>

1144
01:04:43.183 --> 01:04:44.786
<i>Naturally. his media mocked</i>

1145
01:04:44.819 --> 01:04:46.920
<i>the pompous inauguration</i>
<i>ceremony.</i>

1146
01:04:46.954 --> 01:04:49.691
<i>But Boris was waiting</i>
<i>for something else:</i>

1147
01:04:49.724 --> 01:04:53.026
<i>a chance to show the Tzar</i>
<i>who was really in charge.</i>

1148
01:05:18.018 --> 01:05:18.952
Sir...

1149
01:05:26.026 --> 01:05:26.994
Umhm.

1150
01:05:32.099 --> 01:05:33.100
Umhm.

1151
01:05:38.238 --> 01:05:39.406
Hm.

1152
01:05:41.375 --> 01:05:43.778
<i>On August 12. 2000. the</i>
<i>Kursk.</i>

1153
01:05:43.878 --> 01:05:46.346
<i>one of the world's</i>
<i>largest nuclear submarines.</i>

1154
01:05:46.380 --> 01:05:49.551
<i>sank during a training exercise</i>
<i>in the Barents Sea.</i>

1155
01:05:50.618 --> 01:05:52.119
<i>There were a hundred crewmen</i>
<i>aboard.</i>

1156
01:05:53.053 --> 01:05:55.422
<i>Some of them died instantly.</i>

1157
01:05:55.523 --> 01:05:57.625
<i>Others were trapped</i>
<i>at the bottom of the sea.</i>

1158
01:05:59.059 --> 01:06:02.530
<i>This was the opportunity</i>
<i>Berezovsky had been waiting</i>
<i>for.</i>

1159
01:06:03.832 --> 01:06:05.999
We rented a helicopter to keep
a constant eye

1160
01:06:06.033 --> 01:06:07.401
on the area where the sub sank.

1161
01:06:07.434 --> 01:06:08.670
-Has it been identified?
-Yes.

1162
01:06:08.703 --> 01:06:11.940
The information just dropped.
but no rescue team is on site.

1163
01:06:12.039 --> 01:06:14.609
That's revolting.
that's what we have to expose.

1164
01:06:14.642 --> 01:06:16.678
Russian experts
won't go on the record.

1165
01:06:16.711 --> 01:06:19.379
-Find them abroad.
-We have a crew in Germany.

1166
01:06:19.413 --> 01:06:22.684
They say NATO forces offered
their help.

1167
01:06:22.784 --> 01:06:24.418
but the Russian navy turned it
down.

1168
01:06:24.451 --> 01:06:25.753
They're spy ships.

1169
01:06:25.787 --> 01:06:28.121
Russia can't humiliate herself
in front of them.

1170
01:06:28.155 --> 01:06:30.959
Can't humiliate herself
in front of them?

1171
01:06:31.058 --> 01:06:34.061
Go find the families.
ask them what they think!

1172
01:06:34.094 --> 01:06:36.330
-That's what we're doing.
-TV's all about emotion.

1173
01:06:36.430 --> 01:06:38.131
The emotion's with the families.

1174
01:06:38.165 --> 01:06:40.267
Can you imagine their anguish?

1175
01:06:40.300 --> 01:06:43.972
Their loved ones may still be
alive. trapped inside a
watertight container.

1176
01:06:44.071 --> 01:06:46.306
waiting for a rescue
that may never come!

1177
01:07:08.796 --> 01:07:11.064
<i>The situation was out of</i>
<i>control.</i>

1178
01:07:11.098 --> 01:07:12.734
<i>I rushed to Sochi.</i>

1179
01:07:12.767 --> 01:07:15.837
<i>I couldn't understand</i>
<i>why Putin wasn't on the ground.</i>

1180
01:07:18.105 --> 01:07:19.707
What would you have me do?

1181
01:07:22.209 --> 01:07:24.012
They're all dead. it's obvious.

1182
01:07:24.111 --> 01:07:26.313
We can't say it until we reach
them yet.

1183
01:07:26.346 --> 01:07:29.116
According to all the experts.
there are survivors on board.

1184
01:07:29.149 --> 01:07:31.051
That's a fact.
We have to save them.

1185
01:07:31.151 --> 01:07:34.454
I don't care if they're dead or
alive. Berezovsky's circus is
about hurting me.

1186
01:07:34.488 --> 01:07:36.758
Everyone is waiting for you to
act.

1187
01:07:36.858 --> 01:07:40.460
I act when I decide the time is
right.

1188
01:07:40.494 --> 01:07:43.263
Your composure has enhanced
your popularity thus far.

1189
01:07:43.297 --> 01:07:45.499
but it's becoming a liability.

1190
01:07:45.533 --> 01:07:48.770
The Russian people are suffering
and you're not with them.

1191
01:07:48.870 --> 01:07:50.505
This is a serious matter.

1192
01:07:52.172 --> 01:07:54.776
<i>Since the</i>
<i>authorities are still refusing</i>
<i>to budge.</i>

1193
01:07:54.809 --> 01:07:58.478
<i>RTP has created a fund for the</i>
<i>families of the sailors.</i>

1194
01:07:58.513 --> 01:08:00.915
<i>Call this number if you want</i>
<i>to support the relatives...</i>

1195
01:08:01.015 --> 01:08:02.149
Do you realize?

1196
01:08:02.884 --> 01:08:06.654
They destroyed the State.
pillaged it for ten years.

1197
01:08:07.522 --> 01:08:10.290
bankrupted our army.
now they're raising money!

1198
01:08:10.324 --> 01:08:11.258
Fucking bastards!

1199
01:08:11.759 --> 01:08:15.228
Why don't they sell their
fucking chalets in Saint-Moritz!

1200
01:08:17.665 --> 01:08:19.232
Get that son of a bitch on the
phone.

1201
01:08:19.266 --> 01:08:20.400
Yes.

1202
01:08:28.208 --> 01:08:29.309
<i>Yeah?</i>

1203
01:08:29.409 --> 01:08:31.045
Do you realize what you're
doing?

1204
01:08:31.779 --> 01:08:35.083
Your network is giving
round-the-clock airtime

1205
01:08:35.182 --> 01:08:37.518
to whores
pretending to be sailors' wives.

1206
01:08:37.552 --> 01:08:39.587
What are you talking about?
You out of your mind?

1207
01:08:39.687 --> 01:08:41.321
They're not whores.
they're the real wives!

1208
01:08:41.355 --> 01:08:44.458
You're State television. Boris.

1209
01:08:44.559 --> 01:08:46.594
and you're conspiring
against the Presidency!

1210
01:08:46.694 --> 01:08:48.696
What does that mean. hm?

1211
01:08:48.730 --> 01:08:51.599
What does this mean. exactly?
I'm asking you a question!

1212
01:08:51.699 --> 01:08:53.935
I have a question for you.
Vladimir Vladimirovich.

1213
01:08:53.968 --> 01:08:57.337
What the hell are you doing
vacationing on the Black Sea?

1214
01:08:57.371 --> 01:08:59.707
Shouldn't you be in Murmansk
running operations?

1215
01:08:59.807 --> 01:09:01.208
Where are you?

1216
01:09:01.241 --> 01:09:03.343
Fucking laughing! Where are you.
huh?

1217
01:09:03.377 --> 01:09:05.345
Côte d'Azur. right? What are you
doing at Côte d'Azur?

1218
01:09:05.445 --> 01:09:06.547
<i>Oh. c'mon!</i>

1219
01:09:06.581 --> 01:09:08.683
I'm not the President.
nobody gives a damn where I am!

1220
01:09:08.716 --> 01:09:11.451
Plus. it so happens I am in
Moscow!

1221
01:09:11.485 --> 01:09:13.855
<i>Just think about it. Volodya.</i>

1222
01:09:13.888 --> 01:09:16.223
<i>If you go and console the</i>
<i>sailors' wives.</i>

1223
01:09:16.256 --> 01:09:18.559
<i>your ratings will</i>
<i>go through the roof.</i>

1224
01:09:18.593 --> 01:09:22.597
And our network will put
its full firepower behind you.

1225
01:09:22.630 --> 01:09:24.231
<i>And you know that's</i>
<i>substantial.</i>

1226
01:09:30.638 --> 01:09:31.639
Well?

1227
01:09:32.507 --> 01:09:35.009
We're going back to Moscow.
Set up that fucking meeting.

1228
01:09:35.109 --> 01:09:36.476
We have no choice.

1229
01:09:44.986 --> 01:09:46.754
And once this mess is behind us.

1230
01:09:48.122 --> 01:09:49.757
we'll take care of your friend
Boris.

1231
01:10:01.002 --> 01:10:04.172
He doesn't mean you any harm.
He respects you.

1232
01:10:04.271 --> 01:10:07.407
You stay safely in Moscow.
do whatever business you like.

1233
01:10:08.142 --> 01:10:11.344
But you must stay out of
politics once and for all.

1234
01:10:11.378 --> 01:10:13.280
Politics is his business.

1235
01:10:14.314 --> 01:10:17.384
Putin is the pure product of the
KGB.

1236
01:10:19.453 --> 01:10:21.055
Its fiercest species.

1237
01:10:21.956 --> 01:10:25.292
He will put Russia in shackles.

1238
01:10:25.325 --> 01:10:27.662
And all we've done in the last
10 years

1239
01:10:27.695 --> 01:10:31.431
to turn it into a normal country
will be swept away.

1240
01:10:31.532 --> 01:10:33.167
Even you. Vadya.

1241
01:10:33.201 --> 01:10:36.070
You're creating a regime
worse than the Soviet Union.

1242
01:10:36.170 --> 01:10:37.638
At least back then.

1243
01:10:37.672 --> 01:10:41.441
the Party could muzzle
the KGB guard dogs.

1244
01:10:41.542 --> 01:10:43.811
But now the Party no longer
exists.

1245
01:10:43.845 --> 01:10:46.147
The FSB is worse than the KGB.

1246
01:10:46.180 --> 01:10:48.281
Who's gonna stop them. you?

1247
01:10:48.315 --> 01:10:50.918
Certainly not.
You've become one of them.

1248
01:10:51.719 --> 01:10:54.055
They're vicious animals.

1249
01:10:54.088 --> 01:10:55.823
They come from the void.

1250
01:10:56.557 --> 01:10:59.026
They've cleared their path
with a sledgehammer.

1251
01:10:59.060 --> 01:11:01.394
No rules. no limits.

1252
01:11:01.428 --> 01:11:05.199
They're hungry.
It's brutish hunger.

1253
01:11:05.833 --> 01:11:07.835
They were humiliated.

1254
01:11:07.869 --> 01:11:10.738
They're descended
from centuries of humiliation.

1255
01:11:12.339 --> 01:11:15.009
They have to grab everything
right away.

1256
01:11:16.244 --> 01:11:18.980
Because they know the tables
will turn.

1257
01:11:19.013 --> 01:11:20.248
Maybe. Boris.

1258
01:11:20.948 --> 01:11:21.949
I don't know.

1259
01:11:23.450 --> 01:11:26.954
What I do know is that Russia
has always been forged this way.

1260
01:11:28.022 --> 01:11:29.123
With an axe.

1261
01:11:33.728 --> 01:11:36.864
<i>Cautiously. Berezovsky</i>
<i>chose exile in London.</i>

1262
01:11:36.898 --> 01:11:40.001
<i>Meanwhile. we were taking off</i>
<i>for New York.</i>

1263
01:11:40.034 --> 01:11:42.335
<i>When you reach the top.</i>
<i>politics propels you onto</i>

1264
01:11:42.369 --> 01:11:44.404
<i>the world stage with no</i>
<i>preparation.</i>

1265
01:11:45.372 --> 01:11:48.009
<i>The world's greats become your</i>
<i>peers.</i>

1266
01:11:48.109 --> 01:11:49.710
<i>But they're a closed circle.</i>

1267
01:11:49.744 --> 01:11:51.279
<i>They've had time to get</i>
<i>acquainted.</i>

1268
01:11:51.378 --> 01:11:53.214
<i>learn the ground rules.</i>

1269
01:11:53.247 --> 01:11:56.449
<i>However much you may be feared</i>
<i>and respected in your own</i>
<i>country.</i>

1270
01:11:56.483 --> 01:11:58.920
<i>here. you're just the new kid</i>
<i>on the block.</i>

1271
01:12:00.154 --> 01:12:02.223
The Waldorf Astoria is the best
hotel.

1272
01:12:02.256 --> 01:12:04.258
And protocol has booked us a
whole floor.

1273
01:12:04.292 --> 01:12:05.425
20 rooms.

1274
01:12:07.394 --> 01:12:08.262
Penthouse?

1275
01:12:09.263 --> 01:12:10.064
No.

1276
01:12:10.932 --> 01:12:12.233
Why not?

1277
01:12:12.266 --> 01:12:15.169
Top 3 floors are booked by the
year for the Saudis.

1278
01:12:17.271 --> 01:12:18.773
This won't take more than an
hour.

1279
01:12:18.806 --> 01:12:20.473
15 minutes to the TV studio.

1280
01:12:20.508 --> 01:12:22.677
half-hour interview. 15 minutes
back.

1281
01:12:24.779 --> 01:12:27.014
-It's a good hit for us.
-Hm-hm.

1282
01:12:37.658 --> 01:12:38.526
What's this?

1283
01:12:39.794 --> 01:12:40.828
It's the freeze.

1284
01:12:42.429 --> 01:12:45.398
The US President's motorcade
is on the move.

1285
01:12:45.432 --> 01:12:46.634
No one else can budge.

1286
01:12:50.538 --> 01:12:51.939
How long does it last?

1287
01:12:53.708 --> 01:12:54.809
Depends.

1288
01:13:00.047 --> 01:13:02.717
So what's it like being a spy?

1289
01:13:02.817 --> 01:13:04.552
Not very different
from being a journalist.

1290
01:13:05.987 --> 01:13:09.456
Your job is to gather
information. to synthesize it.

1291
01:13:10.625 --> 01:13:14.328
You show it to the decision
makers who can use that
information.

1292
01:13:14.362 --> 01:13:16.097
Did you enjoy it?

1293
01:13:16.130 --> 01:13:19.734
Working in intelligence
allowed me to broaden my vision.

1294
01:13:19.834 --> 01:13:22.370
To acquire certain skills.

1295
01:13:23.704 --> 01:13:26.707
Skills of management.
focusing on priorities.

1296
01:13:28.075 --> 01:13:29.476
A learning experience.

1297
01:13:30.578 --> 01:13:34.315
The Kursk tragedy shook
everyone.

1298
01:13:34.348 --> 01:13:37.184
Can you tell me what happened?

1299
01:13:37.218 --> 01:13:39.654
What happened to the submarine?

1300
01:13:41.255 --> 01:13:42.489
It sank.

1301
01:13:51.999 --> 01:13:53.401
If fucking Martians

1302
01:13:53.500 --> 01:13:55.636
were to seize power in Moscow.

1303
01:13:55.736 --> 01:13:58.906
the US would immediately see
them as a legitimate government.

1304
01:13:59.006 --> 01:14:01.709
just as long as they didn't go
near their interests

1305
01:14:01.742 --> 01:14:04.512
and deferred to them as the big
boss.

1306
01:14:05.746 --> 01:14:09.083
The trouble is. they think
they won the Cold War.

1307
01:14:09.116 --> 01:14:10.418
but the Soviet Union

1308
01:14:11.385 --> 01:14:12.253
didn't lose it.

1309
01:14:13.020 --> 01:14:14.989
The Cold War ended because

1310
01:14:15.022 --> 01:14:17.024
we freed ourselves from a
dictatorship.

1311
01:14:17.124 --> 01:14:18.693
which is not the same thing.

1312
01:14:19.560 --> 01:14:21.429
We dismantled the Warsaw Pact.

1313
01:14:21.529 --> 01:14:23.531
We offered them an olive branch.

1314
01:14:23.564 --> 01:14:24.632
Not surrender.

1315
01:14:26.133 --> 01:14:27.702
They should bear that in mind.

1316
01:14:28.769 --> 01:14:29.904
Just once in a while.

1317
01:14:48.322 --> 01:14:50.024
Limonov respects you.

1318
01:14:50.057 --> 01:14:52.059
I thought he despised me.

1319
01:14:52.159 --> 01:14:53.327
He's a visionary.

1320
01:14:54.228 --> 01:14:56.330
Everyone has a place in his
party.

1321
01:14:58.232 --> 01:15:02.069
So what do you think
of my revolutionary avant-garde?

1322
01:15:02.169 --> 01:15:04.905
The Kremlin isn't exactly
quaking in its boots.

1323
01:15:04.939 --> 01:15:07.174
The Kremlin is very wrong.
Sit down.

1324
01:15:09.443 --> 01:15:11.312
So. how was the trip?

1325
01:15:12.747 --> 01:15:14.548
You know what it's like over
there.

1326
01:15:14.582 --> 01:15:16.450
Always fairly amusing I guess.

1327
01:15:16.484 --> 01:15:18.319
Yes. New York can be fun.

1328
01:15:18.352 --> 01:15:20.221
as long as you avoid the
Americans.

1329
01:15:22.123 --> 01:15:24.091
Which one do you prefer.
Eduard?

1330
01:15:25.693 --> 01:15:27.161
This one!

1331
01:15:27.194 --> 01:15:28.996
Imperialism isn't the problem.

1332
01:15:29.096 --> 01:15:30.731
American culture is.

1333
01:15:30.831 --> 01:15:32.166
You used to be attracted to it.

1334
01:15:32.199 --> 01:15:35.102
before it swallowed you up
and spat you out.

1335
01:15:35.136 --> 01:15:36.470
Watching Yeltsin

1336
01:15:36.504 --> 01:15:40.474
turn Russia into a cheap version
of the American nursing home

1337
01:15:40.509 --> 01:15:43.110
prompted me to form
the National Bolshevik Party.

1338
01:15:43.144 --> 01:15:45.446
And you know why I called it
that?

1339
01:15:45.479 --> 01:15:47.081
To infuriate you!

1340
01:15:47.114 --> 01:15:48.816
Nazbol!

1341
01:15:48.849 --> 01:15:51.752
We bring together former
Stalinists.

1342
01:15:51.852 --> 01:15:54.523
homosexuals and punks.

1343
01:15:54.622 --> 01:15:56.624
anarchists. skinheads.

1344
01:15:56.724 --> 01:15:58.125
religious fanatics

1345
01:15:58.159 --> 01:16:00.261
from Buddhist to Orthodox!

1346
01:16:00.361 --> 01:16:02.029
The hardest part is keeping them

1347
01:16:02.129 --> 01:16:03.764
from smashing each other's heads
in.

1348
01:16:03.798 --> 01:16:05.833
You can be sure
they will sooner or later.

1349
01:16:05.866 --> 01:16:07.768
Oh. you don't understand.

1350
01:16:07.802 --> 01:16:09.770
These young people want
to escape the boredom

1351
01:16:09.804 --> 01:16:11.540
of ordinary life.

1352
01:16:11.639 --> 01:16:13.307
They crave heroics.

1353
01:16:14.008 --> 01:16:16.243
And it would be a shame to waste
that.

1354
01:16:18.145 --> 01:16:19.780
May I bum a cigarette. Sergei?

1355
01:16:19.814 --> 01:16:20.714
Yes.

1356
01:16:20.748 --> 01:16:22.016
I need a walk.

1357
01:16:26.387 --> 01:16:29.423
<i>I'd always seen Eduard</i>
<i>Limonov as a brilliant</i>
<i>sociopath</i>

1358
01:16:29.524 --> 01:16:32.393
<i>with no political acumen</i>
<i>whatsoever.</i>

1359
01:16:32.426 --> 01:16:35.329
<i>So I wasn't yet ready to</i>
<i>recognize that he was right.</i>

1360
01:16:36.565 --> 01:16:40.034
<i>For the first time I saw</i>
<i>his reasoning for what it was.</i>

1361
01:16:40.768 --> 01:16:43.404
<i>Not the result of rigorous</i>
<i>analysis</i>

1362
01:16:43.437 --> 01:16:45.806
<i>but far more than casual</i>
<i>intuition.</i>

1363
01:16:54.516 --> 01:16:55.517
Come in.

1364
01:16:56.450 --> 01:16:58.018
Vladimir Vladimirovich.

1365
01:16:58.052 --> 01:17:00.688
Vadim Alexeyevich is here to see
you.

1366
01:17:00.721 --> 01:17:01.689
You may come in.

1367
01:17:06.827 --> 01:17:10.197
How are my ratings?
Elections are coming. Vadya.

1368
01:17:10.231 --> 01:17:12.466
You don't really need to worry.
You're round 60%.

1369
01:17:12.567 --> 01:17:14.668
Closest candidate gets no more
than 12%.

1370
01:17:14.702 --> 01:17:16.571
I'm not interested in them.
they're insignificant.

1371
01:17:16.605 --> 01:17:18.472
One Russian is more popular than
I am.

1372
01:17:19.740 --> 01:17:20.875
Stalin.

1373
01:17:22.076 --> 01:17:23.978
I believe he's been dead
for some time.

1374
01:17:24.078 --> 01:17:25.946
You intellectuals insist on
denouncing

1375
01:17:25.980 --> 01:17:26.981
the horrors of the Gulag.

1376
01:17:27.114 --> 01:17:30.184
You think Stalin was popular
in spite of the killings.

1377
01:17:30.217 --> 01:17:31.185
You're wrong.

1378
01:17:31.218 --> 01:17:33.454
Stalin was popular
because of the killings.

1379
01:17:33.487 --> 01:17:36.891
because he knew how to handle
a thief. a traitor.

1380
01:17:38.459 --> 01:17:41.563
Know what Stalin did when
the Soviet-run trains

1381
01:17:41.596 --> 01:17:42.863
started to derail?

1382
01:17:42.963 --> 01:17:43.864
No. I don't.

1383
01:17:44.265 --> 01:17:46.267
He had the head of the railway
shot for sabotage.

1384
01:17:46.834 --> 01:17:50.237
It didn't solve the problem.
possibly aggravated it.

1385
01:17:50.337 --> 01:17:53.508
But it allowed an outlet for
fury.

1386
01:17:54.509 --> 01:17:56.143
Fury is a structural given.

1387
01:17:56.243 --> 01:17:58.112
No point fighting it.
it must be managed.

1388
01:17:59.847 --> 01:18:01.949
-You want to feed the fury.
-Yes.

1389
01:18:01.982 --> 01:18:03.250
People want a head to roll.

1390
01:18:04.752 --> 01:18:05.753
Whose?

1391
01:18:05.786 --> 01:18:07.522
The most arrogant oligarch.

1392
01:18:08.623 --> 01:18:09.790
Dmitry Sidorov.

1393
01:18:11.358 --> 01:18:12.527
Your former friend.

1394
01:18:13.628 --> 01:18:15.162
I'm told he ran off with your
woman.

1395
01:18:16.497 --> 01:18:17.532
She must have made you happy.

1396
01:18:17.632 --> 01:18:20.602
Didn't last long.
Let bygones be bygones.

1397
01:18:20.635 --> 01:18:22.503
You know. he's planning
to sell a majority share

1398
01:18:22.537 --> 01:18:25.172
of his fossil fuel empire to
Exxon Mobil.

1399
01:18:25.272 --> 01:18:26.675
Been at it long enough.

1400
01:18:26.774 --> 01:18:29.611
He'll make himself
20 billion dollars richer

1401
01:18:29.644 --> 01:18:31.245
by putting our fossil fuel giant

1402
01:18:31.278 --> 01:18:33.147
in the hands of American
investors.

1403
01:18:33.180 --> 01:18:34.782
You could say that a Russian
company

1404
01:18:34.815 --> 01:18:36.283
will acquire international
status.

1405
01:18:36.317 --> 01:18:37.918
I won't say that. it isn't true.

1406
01:18:38.018 --> 01:18:39.621
He's gathered a huge war chest

1407
01:18:39.654 --> 01:18:42.056
to run against me in the 2007
election.

1408
01:18:42.156 --> 01:18:42.790
How do you know?

1409
01:18:43.224 --> 01:18:45.226
How do you think?
We tapped his phone.

1410
01:18:50.030 --> 01:18:51.165
"Nonentity."

1411
01:18:52.667 --> 01:18:56.437
That's what he calls me when he
speaks to his friends in
Washington. D.C.

1412
01:18:56.538 --> 01:18:58.305
"A nonentity."

1413
01:18:58.405 --> 01:19:02.176
He explains that when elected.
he'll change the constitution

1414
01:19:02.209 --> 01:19:05.379
and dismantle the nuclear
arsenal.

1415
01:19:05.412 --> 01:19:06.814
"Nonentity!"

1416
01:19:07.982 --> 01:19:09.049
"Nonentity!"

1417
01:19:11.185 --> 01:19:12.086
This man...

1418
01:19:13.187 --> 01:19:15.489
has fed me more mud than I can
swallow.

1419
01:19:20.494 --> 01:19:21.730
So I've ordered

1420
01:19:21.829 --> 01:19:24.098
Dmitry Sidorov be arrested

1421
01:19:24.198 --> 01:19:25.833
tomorrow at dawn.

1422
01:19:25.933 --> 01:19:28.469
He's heading to Siberia.
has to stop to refuel.

1423
01:19:28.570 --> 01:19:29.970
That's where we'll take him.

1424
01:19:30.070 --> 01:19:32.973
Cameramen. photographers.
they'll all be on site.

1425
01:19:33.073 --> 01:19:35.577
Your job is to orchestrate it
for the media.

1426
01:19:40.247 --> 01:19:41.382
Go. go. go.

1427
01:19:48.355 --> 01:19:50.692
-Nobody move!
-Okay.

1428
01:19:54.128 --> 01:19:55.262
This is it.

1429
01:19:56.765 --> 01:19:57.865
Here we are.

1430
01:19:57.965 --> 01:19:59.867
<i>The news went all around</i>
<i>the world.</i>

1431
01:19:59.967 --> 01:20:01.770
<i>The immediate effect was to</i>
<i>remind people</i>

1432
01:20:01.869 --> 01:20:03.904
<i>that money can't protect</i>
<i>you from everything.</i>

1433
01:20:04.739 --> 01:20:07.875
<i>Of course for you Westerners.</i>
<i>this is totally taboo.</i>

1434
01:20:07.975 --> 01:20:10.779
<i>A politician arrested. why not?</i>

1435
01:20:10.878 --> 01:20:12.880
<i>But a billionaire? Unthinkable.</i>

1436
01:20:13.480 --> 01:20:15.650
<i>Because your society</i>
<i>was founded on the principle</i>

1437
01:20:15.750 --> 01:20:17.918
<i>that there is no power</i>
<i>greater than money.</i>

1438
01:20:19.621 --> 01:20:22.022
<i>My job was to fit Dmitry's fall</i>
<i>from grace</i>

1439
01:20:22.056 --> 01:20:24.391
<i>into a successful TV format.</i>

1440
01:20:24.491 --> 01:20:25.893
<i>This wasn't difficult.</i>

1441
01:20:26.493 --> 01:20:28.028
<i>The masses have</i>
<i>always loved to watch</i>

1442
01:20:28.062 --> 01:20:29.863
<i>a powerful man's head roll.</i>

1443
01:20:29.897 --> 01:20:32.667
<i>There's no bloodier dictator</i>
<i>than the people.</i>

1444
01:20:34.401 --> 01:20:35.869
<i>Once Sidorov was arrested.</i>

1445
01:20:35.903 --> 01:20:38.906
<i>Putin's reelection was a mere</i>
<i>formality.</i>

1446
01:20:38.939 --> 01:20:40.407
<i>From that point forward.</i>

1447
01:20:40.508 --> 01:20:43.911
<i>the Russian government began</i>
<i>undergoing a profound change.</i>

1448
01:20:44.011 --> 01:20:46.781
<i>The power struggle shifted</i>
<i>from the public stage</i>

1449
01:20:46.815 --> 01:20:48.550
<i>to the Tzar's inner circle.</i>

1450
01:20:48.583 --> 01:20:51.786
<i>The State once again depended</i>
<i>on court intrigue.</i>

1451
01:20:52.654 --> 01:20:54.556
<i>There are those with an office</i>
<i>close to the Tzar's</i>

1452
01:20:54.589 --> 01:20:56.658
<i>and those with a direct line to</i>
<i>him.</i>

1453
01:20:56.691 --> 01:20:59.326
<i>There are those who accompany</i>
<i>him on overseas missions.</i>

1454
01:20:59.426 --> 01:21:01.563
<i>and those who vacation with him</i>
<i>in Sochi.</i>

1455
01:21:02.296 --> 01:21:05.834
<i>No detail can be overlooked.</i>
<i>no matter how trivial.</i>

1456
01:21:05.933 --> 01:21:07.935
<i>From seating plans at gala</i>
<i>dinners.</i>

1457
01:21:08.035 --> 01:21:10.638
<i>to waiting times</i>
<i>in the President's antechamber.</i>

1458
01:21:10.672 --> 01:21:13.608
<i>Nothing escapes a courtier's</i>
<i>attention.</i>

1459
01:21:16.110 --> 01:21:19.279
I adapted to the new
regime as I adapt to everything.

1460
01:21:19.313 --> 01:21:21.649
Some were far better at it than
I was.

1461
01:21:21.683 --> 01:21:22.983
Like Igor Sechin.

1462
01:21:24.351 --> 01:21:26.320
Especially Igor Sechin.

1463
01:21:27.689 --> 01:21:28.956
Like many men of his kind

1464
01:21:28.989 --> 01:21:31.358
he drew his strength
from being underestimated.

1465
01:21:32.192 --> 01:21:36.029
When the period of the courtiers
came. he was in his element.

1466
01:21:36.063 --> 01:21:38.566
Indeed. he was head courtier.

1467
01:21:46.574 --> 01:21:48.610
Well. did you get what you want?

1468
01:21:48.643 --> 01:21:49.811
Got what the Tzar wanted.

1469
01:21:49.844 --> 01:21:52.479
He wanted Dmitry's business for
himself?

1470
01:21:52.514 --> 01:21:54.682
What he wants
is to destroy the oligarchs.

1471
01:21:54.716 --> 01:21:57.552
And replace them
with siloviki like yourself?

1472
01:21:57.585 --> 01:22:00.622
Russia has always needed
strongmen.

1473
01:22:00.655 --> 01:22:03.090
Soldiers. spies. police.

1474
01:22:04.091 --> 01:22:05.125
That's how I got where I am.

1475
01:22:05.225 --> 01:22:07.595
And why you take what you want.
Well done.

1476
01:22:07.629 --> 01:22:09.864
If that's how you wish to put
it. Vadim Alexeyevich.

1477
01:22:11.098 --> 01:22:13.467
Oh and watch out.

1478
01:22:13.500 --> 01:22:15.737
He's back from the G20 in
Berlin.

1479
01:22:15.770 --> 01:22:17.539
Tired. bad-tempered.

1480
01:22:20.374 --> 01:22:22.777
It's always the same.
they treat me like I'm...

1481
01:22:22.877 --> 01:22:25.479
the president of Finland.

1482
01:22:25.513 --> 01:22:28.516
They better watch out.
They need to be very careful.

1483
01:22:29.416 --> 01:22:33.020
The ability to inspire fear
is a poor man's sole weapon

1484
01:22:33.120 --> 01:22:35.657
when he's defending his dignity.
I learned that on the street.

1485
01:22:35.757 --> 01:22:39.026
Trouble is. Mr. President.
by spooking our enemies

1486
01:22:39.059 --> 01:22:41.161
we're in danger
of spooking the markets too.

1487
01:22:41.195 --> 01:22:42.931
And we can't afford that.

1488
01:22:43.030 --> 01:22:45.767
The markets never ruled Russia.
Vadya.

1489
01:22:45.800 --> 01:22:47.501
Maybe once.

1490
01:22:47.535 --> 01:22:49.938
Hm. Maybe once under-- under
Yeltsin.

1491
01:22:50.037 --> 01:22:52.640
What was the result then?
Law of the jungle.

1492
01:22:54.441 --> 01:22:55.643
We-- we need...

1493
01:22:56.511 --> 01:22:57.712
to take control.

1494
01:22:57.745 --> 01:23:00.615
Take control of all the wealth
of the country.

1495
01:23:00.648 --> 01:23:04.418
The forests. the mines. the gas.
and the petrol.

1496
01:23:05.820 --> 01:23:07.755
We'll see to it
that it serves the interests

1497
01:23:07.789 --> 01:23:11.793
and the glory of the Russian
people.

1498
01:23:14.194 --> 01:23:15.530
Like with Dmitry.

1499
01:23:15.563 --> 01:23:16.598
What about Dmitry?

1500
01:23:17.599 --> 01:23:19.934
Well. the oil monopolies

1501
01:23:19.968 --> 01:23:23.303
went directly from
Sidorov's pocket to Sechin's.

1502
01:23:24.438 --> 01:23:26.039
What's that got to do
with the interest and glory

1503
01:23:26.073 --> 01:23:27.074
of the Russian people?

1504
01:23:56.971 --> 01:23:59.841
Lovely weather. you
should have a dip before you
leave.

1505
01:23:59.874 --> 01:24:02.109
Thanks. another time.

1506
01:24:02.209 --> 01:24:03.343
You prefer Sochi?

1507
01:24:04.478 --> 01:24:05.713
You know why I'm here.

1508
01:24:07.715 --> 01:24:09.884
I'd like to hear you say it.

1509
01:24:09.984 --> 01:24:12.085
-There's a rumor... -You didn't
come here about a rumor.

1510
01:24:15.355 --> 01:24:16.490
Okay.

1511
01:24:19.293 --> 01:24:21.161
We have very reliable intel

1512
01:24:21.194 --> 01:24:24.097
that you're one of the Ukrainian
protesters' main supporters.

1513
01:24:24.131 --> 01:24:26.668
-Well. since you know...
-Putin is spitting mad.

1514
01:24:26.701 --> 01:24:27.602
I was worried.

1515
01:24:27.835 --> 01:24:29.837
but in fact
you come bearing good news.

1516
01:24:29.871 --> 01:24:32.774
Ukraine has been an integral
part of Russian territory

1517
01:24:32.807 --> 01:24:33.775
for centuries.

1518
01:24:34.174 --> 01:24:36.878
-Do you genuinely believe that?
-I'm just the messenger!

1519
01:24:37.545 --> 01:24:38.680
Know what he said?

1520
01:24:40.014 --> 01:24:41.849
"Go and see that fucker!

1521
01:24:41.883 --> 01:24:44.552
"Tell him he's gone too far
"and try to reason with him."

1522
01:24:47.021 --> 01:24:49.356
-You know what his problem is?
-I know what you think it is.

1523
01:24:49.389 --> 01:24:51.124
That he's not your regular
politician.

1524
01:24:51.158 --> 01:24:53.561
that he's KGB. he's a spy.

1525
01:24:53.661 --> 01:24:55.228
No. He's not a spy.

1526
01:24:55.262 --> 01:24:58.066
A spy's job is to gather
accurate intelligence.

1527
01:24:58.165 --> 01:24:59.299
but he's a counterspy.

1528
01:24:59.333 --> 01:25:02.302
A counterspy's job is to be
paranoid.

1529
01:25:02.402 --> 01:25:04.806
to see conspiracies everywhere.

1530
01:25:04.839 --> 01:25:06.541
and to invent them if necessary.

1531
01:25:06.574 --> 01:25:08.275
You've been in exile too long.

1532
01:25:09.043 --> 01:25:10.143
You've lost touch.

1533
01:25:10.177 --> 01:25:12.547
As if the poor Ukrainians
don't have every reason

1534
01:25:12.580 --> 01:25:14.682
to revolt against a
pro-Russian government.

1535
01:25:14.782 --> 01:25:18.653
You know who the main supporters
of the Ukrainian protesters are?

1536
01:25:18.686 --> 01:25:21.254
The CIA. the US State
Department.

1537
01:25:21.288 --> 01:25:23.256
major American foundations.

1538
01:25:23.290 --> 01:25:25.560
George Soros and you.

1539
01:25:25.593 --> 01:25:28.029
to the tune of 30 million
dollars!

1540
01:25:28.062 --> 01:25:28.963
Or so I've heard.

1541
01:25:29.063 --> 01:25:30.430
Well. that's politics. Vadya.

1542
01:25:31.365 --> 01:25:32.934
Do you know what else it is?

1543
01:25:32.967 --> 01:25:33.935
It's democracy.

1544
01:25:34.969 --> 01:25:37.204
You forgot the meaning
of that word long ago.

1545
01:25:43.243 --> 01:25:45.345
Remember. I'm not here by
choice.

1546
01:25:45.379 --> 01:25:47.481
I'm living in exile here. Vadya.

1547
01:25:48.716 --> 01:25:50.084
If I even set foot in Russia.

1548
01:25:50.118 --> 01:25:52.219
I'll end up in Siberia like
Sidorov.

1549
01:25:53.955 --> 01:25:58.291
Boris. despite our differences.
the Tzar is still your friend.

1550
01:25:58.325 --> 01:26:00.928
That's why you were permitted
to sell your Russian assets.

1551
01:26:00.962 --> 01:26:03.363
1.3 billion. correct?

1552
01:26:03.397 --> 01:26:04.632
Far less than they were worth.

1553
01:26:12.239 --> 01:26:13.841
What if I keep on at it. hm?

1554
01:26:15.409 --> 01:26:17.477
I didn't come here to threaten
you.

1555
01:26:18.980 --> 01:26:20.648
I understand your resentment.

1556
01:26:21.849 --> 01:26:23.951
But you can't turn against your
country.

1557
01:26:23.985 --> 01:26:25.620
Putin's Russia isn't my country.

1558
01:26:27.121 --> 01:26:28.756
In spite of all our flaws.

1559
01:26:28.856 --> 01:26:31.025
we managed to build a free
country

1560
01:26:31.125 --> 01:26:33.594
where you could do what you
want. you could say what you
want

1561
01:26:33.628 --> 01:26:35.395
for the first time in Russian
history.

1562
01:26:35.495 --> 01:26:37.865
And you have wrecked all that
in just a few years.

1563
01:26:39.867 --> 01:26:42.302
You turned Russia back into
what it always was...

1564
01:26:44.371 --> 01:26:46.140
a prison the size of a country.

1565
01:26:47.274 --> 01:26:49.177
Just like in the Soviet times.

1566
01:27:32.352 --> 01:27:33.554
Hello.

1567
01:27:36.057 --> 01:27:37.725
Is this your boat?

1568
01:27:37.825 --> 01:27:38.926
Nothing is ever mine.

1569
01:27:40.194 --> 01:27:41.696
At least not in the way you
mean.

1570
01:27:43.197 --> 01:27:44.331
Oligarch money?

1571
01:27:45.600 --> 01:27:46.601
Are you afraid?

1572
01:27:48.069 --> 01:27:49.804
Afraid your masters will find
out?

1573
01:27:49.837 --> 01:27:51.338
Masters?

1574
01:27:51.371 --> 01:27:54.575
From what I hear. you're in
the service to power now.

1575
01:27:54.609 --> 01:27:56.210
I suppose so.

1576
01:27:57.211 --> 01:28:00.313
You don't like Vladimir
Vladimirovich very much.

1577
01:28:00.347 --> 01:28:01.749
No. you're right.

1578
01:28:01.849 --> 01:28:02.850
I don't like power.

1579
01:28:03.718 --> 01:28:06.854
I like it even less when you kid
yourself and pretend it's modern
art.

1580
01:28:06.954 --> 01:28:08.856
Sorry Vadya. but I find you
despicable.

1581
01:28:08.890 --> 01:28:10.091
Despicable?

1582
01:28:11.592 --> 01:28:12.593
That's a bit harsh.

1583
01:28:12.627 --> 01:28:13.594
You've earned it.

1584
01:28:15.462 --> 01:28:16.764
You dodged my question.

1585
01:28:16.864 --> 01:28:19.734
Are we being bankrolled
by oligarchs as we speak?

1586
01:28:20.968 --> 01:28:24.872
This boat belongs to
a businessman from Portland.

1587
01:28:24.972 --> 01:28:27.508
He invented some software
when he was 24.

1588
01:28:27.608 --> 01:28:29.210
was a multi-millionaire by 26

1589
01:28:29.243 --> 01:28:32.445
and sold his company
to Microsoft by 28.

1590
01:28:32.479 --> 01:28:34.615
Been bored stiff ever since.

1591
01:28:36.117 --> 01:28:38.351
He'd like to have
another idea in his lifetime

1592
01:28:38.385 --> 01:28:40.288
but it's slow in the coming.

1593
01:28:40.387 --> 01:28:41.656
You sleeping with him?

1594
01:28:42.990 --> 01:28:44.125
Absolutely not.

1595
01:28:45.126 --> 01:28:47.394
When I have an idea
of a line of jewelry.

1596
01:28:47.427 --> 01:28:49.030
he funds it.

1597
01:28:49.130 --> 01:28:50.965
Sometimes he makes a bit of
money.

1598
01:28:50.998 --> 01:28:53.601
I mean.
clearly chump change to him.

1599
01:28:53.634 --> 01:28:56.469
And he lends you his boat
when it strikes your fancy?

1600
01:28:56.503 --> 01:28:57.905
Yes.

1601
01:28:58.005 --> 01:29:01.742
When I'm bored of this world.
which is often.

1602
01:29:01.776 --> 01:29:04.111
I take refuge here.

1603
01:29:04.145 --> 01:29:06.047
A gilded cage.

1604
01:29:06.080 --> 01:29:07.281
Your comfort zone.

1605
01:29:09.650 --> 01:29:10.918
I loved Dmitry.

1606
01:29:13.154 --> 01:29:15.556
I mean we had fun for a few
months.

1607
01:29:15.590 --> 01:29:18.559
I loved the crazy wind that was
blowing.

1608
01:29:18.593 --> 01:29:20.294
Then you got rid of him too.

1609
01:29:20.328 --> 01:29:21.796
I wasn't cruel.

1610
01:29:21.829 --> 01:29:23.197
Not that time.

1611
01:29:25.166 --> 01:29:26.567
We grew apart.

1612
01:29:26.667 --> 01:29:28.169
Dmitry got interested in oil.

1613
01:29:28.202 --> 01:29:30.437
I mean that didn't bring him
much luck.

1614
01:29:33.307 --> 01:29:36.077
But for a few years
I preferred Los Angeles

1615
01:29:36.177 --> 01:29:37.578
to anywhere else.

1616
01:29:37.612 --> 01:29:39.513
Was Hollywood up to your
standards?

1617
01:29:39.547 --> 01:29:40.815
Hollywood!

1618
01:29:41.949 --> 01:29:43.184
I stayed away--

1619
01:29:43.217 --> 01:29:45.920
I stayed away from Hollywood.
It's like Moscow.

1620
01:29:46.187 --> 01:29:50.524
Only power relationships count.
the rest is insignificant.

1621
01:29:50.558 --> 01:29:51.826
I liked the desert.

1622
01:29:51.859 --> 01:29:54.829
I liked the ocean waves.

1623
01:29:55.963 --> 01:29:58.833
driving along the Pacific Coast
Highway and

1624
01:29:59.967 --> 01:30:03.104
when I felt like going to Japan.
I went to Japan.

1625
01:30:16.483 --> 01:30:17.885
This is the prettiest cove.

1626
01:30:20.388 --> 01:30:21.756
Your plane awaits.

1627
01:30:26.594 --> 01:30:28.095
Tonight I'll be in Moscow.

1628
01:30:29.997 --> 01:30:31.165
How miserable.

1629
01:30:47.248 --> 01:30:49.583
<i>The following autumn.</i>
<i>as expected.</i>

1630
01:30:49.617 --> 01:30:51.986
<i>the situation in Ukraine</i>
<i>worsened.</i>

1631
01:30:52.019 --> 01:30:55.156
<i>The protesters refused</i>
<i>to accept the election results.</i>

1632
01:30:55.890 --> 01:30:58.526
<i>Hundreds of thousands of them</i>
<i>occupied the Maidan.</i>

1633
01:30:58.626 --> 01:31:01.562
<i>Kiev's central square.</i>
<i>with songs. orange ribbons.</i>

1634
01:31:01.662 --> 01:31:05.132
<i>multicolored tents</i>
<i>and pro-Western slogans.</i>

1635
01:31:16.911 --> 01:31:19.380
Suddenly. commissions
of international observers

1636
01:31:19.413 --> 01:31:20.514
came out of the woodwork

1637
01:31:20.548 --> 01:31:22.550
to dispute the
results of the election

1638
01:31:22.650 --> 01:31:25.920
which were won by pro-Russian
candidate Yanukovych.

1639
01:31:26.954 --> 01:31:29.423
Those elections were notoriously
rigged.

1640
01:31:29.457 --> 01:31:30.758
I happened to be there.

1641
01:31:30.791 --> 01:31:31.726
Really?

1642
01:31:32.660 --> 01:31:34.462
Well. there'd
just been a vote in Iraq

1643
01:31:34.595 --> 01:31:36.931
with American soldiers
controlling polling stations.

1644
01:31:36.964 --> 01:31:39.333
and everyone thought that was
fine.

1645
01:31:39.433 --> 01:31:41.035
But not in Ukraine.

1646
01:31:41.068 --> 01:31:43.304
No. in Ukraine
there had to be another vote.

1647
01:31:43.337 --> 01:31:45.573
because the result wasn't right.

1648
01:31:45.606 --> 01:31:48.476
They called that farce
the Orange Revolution.

1649
01:31:48.576 --> 01:31:52.213
and the previous year in Georgia
it was the Rose Revolution.

1650
01:31:52.313 --> 01:31:54.482
Another poetic revolution.

1651
01:31:54.582 --> 01:31:56.584
all pretty girls and lofty
ideals.

1652
01:31:56.617 --> 01:31:59.320
Yet another stooge of the
Americans

1653
01:31:59.353 --> 01:32:00.955
is catapulted to power.

1654
01:32:00.988 --> 01:32:05.459
Do you seriously believe
it takes a CIA conspiracy

1655
01:32:05.493 --> 01:32:07.828
to make Ukrainians
want to flee Russia's orbit

1656
01:32:07.862 --> 01:32:09.296
in favor of the European Union?

1657
01:32:09.330 --> 01:32:10.998
What people do you mean?

1658
01:32:11.866 --> 01:32:15.736
Do you really think everyone
finds your Europe so attractive?

1659
01:32:15.770 --> 01:32:18.839
Well. we don't need a crystal
ball to see that Russia's turn
is coming.

1660
01:32:18.873 --> 01:32:22.376
The next lovely color-coded
revolution will be in Moscow.

1661
01:32:22.476 --> 01:32:26.113
The future president of Russia
will have a degree from Yale.

1662
01:32:27.348 --> 01:32:29.350
That process seemed inevitable.

1663
01:32:30.351 --> 01:32:33.120
The young people were fed up
with us. and the Americans

1664
01:32:33.154 --> 01:32:35.756
were making the most of that
rebellion.

1665
01:32:35.790 --> 01:32:38.025
We'd have to be stronger than
them to survive.

1666
01:32:39.126 --> 01:32:41.530
Now the old methods
had outlived their usefulness.

1667
01:32:41.662 --> 01:32:44.198
locking up agitators.
expelling diplomats...

1668
01:32:44.231 --> 01:32:47.768
If we were in a bad mood that
day. eliminating opponents.

1669
01:32:47.868 --> 01:32:49.370
I don't believe in any of that.

1670
01:32:51.372 --> 01:32:54.341
So I took a chance
and tried a different tack.

1671
01:33:07.888 --> 01:33:09.924
The President has been informed
of your arrival.

1672
01:33:10.024 --> 01:33:11.526
He sends his greetings.

1673
01:33:17.665 --> 01:33:19.166
Alexander Sergeyevich.

1674
01:33:19.767 --> 01:33:21.635
I've been following
you and your Night Wolves

1675
01:33:21.669 --> 01:33:23.437
for a few years now.

1676
01:33:23.538 --> 01:33:24.672
I'm impressed.

1677
01:33:25.406 --> 01:33:28.275
You take those lost souls and...

1678
01:33:29.276 --> 01:33:32.547
give them a home.
a sense of discipline.

1679
01:33:32.581 --> 01:33:35.816
Our group gives them
two things they lacked:

1680
01:33:35.916 --> 01:33:38.319
fraternity and strength.

1681
01:33:38.352 --> 01:33:42.323
You aren't just a biker gang.
you're true Russian patriots.

1682
01:33:42.356 --> 01:33:43.525
We have values.

1683
01:33:43.558 --> 01:33:45.192
Russian values.

1684
01:33:45.292 --> 01:33:48.963
Those of our Holy Mother.
the Orthodox Church.

1685
01:33:48.996 --> 01:33:50.898
I understand.
Alexander Sergeyevich.

1686
01:33:50.931 --> 01:33:53.067
and so does the President.

1687
01:33:53.100 --> 01:33:55.469
Wolves are not merely predators.

1688
01:33:55.570 --> 01:33:57.872
they're also
the guardians of the forest.

1689
01:33:59.106 --> 01:34:00.941
Did you see what happened
in Ukraine?

1690
01:34:00.975 --> 01:34:02.710
Yes. Revolution.

1691
01:34:02.810 --> 01:34:03.944
A coup.

1692
01:34:05.946 --> 01:34:07.448
Do you know who took power?

1693
01:34:07.481 --> 01:34:10.284
-The Americans.
-Spot on!

1694
01:34:10.317 --> 01:34:12.119
They set up a youth
organization.

1695
01:34:12.219 --> 01:34:14.623
paid for free concerts in Maidan
Square.

1696
01:34:15.456 --> 01:34:19.426
I bet even the orange ribbon
was thought up by an adman.

1697
01:34:19.460 --> 01:34:21.228
Everything is geared to the
young

1698
01:34:21.262 --> 01:34:25.232
because their energy is the most
precious commodity out there.

1699
01:34:25.266 --> 01:34:28.936
Their frustration. their
desire to change the world.

1700
01:34:28.969 --> 01:34:30.704
Young people need a cause.

1701
01:34:30.738 --> 01:34:31.839
And an enemy.

1702
01:34:33.240 --> 01:34:35.142
We need to find them
a cause and an enemy

1703
01:34:35.242 --> 01:34:38.078
before they choose those things
for themselves.

1704
01:34:38.112 --> 01:34:41.448
Or worse. the Americans choose
for them.

1705
01:34:41.482 --> 01:34:43.250
Except we can't do that.

1706
01:34:43.350 --> 01:34:45.452
Look around you. Alexander.

1707
01:34:45.486 --> 01:34:48.122
all we have here
are bureaucrats in suits.

1708
01:34:48.155 --> 01:34:49.723
We're the adults.

1709
01:34:49.757 --> 01:34:52.726
we're in power.
We're their true enemy.

1710
01:34:52.760 --> 01:34:55.162
You're younger than me. I
believe.

1711
01:34:55.262 --> 01:34:56.764
You've taken a different path.

1712
01:34:57.431 --> 01:34:59.033
You embody freedom and
adventure.

1713
01:34:59.133 --> 01:35:00.834
Your vitality is undimmed.

1714
01:35:00.868 --> 01:35:03.037
Young people can feel that.

1715
01:35:03.137 --> 01:35:05.839
The Tzar is with you.
He's your brother.

1716
01:35:05.873 --> 01:35:07.107
He's no bureaucrat.

1717
01:35:07.141 --> 01:35:10.144
He likes speed. he does judo. he
hunts.

1718
01:35:10.177 --> 01:35:12.980
He is of the race of conquerors.

1719
01:35:13.013 --> 01:35:16.183
Do you think he'd join
one of our rallies?

1720
01:35:16.283 --> 01:35:17.151
Of course.

1721
01:35:17.184 --> 01:35:19.353
The Night Wolves will be
honored.

1722
01:35:19.386 --> 01:35:22.356
We'll hold a rally
for all the young patriots.

1723
01:35:22.389 --> 01:35:25.259
We'll kick off the struggle
against our true foe:

1724
01:35:25.292 --> 01:35:28.162
the decadent West and its false
values.

1725
01:35:28.195 --> 01:35:30.864
Maidan. but in reverse.

1726
01:35:30.898 --> 01:35:32.166
Exactly.

1727
01:35:32.199 --> 01:35:35.202
Russia must become a place

1728
01:35:35.302 --> 01:35:38.172
where people can vent their rage
against the world

1729
01:35:38.205 --> 01:35:41.141
while remaining
faithful servants to the Tzar.

1730
01:35:41.175 --> 01:35:45.446
Basically. you want to make
revolution impossible.

1731
01:35:45.547 --> 01:35:48.315
Let's just say we want to
remove the need for one.

1732
01:35:51.586 --> 01:35:53.053
<i>Without a drop of vodka.</i>

1733
01:35:53.087 --> 01:35:56.390
<i>Zaldostanov left the Kremlin</i>
<i>intoxicated.</i>

1734
01:35:56.423 --> 01:35:58.459
<i>Little did he know my next</i>
<i>meeting</i>

1735
01:35:58.560 --> 01:36:00.160
<i>was with the intriguing</i>
<i>spokesperson</i>

1736
01:36:00.194 --> 01:36:02.564
<i>of an Orthodox renaissance</i>
<i>movement...</i>

1737
01:36:05.065 --> 01:36:08.936
<i>Followed by the head of a group</i>
<i>of strikingly crusty young</i>
<i>communists...</i>

1738
01:36:11.005 --> 01:36:13.608
<i>And the leader</i>
<i>of the Spartak supporters.</i>

1739
01:36:14.208 --> 01:36:15.843
<i>I recruited them all:</i>

1740
01:36:15.876 --> 01:36:17.478
<i>bikers and hooligans.</i>

1741
01:36:17.579 --> 01:36:19.179
<i>anarchists and skinheads.</i>

1742
01:36:19.213 --> 01:36:21.248
<i>communists and religious</i>
<i>fanatics.</i>

1743
01:36:21.348 --> 01:36:24.351
<i>from the far right to the far</i>
<i>left and beyond.</i>

1744
01:36:24.451 --> 01:36:26.120
<i>After what happened in Ukraine.</i>

1745
01:36:26.220 --> 01:36:29.123
<i>we could no longer leave</i>
<i>the forces of fury unchecked.</i>

1746
01:36:29.624 --> 01:36:32.426
<i>Monopolizing power</i>
<i>was no longer enough.</i>

1747
01:36:32.459 --> 01:36:34.696
<i>we needed to monopolize</i>
<i>subversion.</i>

1748
01:36:41.368 --> 01:36:42.637
Wait. I will be back.

1749
01:36:44.104 --> 01:36:46.073
Vadim!

1750
01:36:46.106 --> 01:36:47.509
Miss Chekhova.

1751
01:36:47.609 --> 01:36:50.444
I'm so flattered you blessed
us with your presence.

1752
01:36:50.477 --> 01:36:53.881
Don't mock me. You know how
influential your salon is.

1753
01:36:53.981 --> 01:36:55.149
Love.

1754
01:36:55.316 --> 01:36:58.218
society gossip has never
had much influence on power.

1755
01:36:58.986 --> 01:37:02.122
Thanks to you I can rub
shoulders with my opponents.

1756
01:37:02.990 --> 01:37:03.924
Indeed.

1757
01:37:05.125 --> 01:37:07.629
Garry Kasparov is here.

1758
01:37:11.265 --> 01:37:14.401
Chess champions
have never gone far in politics.

1759
01:37:14.435 --> 01:37:15.402
Vadim Baranov.

1760
01:37:16.170 --> 01:37:19.039
-The Wizard of the Kremlin.
-That's me.

1761
01:37:19.139 --> 01:37:21.308
I hear you've given
your doctrine a name.

1762
01:37:21.408 --> 01:37:23.812
Indeed. "Sovereign Democracy."

1763
01:37:23.911 --> 01:37:27.047
Russia needs to be a democracy
to benefit from globalization.

1764
01:37:27.147 --> 01:37:31.553
I see no traces of democracy
in our society. but do carry on.

1765
01:37:31.653 --> 01:37:34.622
And sovereignty is politically
synonymous with stability.

1766
01:37:34.656 --> 01:37:38.058
The more stable the regime.
the more competitive it is.

1767
01:37:38.158 --> 01:37:41.128
You know what people say
of your "sovereign democracy?"

1768
01:37:41.161 --> 01:37:43.397
That it is to democracy

1769
01:37:43.430 --> 01:37:46.133
what an electric chair is to a
chair.

1770
01:37:49.470 --> 01:37:52.039
It's just a bit of clever wit!
At least it's funny.

1771
01:38:00.481 --> 01:38:02.449
You left the Côte d'Azur.

1772
01:38:02.550 --> 01:38:03.951
I never stay anywhere for long.

1773
01:38:05.185 --> 01:38:07.522
You know me.
it's not one of my attributes.

1774
01:38:07.555 --> 01:38:08.690
Are you living in Moscow?

1775
01:38:08.723 --> 01:38:09.724
{woman in background] Hi.

1776
01:38:09.824 --> 01:38:12.694
When I'm here.
I stay at the Hotel Metropol.

1777
01:38:12.727 --> 01:38:14.194
I rent a suite year-round.

1778
01:38:14.228 --> 01:38:15.462
Are you inviting me?

1779
01:38:20.200 --> 01:38:22.503
Do you remember my dear friend.
the dog-man?

1780
01:38:23.337 --> 01:38:24.438
Of course.

1781
01:38:24.471 --> 01:38:25.673
Arseny.

1782
01:38:25.707 --> 01:38:27.609
He's an acclaimed director now.

1783
01:38:27.642 --> 01:38:30.043
He's putting on Monteverdi's
<i>Orfeo</i> .

1784
01:38:30.978 --> 01:38:35.082
He's turning the whole theater
into a pagan basilica.

1785
01:38:36.216 --> 01:38:37.852
He calls it a space liturgy.

1786
01:38:39.086 --> 01:38:40.988
I was his high priestess in
Paris.

1787
01:38:42.489 --> 01:38:43.525
You want to come?

1788
01:38:43.858 --> 01:38:46.861
Maybe that kind of provocation
no longer interests you.

1789
01:38:54.602 --> 01:38:56.838
I'm not sure I remember who you
are.

1790
01:38:56.871 --> 01:38:58.873
I get lost in all your mazes.

1791
01:38:58.907 --> 01:39:00.007
It's a game.

1792
01:39:01.108 --> 01:39:03.645
Politics is really
the only game worth playing.

1793
01:39:03.745 --> 01:39:05.045
You've become cynical.

1794
01:39:06.113 --> 01:39:08.917
You've reached the limit
of your intelligence.

1795
01:39:09.016 --> 01:39:09.918
Cynical.

1796
01:39:11.118 --> 01:39:12.052
Possibly.

1797
01:39:13.287 --> 01:39:14.589
But not only.

1798
01:39:14.622 --> 01:39:15.623
I don't know.

1799
01:39:17.559 --> 01:39:19.059
I'll have to get back to you on
it.

1800
01:39:22.931 --> 01:39:25.365
As for now. I'm not sure.

1801
01:39:26.400 --> 01:39:27.869
Come with me to the opera.

1802
01:39:30.404 --> 01:39:31.505
We'll dine at the Metropol.

1803
01:40:05.072 --> 01:40:07.575
I'm tired. Ksenia.

1804
01:40:07.675 --> 01:40:08.676
What of?

1805
01:40:10.945 --> 01:40:13.380
Using your black magic
in the service of power?

1806
01:40:14.314 --> 01:40:17.084
The other day I caught a glimpse
of myself in a mirror.

1807
01:40:17.184 --> 01:40:18.318
only it wasn't me.

1808
01:40:19.453 --> 01:40:20.454
It was my father.

1809
01:40:21.321 --> 01:40:23.423
My father's face imprinted on
mine

1810
01:40:23.457 --> 01:40:25.325
despite my best efforts.

1811
01:40:27.461 --> 01:40:28.630
Let's go in.

1812
01:40:29.864 --> 01:40:30.999
I'm cold.

1813
01:40:35.102 --> 01:40:37.204
Last time you asked me a
question.

1814
01:40:38.205 --> 01:40:39.106
Remember?

1815
01:40:39.206 --> 01:40:41.609
Yes. You told me you needed some
time.

1816
01:40:41.643 --> 01:40:43.477
Now I can answer.

1817
01:40:43.511 --> 01:40:45.479
You aren't just cynical.

1818
01:40:46.213 --> 01:40:49.751
You have chosen to espouse your
times.

1819
01:40:49.851 --> 01:40:52.386
You could just as easily
have run away from them.

1820
01:40:52.486 --> 01:40:53.988
Do you like these times?

1821
01:40:54.022 --> 01:40:55.122
They're ours.

1822
01:40:57.491 --> 01:40:59.827
We're no better or worse than
they are.

1823
01:40:59.861 --> 01:41:01.996
I don't think I'm kidding
myself.

1824
01:41:02.030 --> 01:41:04.131
I embody the worst of them.

1825
01:41:04.164 --> 01:41:07.334
And you think you're gonna have
to answer for them one day.

1826
01:41:07.367 --> 01:41:08.736
Do you believe in the future?

1827
01:41:10.004 --> 01:41:10.905
I don't.

1828
01:41:11.639 --> 01:41:13.641
The future doesn't give a shit
about us.

1829
01:41:15.009 --> 01:41:18.746
"Our wound is raw
beneath the yoke of these times.

1830
01:41:21.015 --> 01:41:21.883
"See.

1831
01:41:23.017 --> 01:41:25.787
"behind the forest we walk.

1832
01:41:25.820 --> 01:41:26.654
"trembling.

1833
01:41:27.889 --> 01:41:29.757
"how a castle already lit

1834
01:41:30.390 --> 01:41:32.159
"in the evening awaits."

1835
01:41:32.259 --> 01:41:33.260
Rilke.

1836
01:41:34.328 --> 01:41:35.530
I'd forgotten.

1837
01:41:57.284 --> 01:42:00.187
<i>I've never been</i>
<i>fascinated by St. Petersburg.</i>

1838
01:42:00.287 --> 01:42:03.091
<i>It's a museum</i>
<i>city. stuck in the past.</i>

1839
01:42:03.190 --> 01:42:06.259
<i>The Tzar. on the other hand.</i>
<i>can only fully relax there</i>

1840
01:42:06.293 --> 01:42:08.663
<i>with his oldest. truest</i>
<i>friends:</i>

1841
01:42:08.696 --> 01:42:13.034
<i>a motley crew of former FSB</i>
<i>agents. black belt judokas</i>

1842
01:42:13.067 --> 01:42:15.937
<i>and real-life thugs</i>
<i>who have hit the big time.</i>

1843
01:42:15.970 --> 01:42:18.873
<i>They. it must be said. were</i>
<i>straight out of Richard III.</i>

1844
01:42:19.974 --> 01:42:23.111
<i>In just a few years.</i>
<i>the shady provincial dealers</i>

1845
01:42:23.210 --> 01:42:25.880
<i>had amassed wealth worthy of</i>
<i>Gulf emirs.</i>

1846
01:42:34.122 --> 01:42:35.188
Remarkable!

1847
01:42:35.222 --> 01:42:36.724
Bravo!

1848
01:42:38.225 --> 01:42:39.127
Really delightful.

1849
01:42:39.226 --> 01:42:40.128
Thank you.

1850
01:42:41.328 --> 01:42:43.064
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

1851
01:42:44.832 --> 01:42:46.000
Okay. guys.

1852
01:43:03.117 --> 01:43:06.988
Our new chef's
specialty is truffle risotto.

1853
01:43:08.990 --> 01:43:10.257
Ah.

1854
01:43:10.457 --> 01:43:13.728
Let me know if I should keep him
or send him back to Italy.

1855
01:43:15.295 --> 01:43:16.263
Bon appétit.

1856
01:43:17.765 --> 01:43:20.333
Genia. you let us down.

1857
01:43:20.367 --> 01:43:23.905
You serve us truffle risotto.
but where is the arugula?

1858
01:43:25.272 --> 01:43:28.042
Shall I remind you
that our ice hockey team

1859
01:43:28.142 --> 01:43:30.611
finished the last championship
in sixth place?

1860
01:43:33.147 --> 01:43:35.983
We moved up seven spots in the
ranking

1861
01:43:36.017 --> 01:43:38.285
and overtook Dynamo Moscow.

1862
01:43:38.385 --> 01:43:39.787
Wait till next year.

1863
01:43:39.821 --> 01:43:41.122
you will see!

1864
01:43:41.155 --> 01:43:43.925
Well then. you'll have your
arugula next year.

1865
01:43:45.893 --> 01:43:48.696
You can't find decent arugula
in Russia.

1866
01:43:48.796 --> 01:43:50.798
But I've just bought an estate
by the Black Sea

1867
01:43:50.898 --> 01:43:52.066
in order to grow it.

1868
01:43:52.166 --> 01:43:55.302
It will be magnificent.
but there's a wait.

1869
01:43:55.402 --> 01:43:56.303
Keep the chef!

1870
01:43:56.503 --> 01:43:58.305
He knows what he's doing.

1871
01:43:59.406 --> 01:44:02.009
His flight home
to Pisa was already booked...

1872
01:44:02.043 --> 01:44:03.778
-Oh.
-On Ryanair!

1873
01:44:09.083 --> 01:44:12.385
Yevgeny clearly has high
standards.

1874
01:44:12.419 --> 01:44:16.691
But his talent goes beyond food.
It touches on geopolitics.

1875
01:44:17.859 --> 01:44:20.661
Even some subjects
we've been discussing lately.

1876
01:44:20.695 --> 01:44:23.430
It would be good
if you two had a word. Vadya.

1877
01:44:27.501 --> 01:44:29.070
<i>I didn't know Prigozhin</i>
<i>well.</i>

1878
01:44:29.103 --> 01:44:30.470
<i>Except as a restaurateur.</i>

1879
01:44:30.504 --> 01:44:32.840
<i>But I did know Putin</i>
<i>had been shepherding his ascent</i>

1880
01:44:32.940 --> 01:44:34.509
<i>with unwavering benevolence.</i>

1881
01:44:35.877 --> 01:44:37.545
<i>A 5-minute flight.</i>

1882
01:44:37.578 --> 01:44:39.046
<i>Shortly after taking off</i>

1883
01:44:39.080 --> 01:44:41.616
<i>we began maneuvers</i>
<i>to land on Kamenny Island.</i>

1884
01:44:42.116 --> 01:44:45.119
<i>where the Tzar's close friends</i>
<i>lived in the grandest palaces</i>

1885
01:44:45.219 --> 01:44:47.121
<i>of the imperial aristocracy.</i>

1886
01:44:51.358 --> 01:44:52.994
I'm not an intellectual like
you.

1887
01:44:53.094 --> 01:44:55.362
but life has taught me a few
lessons.

1888
01:44:55.462 --> 01:44:56.831
And not only in jail!

1889
01:44:58.099 --> 01:45:00.001
I don't doubt that.

1890
01:45:00.034 --> 01:45:01.936
Do you know how I started out?

1891
01:45:01.969 --> 01:45:05.072
My partners and I
obtained Saint Petersburg's

1892
01:45:05.106 --> 01:45:06.641
first-ever casino license.

1893
01:45:06.741 --> 01:45:09.010
You obtained it or the Tzar
gave it to you.

1894
01:45:09.110 --> 01:45:10.443
when he was deputy mayor there?

1895
01:45:10.477 --> 01:45:12.379
You know what a casino is?

1896
01:45:12.412 --> 01:45:15.516
A monument to human
irrationality.

1897
01:45:15.616 --> 01:45:17.718
Why the hell throw away your
money

1898
01:45:17.752 --> 01:45:19.887
when all the odds are against
you?

1899
01:45:19.987 --> 01:45:23.291
When you bet on human
irrationality. you always win.

1900
01:45:23.390 --> 01:45:24.725
Sure.

1901
01:45:24.759 --> 01:45:26.260
Sure. Take an average guy.

1902
01:45:27.061 --> 01:45:28.863
As long as he's comfortable.

1903
01:45:28.896 --> 01:45:32.867
has a safe job. can take family
holidays at the seaside.

1904
01:45:32.900 --> 01:45:34.802
has a retirement plan...

1905
01:45:34.902 --> 01:45:36.403
he stays put.

1906
01:45:36.503 --> 01:45:38.139
But if things don't look so
good...

1907
01:45:39.173 --> 01:45:41.474
If he loses his job. his house.

1908
01:45:41.509 --> 01:45:43.578
if the future is less certain...

1909
01:45:44.278 --> 01:45:45.513
will he play it safe?

1910
01:45:46.479 --> 01:45:47.480
Hardly!

1911
01:45:47.682 --> 01:45:51.886
He'll prefer risk
to a hopeless status quo.

1912
01:45:51.919 --> 01:45:54.889
Chaos becomes
more attractive than order.

1913
01:45:54.922 --> 01:45:58.926
Westerners see China. India.
thank God. Russia.

1914
01:45:59.026 --> 01:46:01.629
making great strides
while they're stalling.

1915
01:46:01.662 --> 01:46:04.665
And they're willing to make
the most unreasonable bets.

1916
01:46:04.699 --> 01:46:06.767
Our job is to encourage them.

1917
01:46:06.801 --> 01:46:07.802
The Internet.

1918
01:46:08.936 --> 01:46:11.205
It's the battleground of modern
warfare.

1919
01:46:14.175 --> 01:46:17.311
"Internet Research Agency."
I thought up the name.

1920
01:46:17.345 --> 01:46:19.146
Sounds good. right? What do you
think?

1921
01:46:19.180 --> 01:46:20.514
Hm.

1922
01:46:20.548 --> 01:46:21.448
Anton!

1923
01:46:22.350 --> 01:46:24.285
Our managing editor.

1924
01:46:24.318 --> 01:46:27.221
He has a PhD
in international relations

1925
01:46:27.321 --> 01:46:30.024
and speaks every language
you can think of.

1926
01:46:30.057 --> 01:46:31.826
Pleased to meet you. Anton.

1927
01:46:31.859 --> 01:46:33.694
Tell him what you guys are doing
here.

1928
01:46:33.728 --> 01:46:35.730
Influence. Information.

1929
01:46:35.830 --> 01:46:39.200
The Russian point of view on the
West. for Westerners.

1930
01:46:39.233 --> 01:46:41.702
They're convinced their media
and elites lie about everything.

1931
01:46:41.736 --> 01:46:44.471
so they'll buy alternative
versions.

1932
01:46:44.504 --> 01:46:47.241
The message we're sending is
that we tell the truth.

1933
01:46:47.875 --> 01:46:49.844
Russia tells the truth.

1934
01:46:49.877 --> 01:46:51.245
Like Russia Today.

1935
01:46:51.345 --> 01:46:54.215
Except that we work
in social media. not TV.

1936
01:46:54.849 --> 01:46:56.017
Shall we get some coffee?

1937
01:46:56.884 --> 01:47:00.121
We have a nice little break
area. Sofas. houseplants.

1938
01:47:00.221 --> 01:47:01.622
And ping pong tables.

1939
01:47:01.656 --> 01:47:03.591
You go on.
We'll catch up with you.

1940
01:47:07.728 --> 01:47:12.633
Yevgeny. you'll have to explain
because I don't quite get it.

1941
01:47:12.667 --> 01:47:13.601
Something wrong?

1942
01:47:14.869 --> 01:47:16.137
Can we talk?

1943
01:47:16.170 --> 01:47:17.104
Sure.

1944
01:47:22.276 --> 01:47:23.711
I thought our goal

1945
01:47:23.744 --> 01:47:26.013
was to affect mindsets
in Europe and the States.

1946
01:47:26.113 --> 01:47:27.648
Get into people's heads.

1947
01:47:27.682 --> 01:47:29.884
-Sure.
-And now you bring me Anton?

1948
01:47:29.917 --> 01:47:33.220
-He's the best.
-That's exactly the problem.

1949
01:47:33.254 --> 01:47:34.889
Don't you realize that
Westerners

1950
01:47:34.922 --> 01:47:37.224
aren't interested in politics
anymore?

1951
01:47:37.258 --> 01:47:38.726
If we want to screw them over.

1952
01:47:38.759 --> 01:47:40.928
we should talk about anything
but politics.

1953
01:47:41.028 --> 01:47:42.763
We don't need Anton.

1954
01:47:42.797 --> 01:47:45.032
-Who do we need?
-We need idiots.

1955
01:47:45.132 --> 01:47:47.068
Highly addictive ones.

1956
01:47:48.035 --> 01:47:49.670
Cyber-dependent otakus.

1957
01:47:49.704 --> 01:47:52.606
beauty-advice bimbos.
YouTube conspiracy theorists...

1958
01:47:52.640 --> 01:47:54.742
Anything that generates clicks.

1959
01:47:54.775 --> 01:47:58.045
But we have to get our message
through at some point. don't we?

1960
01:47:59.280 --> 01:48:01.315
Who do you think we are?

1961
01:48:01.415 --> 01:48:03.117
The Komintern?

1962
01:48:03.150 --> 01:48:06.520
I regret to inform you
that the Soviet Union is gone.

1963
01:48:06.554 --> 01:48:10.791
No more party line. no message
to get across either. Yevgeny.

1964
01:48:10.825 --> 01:48:11.926
Just wire.

1965
01:48:12.927 --> 01:48:15.196
Come on. let's go.
We're wasting our time here.

1966
01:48:19.066 --> 01:48:20.301
What wire do you mean?

1967
01:48:21.335 --> 01:48:23.404
How do you break a wire?

1968
01:48:23.437 --> 01:48:26.073
You twist it one way.
and then the other.

1969
01:48:26.173 --> 01:48:28.209
That's what we're going to do.
Yevgeny.

1970
01:48:28.309 --> 01:48:29.577
And how do you do that?

1971
01:48:30.745 --> 01:48:34.148
Build your network
and see who takes the bait.

1972
01:48:34.181 --> 01:48:35.549
They'll all have an obsession.

1973
01:48:35.583 --> 01:48:38.052
We won't know which the clicks
will show us.

1974
01:48:38.085 --> 01:48:39.587
One will be an anti-vaxxer.

1975
01:48:39.687 --> 01:48:42.223
another will be pro-life or
pro-choice.

1976
01:48:42.256 --> 01:48:43.157
It doesn't matter.

1977
01:48:43.190 --> 01:48:45.960
We won't convert anyone.
Yevgeny.

1978
01:48:45.993 --> 01:48:48.996
We just need them all to have
something that drives them nuts

1979
01:48:49.096 --> 01:48:51.098
and someone who enrages them.

1980
01:48:51.832 --> 01:48:53.000
It's infallible.

1981
01:48:53.100 --> 01:48:56.237
No preferences. Yevgeny. no
arguments.

1982
01:48:56.270 --> 01:48:57.338
Just wire.

1983
01:48:57.371 --> 01:49:00.841
We twist it one way and then the
other until it breaks.

1984
01:49:00.875 --> 01:49:02.877
Okay. I got it. Wire.

1985
01:49:04.211 --> 01:49:06.847
But everything is traceable
on the Internet.

1986
01:49:06.881 --> 01:49:09.250
and sooner or later we'll get
caught.

1987
01:49:09.350 --> 01:49:12.753
Yes. we will.
And that's what we're after.

1988
01:49:12.853 --> 01:49:14.355
Serving our allies is
predictable.

1989
01:49:14.388 --> 01:49:16.690
But how will they react
when they realize we're also

1990
01:49:16.724 --> 01:49:18.959
supporting our own opponents?

1991
01:49:18.993 --> 01:49:20.127
They'll think we're fools.

1992
01:49:20.161 --> 01:49:24.165
No. they'll go insane!
Lose their bearings.

1993
01:49:24.265 --> 01:49:26.767
All they'll know is that
we've gotten into their heads

1994
01:49:26.801 --> 01:49:29.503
and are playing with their
neural circuits as we please.

1995
01:49:30.504 --> 01:49:32.907
The Americans wrote the
algorithm.

1996
01:49:33.007 --> 01:49:34.141
We'll use it too.

1997
01:49:34.241 --> 01:49:35.976
only better than them.

1998
01:49:36.010 --> 01:49:37.378
Anyone accusing us of plotting

1999
01:49:37.411 --> 01:49:39.647
against democracy will be an
ally.

2000
01:49:39.747 --> 01:49:42.383
They'll build the myth
that we're all-powerful.

2001
01:49:42.416 --> 01:49:44.151
It'll be the greatest of all
secrets

2002
01:49:44.185 --> 01:49:46.120
because everyone will know it:

2003
01:49:46.153 --> 01:49:49.723
the Russians are controlling
the modern world.

2004
01:49:49.757 --> 01:49:51.158
They are its masters.

2005
01:49:52.393 --> 01:49:55.796
That's the interesting thing
about politics. Yevgeny.

2006
01:49:55.830 --> 01:49:58.232
Anything that makes you seem
strong

2007
01:49:58.265 --> 01:50:00.634
actually increases that
strength.

2008
01:50:18.085 --> 01:50:19.386
Borya.

2009
01:50:19.420 --> 01:50:20.421
Vadya.

2010
01:50:23.424 --> 01:50:25.527
Do you come bearing a message?

2011
01:50:25.560 --> 01:50:27.828
Sorry Borya. no message.

2012
01:50:27.928 --> 01:50:29.663
So. to what do I owe this?

2013
01:50:29.697 --> 01:50:30.798
Purely pleasure.

2014
01:50:33.434 --> 01:50:36.070
You're in London to see
the British Olympic Association?

2015
01:50:37.572 --> 01:50:38.973
You're well informed. as ever.

2016
01:50:39.073 --> 01:50:41.108
The Sochi Olympics seem to be
the only thing

2017
01:50:41.208 --> 01:50:42.776
- the Tzar cares about these
days. -

2018
01:50:42.810 --> 01:50:44.979
The President was kind enough to
let me

2019
01:50:45.079 --> 01:50:46.847
supervise the opening ceremony.

2020
01:50:46.947 --> 01:50:48.682
Well I hope you'll be
giving out medals

2021
01:50:48.716 --> 01:50:50.851
to the best political
assassination.

2022
01:50:50.951 --> 01:50:52.587
I don't know. Boris.

2023
01:50:52.621 --> 01:50:55.122
The main thing is
for Russia to come out on top.

2024
01:50:56.957 --> 01:50:58.225
I'm not worried.

2025
01:50:59.460 --> 01:51:01.095
You'll find...

2026
01:51:01.128 --> 01:51:02.830
the worst possible solution.

2027
01:51:03.931 --> 01:51:05.099
You always do.

2028
01:51:17.011 --> 01:51:20.748
Well. you may not
have a message for me. but...

2029
01:51:22.617 --> 01:51:24.018
I have one for him.

2030
01:51:27.656 --> 01:51:30.124
Oh. come on. there's no polonium
in it.

2031
01:51:30.157 --> 01:51:33.460
It's a letter to the Tzar.
I wrote it from the heart.

2032
01:51:33.494 --> 01:51:35.296
You can read it if you want to.

2033
01:51:40.768 --> 01:51:43.470
"I beg you to grant me your
forgiveness as a Christian..."

2034
01:51:43.504 --> 01:51:44.738
Are you serious?

2035
01:51:44.772 --> 01:51:48.643
I'm appealing to his faith.
and I'm offering my services.

2036
01:51:48.677 --> 01:51:51.111
"Based on the experience I've
gained..."

2037
01:51:56.383 --> 01:51:58.819
Listen. honestly. no way!

2038
01:52:00.555 --> 01:52:02.289
- But.
- Times have changed.

2039
01:52:02.389 --> 01:52:05.159
You're not in the running
anymore. Sorry if I'm being
cruel.

2040
01:52:05.192 --> 01:52:06.760
I'm appealing to his humanity.

2041
01:52:06.794 --> 01:52:07.861
Boris.

2042
01:52:07.895 --> 01:52:09.496
Who are you kidding?

2043
01:52:09.531 --> 01:52:11.865
"The hardship of exile?"

2044
01:52:11.899 --> 01:52:13.434
"The passage of time..."

2045
01:52:13.535 --> 01:52:15.903
"Death drawing near." I get it.

2046
01:52:17.037 --> 01:52:18.872
But I don't think it'll make him
blink.

2047
01:52:18.906 --> 01:52:22.943
The comfort of spending my final
days in our motherland.

2048
01:52:23.043 --> 01:52:25.179
You don't think he'll understand
that?

2049
01:52:31.720 --> 01:52:32.920
I have to go now.

2050
01:52:41.061 --> 01:52:42.930
Just give him the letter.
anyway.

2051
01:52:44.832 --> 01:52:46.000
I think it might cut it.

2052
01:52:47.334 --> 01:52:48.603
I genuinely do.

2053
01:52:53.742 --> 01:52:54.975
So...

2054
01:52:55.075 --> 01:52:56.076
Did it go well?

2055
01:52:56.745 --> 01:52:58.580
How could it possibly?

2056
01:52:58.613 --> 01:53:01.683
He helped you.
You could give him a hand.

2057
01:53:01.716 --> 01:53:04.719
Boris sees
the Sochi Olympics approaching.

2058
01:53:04.753 --> 01:53:07.187
There's still plenty of money
to be made.

2059
01:53:07.221 --> 01:53:09.356
even if everyone's already
lined their pockets.

2060
01:53:10.357 --> 01:53:11.959
Present company included.

2061
01:53:13.861 --> 01:53:15.496
Do you like those?

2062
01:53:15.530 --> 01:53:17.565
They're the main costumes
for the Opening Ceremony.

2063
01:53:17.599 --> 01:53:18.866
Most importantly.

2064
01:53:18.899 --> 01:53:21.703
does the British Olympic
Association like them?

2065
01:53:21.736 --> 01:53:23.203
Who cares?

2066
01:53:23.237 --> 01:53:25.205
They've already had to
swallow a Winter Olympics

2067
01:53:25.239 --> 01:53:27.207
at a balmy seaside resort.

2068
01:53:27.241 --> 01:53:30.144
Totally devoid
of athletic infrastructure.

2069
01:53:31.478 --> 01:53:32.614
Have you seen the others?

2070
01:53:34.381 --> 01:53:36.116
No. Not really. no.

2071
01:53:43.257 --> 01:53:47.294
Look. Each island represents
a period in our history.

2072
01:53:47.394 --> 01:53:50.030
They're animatronic
and float in midair.

2073
01:53:50.064 --> 01:53:53.901
Our entire literary history
will go marching by.

2074
01:53:53.934 --> 01:53:56.638
All the domes of Saint Basil's
will fly away.

2075
01:53:56.671 --> 01:53:58.906
And then... Swan Lake.

2076
01:54:02.142 --> 01:54:03.143
Like it?

2077
01:54:06.914 --> 01:54:09.316
Vadya. that Russia doesn't
exist.

2078
01:54:12.086 --> 01:54:13.287
At least not anymore.

2079
01:54:14.656 --> 01:54:17.324
But they're the ones
who inspired us back then.

2080
01:54:18.425 --> 01:54:19.527
It's too late now.

2081
01:54:21.962 --> 01:54:23.030
You know that.

2082
01:54:27.935 --> 01:54:29.303
You won't save your soul.

2083
01:54:32.172 --> 01:54:35.577
The ceremony is just a mask
for the dictatorship.

2084
01:54:35.610 --> 01:54:36.511
and the rest...

2085
01:54:36.544 --> 01:54:38.312
is just empty pretext.

2086
01:54:41.348 --> 01:54:42.684
I see through you.

2087
01:54:46.621 --> 01:54:48.222
It doesn't mean I don't love
you.

2088
01:54:50.324 --> 01:54:52.326
But I'm not gonna be
your partner in crime.

2089
01:54:59.466 --> 01:55:01.969
-Can I offer a drink?
-Champagne. please.

2090
01:55:02.069 --> 01:55:03.470
-Ma'am?
-Same.

2091
01:55:03.571 --> 01:55:04.471
Thanks.

2092
01:55:11.513 --> 01:55:13.013
The Tzar is...

2093
01:55:14.649 --> 01:55:16.651
going to free our old friend
Dmitry.

2094
01:55:19.987 --> 01:55:21.955
Are you sure?

2095
01:55:21.989 --> 01:55:23.625
It isn't the first time
you've told me that.

2096
01:55:23.725 --> 01:55:25.860
He'll do it two weeks before the
start of the Games.

2097
01:55:27.227 --> 01:55:29.496
Western media will have a field
day.

2098
01:55:29.531 --> 01:55:31.265
- <i>Your</i>
<i>attention...</i> -That's the idea.

2099
01:55:34.501 --> 01:55:37.404
<i>...flight number 068. to Paris</i>

2100
01:55:41.609 --> 01:55:44.846
<i>The flight is ready to depart.</i>
<i>passengers</i>

2101
01:55:44.879 --> 01:55:46.881
You never asked me what I did
with my day.

2102
01:55:47.916 --> 01:55:49.116
Not shopping...

2103
01:55:50.618 --> 01:55:52.052
that's not like you.

2104
01:55:52.921 --> 01:55:55.022
Something edgier.

2105
01:55:55.055 --> 01:55:56.990
Drop the sarcasm for five
minutes. will you?

2106
01:55:57.024 --> 01:55:59.159
I wasn't being sarcastic.
I was trying to guess.

2107
01:55:59.193 --> 01:56:00.562
I went to the gynecologist.

2108
01:56:06.300 --> 01:56:07.401
I'm pregnant.

2109
01:56:19.079 --> 01:56:21.549
-You look...
-I'm a little shocked. yes.

2110
01:56:26.921 --> 01:56:28.556
Actually. I'm blown away.

2111
01:56:31.091 --> 01:56:32.326
I have no words.

2112
01:56:44.606 --> 01:56:46.473
<i>According to early</i>
<i>police reports</i>

2113
01:56:46.574 --> 01:56:49.544
<i>Boris Berezovsky's death</i>
<i>is consistent with hanging.</i>

2114
01:56:49.577 --> 01:56:53.080
<i>Berezovsky was found dead last</i>
<i>night in his Ascot residence.</i>

2115
01:56:53.180 --> 01:56:55.850
<i>Pathologists have found</i>
<i>no signs of a struggle.</i>

2116
01:56:55.950 --> 01:56:58.218
<i>Access has been closed</i>
<i>until the results of the tests</i>

2117
01:56:58.252 --> 01:57:00.220
<i>for chemical. biological</i>
<i>and nuclear agents</i>

2118
01:57:00.320 --> 01:57:01.623
have been returned.

2119
01:57:07.194 --> 01:57:08.863
It had to end this
way.

2120
01:57:09.697 --> 01:57:11.498
Exile was too painful for him.

2121
01:57:13.333 --> 01:57:14.836
I'll miss him.

2122
01:57:14.869 --> 01:57:17.371
He painted an appalling image
of the opposition.

2123
01:57:17.471 --> 01:57:18.840
That was priceless for us.

2124
01:57:20.274 --> 01:57:22.777
This is the program
for the opening ceremony.

2125
01:57:24.344 --> 01:57:26.246
Updated according to your notes.

2126
01:57:33.387 --> 01:57:35.255
What is "Daft Punk"?

2127
01:57:35.355 --> 01:57:37.525
Um. electronic music.

2128
01:57:37.625 --> 01:57:39.027
Number 1 worldwide.

2129
01:57:40.360 --> 01:57:43.330
Two Frenchmen who never remove
their robot helmets.

2130
01:57:43.363 --> 01:57:45.499
This setup wasn't in the
previous draft.

2131
01:57:45.533 --> 01:57:47.769
They won 5 Grammy awards last
week.

2132
01:57:47.802 --> 01:57:49.269
We have to get up to date.

2133
01:57:49.303 --> 01:57:51.606
You've asked the police choir
to sing their song?

2134
01:57:52.941 --> 01:57:55.342
Vladimirovich. he's turning
the whole ceremony into a farce.

2135
01:57:56.644 --> 01:57:57.645
Okay.

2136
01:57:58.513 --> 01:58:00.247
Explain your rationale to Igor.

2137
01:58:01.516 --> 01:58:04.018
Today it's what people want to
dance to.

2138
01:58:04.052 --> 01:58:05.720
-It's that simple.
-It'll be ridiculous.

2139
01:58:05.753 --> 01:58:07.855
No. it'll be kitsch.

2140
01:58:07.889 --> 01:58:10.658
The entire world.
three billion spectators

2141
01:58:10.758 --> 01:58:13.160
are waiting for the greatest
show they've ever seen.

2142
01:58:13.193 --> 01:58:15.763
It can only be
the apotheosis of kitsch.

2143
01:58:17.397 --> 01:58:20.668
Kitsch is the only language
available to us

2144
01:58:20.768 --> 01:58:23.437
if we are to communicate
with the masses.

2145
01:58:23.538 --> 01:58:26.808
-We want to show them our
Russia. -They don't want to see
your Russia.

2146
01:58:26.841 --> 01:58:30.477
Besides. you have nothing to
show and everything to hide.

2147
01:58:31.045 --> 01:58:34.181
We want to paint the picture
of an open Russia.

2148
01:58:34.214 --> 01:58:37.585
Sure-footed.
but also capable of smiling.

2149
01:58:37.685 --> 01:58:40.153
Today's world requires
self-deprecation.

2150
01:58:40.187 --> 01:58:43.091
Not your balalaikas. Igor.

2151
01:58:43.190 --> 01:58:46.193
Do you understand what I'm
saying or is it gibberish to
you?

2152
01:58:47.461 --> 01:58:49.564
What can you do. hm?

2153
01:58:50.565 --> 01:58:54.201
Vadya is an acrobat.

2154
01:58:54.234 --> 01:58:57.705
An artist for politicians.
a politician for artists.

2155
01:58:57.739 --> 01:58:59.339
Be careful. Vadya.

2156
01:58:59.439 --> 01:59:01.709
Sooner or later
you might miss the trapeze.

2157
01:59:02.577 --> 01:59:04.512
Fall flat on your face.

2158
01:59:08.215 --> 01:59:14.989
I declare the 22nd Winter
Olympic Games of Sochi open.

2159
01:59:17.825 --> 01:59:20.061
<i>That was probably</i>
<i>the night I should have left.</i>

2160
01:59:20.094 --> 01:59:23.330
<i>Closed the book at that page.</i>
<i>It was a good ending for me.</i>

2161
01:59:37.512 --> 01:59:39.246
<i>The Ukrainian</i>
<i>independence movement</i>

2162
01:59:39.279 --> 01:59:42.750
<i>seized on the Olympic ceasefire</i>
<i>to occupy Maidan Square again</i>

2163
01:59:44.919 --> 01:59:46.888
<i>Two days before the end of the</i>
<i>Games</i>

2164
01:59:46.988 --> 01:59:49.590
<i>they ousted pro-Russian</i>
<i>President Yanukovych.</i>

2165
01:59:49.624 --> 01:59:50.958
<i>who fled the same day.</i>

2166
01:59:52.359 --> 01:59:54.095
<i>The chaos that ensued</i>
<i>gave the Tzar</i>

2167
01:59:54.128 --> 01:59:56.631
<i>a golden opportunity</i>
<i>to invade Ukraine.</i>

2168
02:00:00.300 --> 02:00:02.804
Russian snipers killed
over a hundred protesters.

2169
02:00:03.938 --> 02:00:05.505
They say you were in charge.

2170
02:00:07.675 --> 02:00:08.910
Who says?

2171
02:00:09.010 --> 02:00:10.011
Ukrainians.

2172
02:00:11.278 --> 02:00:12.547
From your own emails.

2173
02:00:14.148 --> 02:00:16.316
They say you have Ukrainian
blood on your hands.

2174
02:00:25.459 --> 02:00:27.929
The night before the closing
ceremony

2175
02:00:27.962 --> 02:00:29.664
following his grand plan.

2176
02:00:30.665 --> 02:00:32.900
the Tzar decided to annex
Crimea.

2177
02:00:35.169 --> 02:00:37.572
Crimea was part of Ukraine.

2178
02:00:38.973 --> 02:00:40.708
We weren't about to send regular
troops

2179
02:00:40.808 --> 02:00:42.677
to invade a sovereign country.

2180
02:00:42.710 --> 02:00:43.678
No.

2181
02:00:44.478 --> 02:00:46.313
You sent in Russian soldiers

2182
02:00:46.346 --> 02:00:48.950
who weren't wearing any national
insignia.

2183
02:00:49.050 --> 02:00:50.585
"Little green men".

2184
02:00:50.685 --> 02:00:52.687
as your fellow journalists used
to say.

2185
02:01:03.197 --> 02:01:05.733
Can I bother you for a moment.
Vadim Alexeyevich?

2186
02:01:05.833 --> 02:01:06.934
Go right ahead.

2187
02:01:09.003 --> 02:01:11.706
How did your trip to Lugansk go?
Well?

2188
02:01:11.739 --> 02:01:14.075
I'm sure you've read
your services' reports.

2189
02:01:16.343 --> 02:01:18.345
We have news from the Americans.

2190
02:01:19.213 --> 02:01:20.248
What news?

2191
02:01:20.347 --> 02:01:21.983
Seems they've drawn up a
blacklist

2192
02:01:22.016 --> 02:01:23.851
of people forbidden on their
soil.

2193
02:01:24.852 --> 02:01:27.420
Your name is on it.

2194
02:01:27.454 --> 02:01:30.191
I've got a feeling you'll have
to forget about going to New
York for a while.

2195
02:01:30.224 --> 02:01:31.259
Oh.

2196
02:01:31.358 --> 02:01:33.326
Their sanctions for the takeover
of Crimea.

2197
02:01:33.360 --> 02:01:34.595
When do they start?

2198
02:01:34.629 --> 02:01:35.630
This Monday.

2199
02:01:37.031 --> 02:01:39.901
It's good thing I stopped liking
New York a long time ago.

2200
02:01:40.868 --> 02:01:42.737
I've heard something else. too.

2201
02:01:45.606 --> 02:01:46.473
Go on.

2202
02:01:47.275 --> 02:01:49.076
It'll be official tomorrow.

2203
02:01:49.110 --> 02:01:53.114
Your name is also
on the Europeans' shortlist.

2204
02:01:54.248 --> 02:01:55.516
Paris.

2205
02:01:55.616 --> 02:01:57.018
London.

2206
02:01:57.051 --> 02:01:57.985
no more.

2207
02:01:59.153 --> 02:02:00.487
I'm told you'll miss Naples.

2208
02:02:02.990 --> 02:02:06.393
Well. I won't bother you
any longer. Vadim Alexeyevich.

2209
02:02:07.895 --> 02:02:09.797
I'm sure you have arrangements
to make.

2210
02:02:10.397 --> 02:02:11.398
And fast.

2211
02:02:53.808 --> 02:02:55.776
- <i>Sir?</i>
- Lionia. have you heard?

2212
02:02:55.810 --> 02:02:56.777
<i>Yes.</i>

2213
02:02:56.811 --> 02:02:59.013
Yes. tonight
or tomorrow at the latest.

2214
02:02:59.046 --> 02:03:00.047
<i>Interview?</i>

2215
02:03:00.081 --> 02:03:02.516
No. no interviews.
just a press release.

2216
02:03:02.550 --> 02:03:04.151
Can you take this down?

2217
02:03:04.185 --> 02:03:05.686
<i>Yes.</i>

2218
02:03:06.453 --> 02:03:08.589
"I see this sanction as an Oscar

2219
02:03:08.623 --> 02:03:11.125
"awarded for my entire political
career.

2220
02:03:12.126 --> 02:03:14.228
"It means I have served
my country honorably."

2221
02:03:14.328 --> 02:03:15.229
Full stop.

2222
02:03:15.963 --> 02:03:18.032
- <i>Any thing</i>
<i>else?</i> -No. that's all.

2223
02:03:18.065 --> 02:03:19.133
Thank you.

2224
02:03:54.101 --> 02:03:55.269
Ksenia?

2225
02:03:55.369 --> 02:03:56.370
{Ksenia on phone] <i>Yes.</i>

2226
02:03:56.537 --> 02:03:59.106
Pack your bags.
I'll be over in 15 minutes.

2227
02:04:01.609 --> 02:04:04.245
<i>A few hours later</i>
<i>we landed in Stockholm</i>

2228
02:04:04.278 --> 02:04:06.479
<i>for our last European weekend.</i>

2229
02:04:49.557 --> 02:04:51.559
I suppose it was bound
to happen.

2230
02:04:53.060 --> 02:04:55.062
Only you could avoid it.

2231
02:04:55.096 --> 02:04:56.397
By resigning.

2232
02:04:56.430 --> 02:04:57.565
For instance.

2233
02:05:00.167 --> 02:05:04.205
Power is addictive.
It's a tough habit to kick.

2234
02:05:04.238 --> 02:05:06.540
Before. when you spouted
that kind of truism.

2235
02:05:06.574 --> 02:05:07.742
I could hear the irony.

2236
02:05:09.176 --> 02:05:10.211
Not anymore.

2237
02:05:10.311 --> 02:05:11.312
There was none.

2238
02:05:12.246 --> 02:05:13.948
The war in Ukraine is like the
rest.

2239
02:05:15.116 --> 02:05:17.818
I never wanted it.
I even opposed it.

2240
02:05:17.852 --> 02:05:19.053
If you say so.

2241
02:05:19.086 --> 02:05:20.254
Indeed.

2242
02:05:20.855 --> 02:05:22.089
I do say so.

2243
02:05:23.090 --> 02:05:25.960
And I also say that once the
Tzar had made up his mind.

2244
02:05:26.994 --> 02:05:29.864
I did everything I could
to see it succeed.

2245
02:05:29.964 --> 02:05:31.132
Out of habit.

2246
02:05:32.666 --> 02:05:33.834
Out of pride.

2247
02:05:35.102 --> 02:05:36.070
And because I could.

2248
02:05:36.103 --> 02:05:37.605
With no compunction.

2249
02:05:37.705 --> 02:05:39.106
That's true.

2250
02:05:39.140 --> 02:05:40.608
That's how it's always been.

2251
02:05:41.709 --> 02:05:45.980
With the Moscow bombings
and the war in Chechnya.

2252
02:05:46.013 --> 02:05:48.582
With Dmitry's arrest
and Berezovsky's fall.

2253
02:05:48.616 --> 02:05:51.719
And now the murders on the
Maidan.

2254
02:05:53.020 --> 02:05:55.524
I never wanted any of those
things. yet...

2255
02:05:55.623 --> 02:05:58.125
each depended on my tireless
labor.

2256
02:05:58.726 --> 02:05:59.994
And now you're tired.

2257
02:06:00.861 --> 02:06:02.997
Russia devoured my grandfather.

2258
02:06:04.865 --> 02:06:07.234
You met my father.
it devoured him too.

2259
02:06:08.537 --> 02:06:11.105
I don't know about me.
I don't know if I'll be saved.

2260
02:06:11.138 --> 02:06:12.406
Probably not.

2261
02:06:14.141 --> 02:06:16.243
In any case. it's too late.

2262
02:06:19.647 --> 02:06:21.516
But our child will be saved.

2263
02:06:45.406 --> 02:06:46.407
Ksenia?

2264
02:06:50.044 --> 02:06:51.078
Ksenia!

2265
02:06:56.717 --> 02:06:58.152
Ksenia!

2266
02:07:10.364 --> 02:07:13.300
Ksenia!

2267
02:07:34.722 --> 02:07:37.958
<i>Going to Novo-Ogaryovo</i>
<i>was never much of a thrill.</i>

2268
02:07:37.992 --> 02:07:40.294
<i>The bleak. sporty mood pained</i>
<i>me.</i>

2269
02:07:40.327 --> 02:07:42.062
<i>After I got back from Stockholm</i>

2270
02:07:42.096 --> 02:07:44.465
<i>I almost never set foot there</i>
<i>again.</i>

2271
02:07:44.498 --> 02:07:47.868
<i>A prince's trust is not a</i>
<i>privilege. but a conviction.</i>

2272
02:07:48.736 --> 02:07:52.006
<i>I had played my part.</i>
<i>I was no longer of any use.</i>

2273
02:07:52.740 --> 02:07:55.809
<i>At some point. I let him get</i>
<i>out of the habit of seeing me.</i>

2274
02:07:55.843 --> 02:07:57.111
<i>That's all.</i>

2275
02:07:58.345 --> 02:08:00.515
<i>He gets up early</i>
<i>and breakfasts on fresh eggs</i>

2276
02:08:00.615 --> 02:08:03.250
<i>sent by Patriarch Kirill from</i>
<i>his farm.</i>

2277
02:08:03.350 --> 02:08:06.253
<i>If there's an emergency. that's</i>
<i>when he reads his confidential</i>
<i>notes</i>

2278
02:08:06.287 --> 02:08:07.589
<i>and makes his wishes known.</i>

2279
02:08:08.989 --> 02:08:10.758
<i>Next. he swims a</i>
<i>kilometer.</i>

2280
02:08:11.792 --> 02:08:14.228
<i>His first visitors wait</i>
<i>by the pool.</i>

2281
02:08:14.261 --> 02:08:17.765
<i>Ministers. advisors. CEOs.</i>

2282
02:08:17.798 --> 02:08:19.601
<i>The presidential motorcade only</i>
<i>leaves</i>

2283
02:08:19.634 --> 02:08:21.435
<i>for the Kremlin in the early</i>
<i>afternoon.</i>

2284
02:08:22.604 --> 02:08:24.838
<i>The streets are closed</i>
<i>half an hour prior.</i>

2285
02:08:24.872 --> 02:08:27.542
<i>Putin drives from Novo-Ogaryovo</i>
<i>to the Kremlin</i>

2286
02:08:27.642 --> 02:08:29.276
<i>through his frozen capital.</i>

2287
02:08:30.010 --> 02:08:31.879
<i>And his real day begins.</i>

2288
02:08:33.314 --> 02:08:35.684
<i>Sometimes only ending at dawn.</i>

2289
02:08:38.786 --> 02:08:40.555
One man stays awake

2290
02:08:41.956 --> 02:08:45.292
while everyone else who matters
in Moscow shares his vigil.

2291
02:08:46.393 --> 02:08:47.861
Like in Stalin's day.

2292
02:08:50.464 --> 02:08:53.267
Who's that? Who's this?

2293
02:08:53.300 --> 02:08:54.501
Oh.

2294
02:08:54.536 --> 02:08:56.036
Hi. my sweet one.

2295
02:08:57.404 --> 02:08:59.173
Can I play with Machka?

2296
02:08:59.206 --> 02:09:01.408
Of course you can.
You're not bothering us.

2297
02:09:02.577 --> 02:09:04.211
Where is she?

2298
02:09:04.311 --> 02:09:06.046
Where's that Machka?

2299
02:09:06.080 --> 02:09:07.448
- Is she under the table?
- No.

2300
02:09:07.481 --> 02:09:09.016
-She's not under the table?
-No.

2301
02:09:09.049 --> 02:09:10.184
- Is she under the
cushion?

2302
02:09:10.217 --> 02:09:11.452
- No.
- Are you sure?

2303
02:09:11.553 --> 02:09:13.287
- No.
- Is she under the piano?

2304
02:09:13.320 --> 02:09:14.556
-No.
-No.

2305
02:09:15.590 --> 02:09:17.559
- There.
- There she is.

2306
02:09:18.225 --> 02:09:20.227
<i>There she is.</i>

2307
02:09:27.935 --> 02:09:31.338
All the happiness I've known in
the world is concentrated in
her.

2308
02:09:32.206 --> 02:09:33.340
Daddy.

2309
02:09:33.440 --> 02:09:36.343
what do you think Machka would
say if she could talk?

2310
02:09:36.377 --> 02:09:38.580
Hm. I think she'd say.

2311
02:09:38.613 --> 02:09:40.582
"I'd have more fun with a real
rabbit."

2312
02:09:40.615 --> 02:09:41.716
Daddy!

2313
02:09:41.750 --> 02:09:46.353
No. no. no. She'd say.
"I like you best of all. Anya.

2314
02:09:46.453 --> 02:09:48.355
"I only want to play with you."

2315
02:09:50.525 --> 02:09:51.859
Cats aren't my favorite thing.

2316
02:09:51.959 --> 02:09:55.029
But how much longer will I be
able to make her happy?

2317
02:09:56.230 --> 02:09:58.866
I never felt fear before Anya.

2318
02:09:58.966 --> 02:10:00.834
From the moment I first laid
eyes on her.

2319
02:10:00.868 --> 02:10:02.436
I've been living in terror.

2320
02:10:02.469 --> 02:10:04.238
I realize my life is in her
hands.

2321
02:10:04.271 --> 02:10:05.607
not the other way around.

2322
02:10:06.641 --> 02:10:08.876
My daughter doesn't count
the hours or the days.

2323
02:10:10.277 --> 02:10:11.879
I've always lived in the future.

2324
02:10:14.749 --> 02:10:16.250
And she has given me the
present.
